<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NewtsInLove     09-09 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newts In Love,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0876 to fix numbering</HEAD>
<HEAD>Park Officials Go to Rescue of Lovestruck Newts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No newts is bad news, park officials say.
   In an outpouring of compassion for a burdened creature that
lives under rocks and eats bugs and worms, the East Bay Regional
Park District is, for the sake of love, about to lend a hand _ or,
at least, a right of way.
   The 4-inch-long tailed amphibians die by the hundreds under the
wheels of vehicles when the newts cross the main road in Tilden
Park during the fall to mate, district spokesman Ned Mackay said
this week.
   With their weak legs, salamanders are not equipped to scoot
across roads dodging cars, he said. The only answer is to
occasionally reserve the road as a freeway for newts, he said.
   The agency is officially devoted to the little lizards,
conducting seasonal ``newt walks'' to allow citizens to ogle the
critters when they emerge from their summer havens and head for the
marshes to make more newts.
   To better protect them, the district announced that Tilden Park
will periodically close the roads after heavy rains, probably
during evening hours, when hordes of the newts make their
love-driven treks.
   Signs are to be posted on a one-mile stretch of the main drive
that warn motorists of closures, said Mackay.
   Less drastic measures to save the newts from slaughter have been
tried, to no avail. In 1975, four signs were posted that said,
``Caution, Newts Xing,'' together with a larger-than-life portrait
of a newt.
   Within a week, tickled visitors had stolen every one.
</TEXT>
