<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     09-09 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chile Leads Surge in Fresh Fruit Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imports of grapes, apples and other items are
growing rapidly to help satisfy a growing American appetite for
fresh fruit, Agriculture Department analysts say.
   Last year, for example, total fresh fruit imports jumped 20
percent to 1.2 million metric tons from 996,000 in 1986, says a
report by the department's Economic Research Service.
   This year's drought also is expected to help boost U.S. demand
for some items, thus adding to the growth in fruit imports. A shift
in exchange rates and demographic factors also has had an effect.
   Grapes made up 21 percent of the fresh fruit imports last year,
with most coming from Chile. Apples accounted for 12 percent of the
total, mostly divided among Canada, Chile and New Zealand.
   The report said the U.S. dollar has been declining against
European currency, the Japanese yen and the Canadian dollar since
1985, but it has risen against the currencies of many major U.S.
agricultural trading partners.
   ``As a result, products from these countries are very
competitive in the U.S. market,'' the report said. ``Relative
production costs abroad, particularly in South America and Mexico,
where many fruits are grown, make these countries relatively more
competitive in the U.S. market.''
   Demographic changes also have favored the rise in fruit imports,
the report said. A growth in the number of women in the nation's
work force, for example, has led to greater demand for convenience
food.
   ``Growth in major ethnic groups is impacting food demand in the
United States,'' the report said. ``Generally, the diets of these
groups have a higher proportion and wider variety of fruits than
the typical American diet.''
   The report added: ``Also, within the United States, knowledge of
and concern for health and nutrition have increased in the past 10
years, leading to increased consumption of fresh fruits.''
   Chile has passed South Africa, Australia and Argentina to become
the leading supplier of fresh fruit to North America and Europe
during the winter months.
   ``Because Chile's grapes come into season during the U.S. winter
months, grapes are now available year round to the U.S. market,''
the report said.
   Apples are also a major Chilean export, and these compete with
the U.S. domestic crop. In 1983, imports of Chilean apples totaled
14,780 metric tons. Last year, those totaled 43,020 tons. Another
growing import are Chilean pears, up from 4,216 tons in 1983 to
14,797 tons last year.
   Exports of fresh fruit by the United States have run ahead of
imports, but the gap is narrowing.
   In 1986, exports totaled 1.36 million tons, compared with
imports of 996,000. Last year, exports at 1.5 million tons compared
with 1.2 million tons of imports.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department personnel specialist
says there are about 2,000 different kinds of jobs in the
department held by 122,900 employees, including 35 farmers.
   Brad Foote of the USDA office of personnel, says the 122,900
employees include all full-time, part-time and temporary workers
located throughout the United States and in foreign agricultural
posts.
   Foote described the department's job situation in USDA News, a
monthly newsletter for employees.
   The job list includes more than 14,500 forestry technicians,
6,000 clerk-typists, 4,900 soil conservationists, 3,500
secretaries, 3,100 biological technicians and 1,300 accounting
technicians.
   Also, he said, the department has a number of ``rather out of
the ordinary'' positions, such as six model makers, whose jobs are
to develop prototype models for use in research and scientific
experiments.
   Foote said others include four tree trimmers, four industrial
hygienists, three aircraft mechanics, two boat operators and one
sewing machine operator.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Videotapes and VCRs are becoming part of the
Agriculture Department's public educational packages.
   The latest is a 15-minute tape designed to show farmers, rural
firefighters, pesticide applicators and farm supply store employees
how to safely handle and transport chemical pesticides in
concentrated form.
   Martin Fitzpatrick, head of the department's office of
transportation, says farmers and commercial applicators carried
about 640 million pounds of pesticides over the nation's roads last
year.
   ``But until now there has been limited educational information
on the safe transport of these materials,'' he said.
   The tape, titled ``Be Prepared _ Just in Case,'' was produced in
cooperation with South States Cooperative Inc. of Richmond, Va.
   Copies of the video, in VHS or Beta format, can be ordered for
$9 plus $2.75 for mailing and handling from Commonwealth Films,
1500 Brook Road, Richmond, Va. 23200. Phone (804) 649-8611.
</TEXT>
