<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Cavazos-Hearing     09-09 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cavazos-Hearing,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cavazos Seen Facing Little Opposition for Education Secretary Post</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Hearing begins at 10 a.m. EDT; will be topped</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional officials say Texas Tech
University President Lauro F. Cavazos should have no trouble
winning Senate confirmation as the next education secretary, which
would make him the first Hispanic ever appointed to the Cabinet.
   The Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee was scheduled to
take up Cavazos' nomination today.
   ``I don't think it's going to be controversial at all,'' said
Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who will introduce Cavazos. ``You're
talking about the dean of a major medical school, the president of
a great university who has served this nation on numerous boards
and commissions around the world. He is clearly loved by everbody
that knows him. This (confirmation) is a certainty.''
   A Senate education subcommittee staff member added: ``I don't
anticipate he'll have any trouble. There's a very good chance it
will be unanimous.''
   The aide, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said a
strong committee vote likely would herald a quick and easy
confirmation in the full Senate, possibly next week.
   President Reagan announced in August he was nominating Cavazos,
the 61-year-old son of a foreman at the fabled King Ranch in Texas,
to replace outgoing Education Secretary William J. Bennett, who
leaves office later this month.
   Cavazos would serve only until January when the next
administration takes over, unless the new president reappoints him
to the post.
   He is the first Hispanic to serve as president of Texas Tech. He
also serves as the president of its medical school, but is not a
medical doctor.
   A registered Democrat, Cavazos has opposed cuts in student
financial aid. He is described as a skilled administrator, a
delegator and a consensus-builder.
   ``His leadership in education on a nationwide basis is well
known,'' Gramm said.
   Known informally as Larry, Cavazos is one of three brothers who
left the King Ranch to attend what was then Texas Technological
College.
   His brother, Bobby, was an All-American running back in football
who now has his own ranch, while Dick became a four-star Army
general.
   Cavazos earned a bachelor's degree in zoology and a master's
degree in cytology _ the study of cells _ at Texas Tech before
receiving his doctorate in physiology from Iowa State University in
1954.
   He became the first Texas Tech graduate to be appointed the
university's president with his selection in 1980.
   Seven of his 10 children have Texas Tech degrees.
</TEXT>
