<DOCNO> AP880909-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MinimumWage     09-09 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minimum Wage,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Assess Strategy on Minimum Wage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats say they will try to move a minimum
wage increase through Congress this year, but the issue is being
complicated by presidential politics.
   Members of the House and Senate who handle labor legislation met
Thursday and agreed to try for final passage of the legislation
before Congress adjourns for the year next month.
   But it was also clear that differences between Democrats and
Republicans could doom the bill. The Reagan administration has
steadfastly opposed boosting the wage base, which has stood at
$3.35 an hour since 1981.
   George Bush, the Republican presidential nominee, told
Knight-Ridder newspapers Wednesday that he would soon propose
``some adjustment'' in the minimum wage. Bush's new position
represents an attempt to gain support from blue-collar voters and
came shortly after a campaign appearance at which he was booed
repeatedly by shipyard workers in Oregon.
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the Senate Labor
Committee, noted the political implications on Wednesday.
   ``We've been battling on these issues for the last seven years,
and it's fair to say: Where was George when we carried those
measures in the full committee or the subcommittee? There's been
absolute silence,'' he said.
   The Democratic-controlled Congress has been poised for weeks to
consider legislation that would raise the minimum wage to $4.55 an
hour by 1991 in a Senate bill and to $5.05 hourly by 1992 under a
House measure.
   In an effort to pass the proposal by the time Congress adjourns
next month, House Democratic leaders have agreed to accept the
lower Senate figure. On Thursday, Kennedy, House Labor Committee
Chairman Augustus F. Hawkins and others met and agreed to try to
move the bill quickly.
   The measure, however, faces the threat of a veto by President
Reagan.
   In addition, Republicans are ready to introduce amendments that
many Democrats oppose.
   Chief among them is a proposal for a ``training wage'' lower
than the minimum wage, that businesses would be allowed to pay new
workers. In the Knight-Ridder interview, Bush indicated support for
a training wage.
   Republicans say the training wage, which could be paid to each
worker for only a few months, would create extra jobs. But
Democratic opponents say the provision would be a loophole that
would allow companies to pay less money to millions of workers
while not guaranteeing that any of them actually receive training.
   Democratic aides say such a proposal might pass, but would doom
the overall bill because liberals bitterly oppose the training wage
and would vote against a final package that contains it.
   Hawkins, D-Calif., said he considered the training wage proposal
to be a ``killer amendment,'' and said he would pull the bill from
the House floor if the amendment was passed.
   ``I'd disown it myself,'' he said.
   Removing the bill from consideration, however, would allow Bush
to contrast his newfound support for a minimum wage boost with a
Democratic decision to postpone consideration of such an increase
until at least next year.
   Rep. Thomas E. Petri of Wisconsin, ranking Republican on the
labor standards subcommittee, which oversees the minimum wage, said
he did not know what minimum wage changes Bush favors.
   ``I hope when the vice president spells out the changes he has
in mind, we'll have a chance to vote on them on the floor,'' he
said.
   Petri and Sen. Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn., have introduced bills
that would expand the earned income tax credit to which poor
working families are entitled. They say that such a change would
help low-income workers more efficiently than a minimum wage
increase, which they say would have more of an impact on workers in
the middle class.
   Currently, low-income workers are allowed tax credits of up to
$874, a break that Petri and Boschwitz would expand by for the
first time increasing it according to the size of workers' families.
   Republican vice presidential nominee Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind.,
has been an ardent opponent of Democratic attempts to raise the
minimum wage.
   But he _ along with Petri and many other Republican lawmakers _
support a different formula that would raise the minimum wage to $4
hourly, institute a training wage and increase the earned income
tax credit. It is unclear if this is the idea Bush favors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
