<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-AirShow     09-09 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Air Show,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0886 to fix numbering</HEAD>
<HEAD>Spanish Air Force Decides To Hold Air Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Ministry has decided to go
ahead with an air show featuring Spanish, British and French
stunt-flying teams, despite protests about safety stemming from a
recent air show disaster in West Germany.
   The Italian team involved in the Aug. 28 crash that killed 56
people will fly once over the Sept. 19 show, but it will not
perform, air force spokesman Col. Juan Antonio Martinez-Ortiz said
Thursday.
   Martinez-Ortiz said authorities had adopted new safety
regulations for the show, planned as part of inauguration
ceremonies for an air force combat wing of U.S.-built F-18A
fighters at an air base in the city of Zaragoza.
   Hipolito Gomez, head of the autonomous government of the
northern region of Aragon, criticized the ministry's decision and
said it showed ``disdain for the people of Aragon.'' Zaragoza is
the capital of Aragon.
   Gomez, a conservative, asked the government of Socialist Prime
Minister Felipe Gonzalez to cancel the air show because he feared
for spectators' safety.
   The new Spanish regulations, similar to those adopted at a
recent air show in Farnborough, England, prohibit the teams from
flying toward spectators, Martinez-Ortiz said.
   ``The spectators will be on one side of the runway and the
maneuvers will take place on the other side,'' he said.
   At the Aug. 28 show at the U.S. Air Force Base in Ramstein,
three Italian jets collided while performing a stunt, and one
crashed into a crowd of spectators and blew up.
</TEXT>
