<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Nigeria-Roads,0132</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0892 to fix numbering</HEAD>
<HEAD>Road Accidents Kill 66 Daily</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nigerians stand a 1-in-9 chance of being
killed in road accidents, which claim 66 lives each day in Nigeria,
according to a report by a commission headed by Nobel laureate Wole
Soyinka.
   The report, released Thursday, said 79,000 people have been
killed in road accidents since 1980 in what the commission
described as ``carnage and national tragedy.''
   Since independence from Britain in 1960, a total of 154,667
traffic deaths and more than 550,000 injuries have been reported in
this country of about 103 million people.
   The accident rate has increased steadily in recent years, the
report added.
   Soyinka, a playwright, poet and novelist, received the Nobel
Prize for literature in 1986.
</TEXT>
