<2ND_LINE>PM-Prosecutor's Dress,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0895 to fix numbering</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Files Sex Complaint Over Short Skirt, `Bimbo' Remarks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman prosecutor who says her
boss claims she looks, talks and dresses like a ``bimbo'' has filed
a sex harassment complaint.
   Brenda Taylor, 25, said Wednesday she was in danger of losing
her job at the Broward state attorney's office because her male
superiors found her designer dresses too provocative.
   The complaint filed last week with the Broward Human Relations
Commission contains a list of grievances against her supervisor,
assistant state attorney John Countryman.
   The complaint accuses him of telling Ms. Taylor she looks and
talks like a ``bimbo,'' and that her skirts are too short, giving
her the appearance of a ``manhunter.'' He also said her style of
dress ``excites'' defense attorneys, the complaint says.
   Countryman's superior, Ralph Ray, refused to discuss the
complaint.
   Ms. Taylor, who was hired in January and is still on probation,
said Countryman wanted her to wear blue or gray suits with bow
ties, typical ``dress-for-success'' women's wear, she said.
   She said he threatened to keep her on probation indefinitely.
   ``I dress in a way I find comfortable,'' said Ms. Taylor. ``I
don't think long blue skirts, jackets and bow ties look right on
me.''
   None of the judges or attorneys she has worked with has
complained, she said. The only letter in her file on the subject
came from a courthouse secretary who reported that two elderly
visitors whispered about Ms. Taylor's short, tight skirt.
   Ms. Taylor said she intended to continue her career no matter
what happens with her $22,000-a-year job.
   ``I just want to be a good lawyer,'' she said. ``I'm not going
to change the way I dress because I haven't done anything.''
</TEXT>
