<HEAD>Officials Investigate Malady That Has Claimed 300 Lives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health workers are trying to identify an
illness that has claimed more than 300 lives in northern Nigeria, a
newspaper reported.
   The independent Lagos Guardian, quoting local officials, said
the deaths were reported in Kano state, and the government had
dismissed malaria or malnutrition as the possible cause.
   Most of the deaths occurred after an illness of no more than 48
hours, the newspaper reported Thursday.
   A team was in the area taking blood samples to try to identify
the illness, the Guardian said.
   Nigeria, Africa's most populous nation, suffers from many
water-borne diseases such as cholera because of inadequate safe
water supplies. The government warned of an expected outbreak of
such diseases following recent heavy rains.
