<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GermanEmigres     09-09 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-German Emigres,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exit Visas For Ethnic Germans Increased In 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government issued exit visas this year to
15,715 ethnic Germans, a sharp increase over previous levels, a
spokesman announced.
   Spokesman Vadim Perfiliev told reporters Thursday that the
figure covers the first seven months of 1988 and includes 844
children. He said 7,000 applications are now being processed.
   This year's figure is 150 percent higher than last year's,
Perfiliev said.
   He said 142 requests for visas were denied in the first seven
months of 1988 on the grounds that the applications included
falsified information, either about relatives in West Germany or
about applicants themselves.
   The Soviet Union has about 1.6 million citizens of German
extraction, most of them in western parts of the country. During
various periods in Russian history, Germans were invited to serve
as technicians in various areas. Many established wealthy
agricultural colonies and maintained their ethnic identities.
   Before World War II, ethnic Germans living in the Middle Volga
area had their own autonomous region, but during the war their
republic was abrogated and they were moved eastward into Siberia
and Middle Asia.
</TEXT>
