<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0449EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Seabrook-License     09-09 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seabrook-License,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC Expected To Vote Next Week on Seabrook Obstacle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nuclear Regulatory Commission vote next week
is likely to remove a major hurdle in the long quest by operators
of the Seabrook, N.H., nuclear power plant to obtain a low-power
operating license.
   None of the commissioners objected to the proposed rules change
at a staff briefing Thursday, and NRC Chairman Lando W. Zech Jr.
said afterwards that he likely would take the staff's
recommendation and support it. A vote is scheduled for next Friday.
   The proposal would allow Seabrook to receive a license to
conduct tests at 5 percent power capacity without having a system
in place to notify residents within 10 miles of the reactor of an
accident.
   ``It is highly unlikely that members of the general public would
be exposed to dangerous levels of radiation following an accident
at low power,'' the staff said in a 23-page report to the
commissioners.
   The rule, if adopted, would allow the commission to reverse a
February ruling by the Atomic Safety and Licensing Appeal Board
that blocked a low-power license after sirens were removed from the
Massachusetts municipalities within the plant's 10-mile zone.
   New Hampshire Yankee, the plant's operator, was forced to remove
the sirens after a federal appeals court sided with state and local
officials. Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and other plant
opponents wanted the sirens removed because they believe no
evacuation system can adequately protect nearby residents.
   Under the new rule, New Hampshire Yankee still would need a
notification system for a full-power license. The company has
suggested truck-mounted sirens and siren-equipped helicopters as
replacements.
   Massachusetts Attorney General James Shannon said in a telephone
interview Thursday that the state probably would not try to block
the rule change in court, but instead challenge the actual license
if it is eventually issued.
   After the siren issue, the only other low-power question pending
before the commission is an appeal by Seabrook critics that the
reactor's bleak financial condition should block issuance of the
permit.
   It is unclear when that issue will be decided and whether it
will hold up the oft-delayed license, said Martin G. Malsch, deputy
general counsel for licensing and regulation at the commission.
   Zech declined to comment on the potential impact of the
financial qualification question.
   ``We're taking one step at a time with Seabrook,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
