<DOCNO> AP880909-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AirlineScorecard     09-09 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airline Scorecard,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poor Weather Hampers Airline Arrivals in Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About four of every five flights by major U.S.
airlines arrived on time in July, although poor weather held down
the on-time performance in the heavily traveled air corridors of
the Northeast, according to Transportation Department figures.
   Two carriers serving the Sun Belt _ America West and Southwest
Airlines _ reported better than 91 percent of their flights on time
during July. Airports in Salt Lake City, Phoenix and Las Vegas had
the best arrival rates.
   The monthly statistics were released by the department Thursday.
   Pan American World Airways had the worst arrival record among
the 13 airlines monitored, with only 68.8 percent of its July
flights arriving within 15 minutes of schedule, the government's
on-time standard. The department provided more recent figures for
consumer complaints, showing that Pan Am also had the highest rate
in that category in August.
   Overall, 81.5 percent of the more than 441,000 flights during
July arrived within 15 minutes of schedule, slightly fewer than the
84.3 percent during June.
   The figures do not include delays caused by mechanical problems,
but do include those that are due to poor weather. Airlines that
have a concentration of flights in the Southwest have consistently
performed well, as did airports in that part of the country.
   On the other hand, airports in the Northeast where weather as
well as heavy air traffic contributed to delays were generally at
the bottom of the on-time list, as were some of the air carriers
that serve that region.
   The three New York City area airports _ LaGuardia, John F.
Kennedy and Newark International _ as well as Philadelphia had the
worst arrival rate, with about one-third of their flights delayed.
Boston and Pittsburgh, where a runway repair project also added to
delays, also fared badly.
   The Transportation Department began monitoring airline arrival
rates last September amid growing complaints about flight delays
and poor service.
   Delta Air Lines, which earlier this year struggled well down the
list in on-time performance among the 13 carriers, posted the third
best arrival rate in July with 86.1 percent of its flights on time.
   In addition to Pan Am, the airlines with the worst record were
Piedmont Airlines and USAir, both of which reported arrival rates
of slightly better than 74 percent.
   David Shipley, a USAir spokesman, blamed the poor showing on the
runway problem at Pittsburgh, where USAir has its major hub, as
well as weather problems. He said 10 percent of USAir's total
arrival delays were linked to the runway being closed.
   Salt Lake City had the best arrival rate of the 27 airports
monitored, with 92.3 percent of its flights arriving on time. The
other two airports with arrival rates of better than 90 percent
were Phoenix and Las Vegas, Nev.
   Meanwhile, complaints from air travelers to the Transportation
Department's office of consumer affairs continued to decline
compared with 1987, as they have steadily during the year.
   During August, the department received 2,363 complaints from air
travelers, two-thirds fewer than the 7,337 received during the same
month a year ago.
   Pan Am had the worst record, with 17.14 complaints for every
100,000 passengers flown, followed by Hawaiian Airlines, with 13.18
and TWA with 10.75.
   Continental Airlines and Northwest Airlines, which during most
of the past year have led the airlines in number of complaints,
showed a sharp improvement with their July figures. Continental had
its best month in a year, with 9.94 complaints per 100,000
passengers, and Northwest had 6.2 rate of complaints.
   The August complaint statistics were released along with the
July on-time statistics.
   The number of mishandled bags increased slightly during July to
7.15 per 1,000 boardings from 6.76 in June. TWA had the highest
number of such complaints, 11.65 for every 1,000 boardings.
</TEXT>
