<HEAD>Vietnamese Airliner Crashes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnamese jetliner crashed and
exploded in a rice field four miles short of Bangkok's airport
Friday, an air force spokesman said.
   Air Vice Marshal Sommot Sundaravej said air force helicopters
rescued six people _ four men and two women. He said he had no
information on casualties or on how many people were aboard the Air
Vietnam flight from Vietnam's capital, Hanoi.
   The flight is often taken by foreign diplomatic staff or relief
workers, Sundaravej said.
   Sundaravej said Flight VN831 crashed in a rice field at Fa Kam
village at 11:37 a.m. (12:37 a.m. EDT). The Soviet-made TU-134
exploded into small pieces after impact, he said.
   According to Jane's All The World's Aircraft, various versions
of the twin-engine TU-134 seat from 80 to 96 people.
