<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen     09-09 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says Democrats Will Fight `Moral Deficit'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, the Democratic vice
presidential nominee, is sharpening up his rhetoric as he and
Michael Dukakis fight back against Republican attacks that have
helped send their campaign sinking in the polls.
   Bentsen, who was heading to Iowa today for a speech in which he
planned to blast the GOP record on agriculture, told a gala
Democratic Party dinner in New York on Thursday night that he and
Dukakis would erase the ``moral deficit'' of the last eight years.
   With the help of record fundraising, including $5 million raised
at the Manhattan dinner alone, Democrats would be better able than
ever to deliver their message of ``hope,'' he said.
   ``The message is going to be `No' to the hate-mongering
disciples of the hard right,'' he said.
   ``The message is going to be `No' to the massive budget deficits
and trade deficits that have endangered America's economic
leaderhsip in the world.
   ``And the message is going to be `No' to the candidates who
impugn the loyalty and patriotism of others while hiding behind the
American flag,'' he said, a direct slap at Bush's criticism of
Dukakis, who, based on a court opinion that it was
unconstitutional, vetoed a Massachusetts law requiring the pledge
of allegiance in schools.
   Bentsen, speaking before New York Gov. Mario Cuomo and Dukakis,
was introduced by Texas State Treasurer Ann Richards, who was the
Democrats' keynote speaker at their convention in July.
   She got a roar from the crowd when she poked Bush for fumbling
the date of the attack on Pearl Harbor in a speech this week.
   ``Well, I told you he'd put a silver foot in his mouth,'' she
said. ``You see that one yesterday? I mean, I didn't even get shot
down, and I know when Pearl Harbor was.''
   After a warm reception, Bentsen continued the line. ``Alas, poor
George,'' he said, ``Ann Richards was born with a silver tongue in
his mouth.''
   ``Or as another Texan said,'' Bentsen added, ``George was born
on third base, and thinks he hit a triple.''
   The dinner, with 2,800 people paying at least $1,000 a seat, was
decidedly upbeat. But nationwide, the ticket is trailing the
Republicans by 51 percent to 42 percent, according to a new
Washington Post-ABC News poll.
   And despite the prominence of Bentsen and Richards, the
Democrats find themselves behind in the polls in Texas, which Bush
also calls home.
   Bentsen, who campaigned in Texas on Labor Day, was traveling to
California after Iowa this week. But Dukakis was visiting the state
today Friday and Bentsen planned to return next week to fight for
the state's prize of 29 electoral votes.
</TEXT>
