<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0510EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-AmericansforBush     09-09 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Americans for Bush,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Campaign Files Complaints Against Private PAC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush's presidential
campaign asked three agencies to investigate a political action
committee that has spent $1.5 million so far to promote Bush and
blast his opponent.
   The latest expenditure by Americans for Bush, an arm of the
National Security Political Action Committee, is a $500,000
television ad campaign painting Democrat nominee Michael Dukakis as
soft on crime and criminals.
   Officials of the group said they would continue spending
lavishly on the vice president unless Bush campaign chairman James
Baker III asks them to stop.
   Bush spokesman Mark Goodin said the campaign has filed
complaints against the group with the Postal Service, the Internal
Revenue Service and the Federal Election Commission.
   ``We are concerned about the name of the organization. It
connotes a connection with this campaign and the vice president.
There is no connection,'' Goodin said. ``We are also concerned
about their fundraising techniques and methods. There are a range
of complaints.''
   Some people have reported receiving as many as three mail
solicitations in the same day from Americans for Bush. Some
contributors, confused by the group's title and letterhead, have
said they believed they were giving money to the Bush campaign.
   NSPAC was formed in 1986 by chairman Elizabeth Fediay, retired
military officials and others. Fediay said the PAC has collected
$3.8 million since last year, including contributions to Americans
for Bush. She said anyone who wants a refund of their contribution
can get one.
   Fediay maintained that only middle-level Bush campaign staffers
have expressed concerns about NSPAC's activities, although Goodin
said Bush himself has asked that Americans for Bush change its name.
   Fediay said she was sending a letter to Baker seeking his view
of the group's independent activities on behalf of Bush. ``If he
asks me to stop advocating the election of George Bush, I will,''
she told reporters at a news conference called to unveil the
group's two latest ads.
   The new 30-second ads started airing Wednesday on national cable
networks and are to continue until Oct. 5 with appearances in
virtually every media market in the country.
   ``Dukakis not only opposes the death penalty, he allowed
first-degree murderers to have weekend passes from prison,'' a
narrator says in both ads.
   One spot goes on, ``Ten murderers on weekend passes have
escaped. One kidnapped and stabbed a Maryland man and raped his
fiancee. As president, George Bush will be as tough on criminals as
they are on us.''
   Leslie Dach, a Dukakis spokesman, said one way the governor
would respond to such attacks is by citing his record in
Massachusetts, where the crime rate has fallen during his tenure.
   Goodin said he was not familiar with the activities, ads or
media strategy planned by the group. The Bush campaign began its
own TV drive this week with sentimental spots showing Bush with his
family and at the Republican convention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
