<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTL     09-09 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PTL Trustee Moves on to Other Bids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRAD HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT MILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PTL founder Jim Bakker said he will
withdraw his offer to buy the ministry's assets if he cannot
confirm funding from his backers today.
   ``It's time to fish or cut bait,'' Bakker said Thursday after
meeting with PTL Bankruptcy Trustee M.C. ``Red'' Benton.
   Benton said Bakker has offered no proof he has the money to
carry out his $172 million bid. The trustee also met Thursday with
other potential buyers.
   In addition, Benton asked U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds
to extend from Saturday until Monday the deadline to present a
buyer, since Saturday is a weekend day. He said he expects to get
the extension.
   ``They did not show us anything (any documents) today,'' Benton
said after meeting with Bakker and his lawyers at PTL's offices.
   He said he would withhold judgment on whether he thinks Bakker
had the money, and would give him until 5 p.m. today to come up
with $3 million to secure his offer and to show proof that the
funds exist for the overall loan.
   Bakker, who resigned from PTL in March 1987 amid a sex-and-money
scandal, said he still is dealing with the investors he had
previously identified as 28 Greek businessmen. But he said Thursday
the investors are not necessarily from Greece and would identify
them only as Europeans.
   ``Somebody invented this Greek tycoon _ one of our beloved media
people _ and I went along with it because they wanted it so
badly,'' Bakker said.
   Bakker also said he is not concerned by reports that the
middleman he was using to talk to the investors has been convicted
of fraud.
   ``I'm very satisfied the money is not tainted,'' Bakker said.
   Louis M. Pihakis, identified as representing Greek financiers
backing Bakker's effort to buy back PTL, served prison terms for
mail fraud and other crimes during the 1970s.
   Pihakis has an unlisted telephone number and could not be
reached Thursday for comment.
   Bakker, who has been asking supporters for donations, said he
has more than $2 million now and ``it's still coming in.''
   ``I have agreed if we don't have confirmation of funds within
the next 24 hours ... we will withdraw our offer to purchase
Heritage USA and go back and regroup,'' Bakker said Thursday. ``I
feel like we need to bring this drama, at least this part of it, to
an end.''
   Benton also met with a group of investors he described only as
Canadian who are interested in bidding on PTL's Heritage USA
Christian theme park, satellite television network and undeveloped
property.
   He said the prospective bidder was not Canadian real estate
executive Peter Thomas, who had offered $113 million for the
ministry but withdrew Wednesday, saying he's ``just tired of
playing around.''
   Benton said Thomas is still ``waiting in the wings.''
   Bakker left PTL in March 1987 amid revelations of extravagant
spending and a sexual encounter with church secretary Jessica Hahn.
The ministry filed for bankruptcy reorganization that June.
</TEXT>
