<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Jet Crashes; At Least 60 Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with at least 60 dead. Pick up
6th pvs, `According to...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnamese jetliner crashed into a
field and exploded four miles short of Bangkok's airport Friday,
killing at least 60 people, an air force spokesman said.
   Air Vice Marshal Sommot Sundaravej said Air Vietnam flight 831
from Hanoi crashed into the rice field at Fa Kam village at 11:37
a.m. (12:37 a.m. EDT).
   Sommot said rescue workers retrieved 60 bodies from the
wreckage. He said six more people were seriously hurt.
   Communications Minister Montree Pongpanit said there were 90
people, including six crew members, aboard the flight. An official
of the Airport Authority of Thailand, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said there were 75 people aboard. There was no immediate
explanation for the discrepancy.
   Sommot said the dead included both Vietnamese and citizens of
other countries, but he did not have details. Usually, a fair
number of foreign diplomatic staff, relief workers and Vietnamese
living abroad take the flight.
   The plane that crashed was a Soviet-made TU-134 jet.
   According to Jane's All The World's Aircraft, various versions
of the twin-engine TU-134 seat from 80-96 people.
   The previous major airplane crash in Thailand was Aug. 31, 1987,
when a Thai Airways domestic airliner crashed into the sea off the
southern resort island of Phuket. All 83 people aboard died in the
crash of the Boeing 737, later blamed on errors by the pilot and
control tower.
</TEXT>
