<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Debt Grew $2.6 Billion In July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharp slowdown in the growth of consumer
credit in July indicates Americans are showing caution despite wage
gains that month, an economist says.
   ``Consumers don't seem to be buying big-ticket items as they had
in the past and that probably reflects the increases in interest
rates,'' Mike Evans, head of a Washington economic consulting firm,
said,
   The government reported Thursday that consumer credit grew at a
4.8 percent annual rate in July, a sharp decline from the 10.2
percent rate for the first six months of the year.
   Americans took out $2.6 billion more in consumer credit than
they paid off in July, well down from the $8.1 billion they took
out in June, according to the Federal Reserve Board.
   The Federal Reserve has been tightening credit since late March
in an effort to dampen demand as a way of cooling inflationary
pressures.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Educators Concerned About Censorship Efforts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Association of School
Administrators says growing pressure to censor the books children
read is harming the education available to America's young people.
   ``Pressures that could result in censorship are increasing, and
that has an adverse effect on the ability of the schools to provide
a broad-based education for children, who will be our future
leaders,'' said Judith Krug, director of the association's office
for intellectual freedom.
   The group issued a report called ``Censorship and Selection:
Issues and Answers for Schools'' that said the pressure comes from
people who want to impose their views on the educational system by
removing or restricting use of certain materials.
   The study was published jointly by the administrators group and
the American Library Association.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Educators, Publishers Stress Adult Literacy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of educators says the next
president must address a ``national disgrace'' that 23 million
adult Americans are illiterate.
   ``Literacy is probably America's most solvable problem,'' Peter
Waite, executive director of Lubach Literacy Action, said Thursday
at a press conference prior to the National Adult Literacy
Symposium.
   Dale Johnson, vice president of the International Reading
Association, said the next president ``must draw national attention
to this crisis,'' which he called ``a national disgrace.''
   ``Millions of Americans are locked out of good jobs, community
participation and the democratic process because they lack adequate
reading and writing skills,'' said Johnson.
   He called for increased federal funding for literacy programs,
establishment of a semi-governmental institute to promote reading
skills, and encouragement for state and local programs.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Vietnam Women's Memorial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel has approved a scaled-down
version of a Senate-approved bill authorizing a monument to
American women who served in the Vietnam War.
   The measure approved Thursday by the House Administration
subcommittee on libraries and memorials calls for a monument to the
10,000 American women who served in Vietnam to be built somewhere
on federal land in the Washington metropolitan area.
   A Senate bill, approved 96-1 in mid-June, specifies that a
bronze statue of an Army nurse be erected on the 2.2-acre grounds
of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial, which lists the names of the
58,000 men and women killed or missing in the Southeast Asian
conflict.
   The vote on separate provisions will force votes by Congress on
a specific site and design for the monument, as well as review by
three federal agencies.
</TEXT>
