<HEAD>Bush Campaign Fires Committee Co-Chairman After Complaints</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leader of a committee of George Bush's
presidential campaign has been dismissed amid accusations that he
and several other Bush volunteers have anti-Semitic backgrounds.
   Jerome Brentar, co-chairman of a committee trying to enlist
support among ethnic-Americans, was asked to resign Thursday after
it was learned he had defended a Cleveland autoworker convicted in
Israel as a Nazi war criminal, a Bush campaign aide said.
   ``We told him that his advocacy on this issue puts him at a
fundamental disagreement with the campaign and with the vice
president,'' said Mark Goodin.
   Goodin said Brentar belonged to a group that defended John
Demjanjuk, who is appealing a death sentence imposed after a court
in Jerusalem found him guilty of mutilating and killing inmates in
Nazi death camps during World War II.
   Rep. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., and five other Jewish members
of the House held a news conference to charge that an ``ugly
assortment of anti-Semites and racists'' had been named to the Bush
campaign committee.
   Goodin later responded that Bush ``is very clear that there is
no place in any organization he is associated with for religious
bigotry or for anyone who would tolerate those views.'' He said the
backgrounds of members of the committee are being reviewed.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>GOP Leaders Warn: Massachusetts Budget Could be $1.2 Billion Short</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican legislators say the state budget signed
by Gov. Michael Dukakis in July is out of balance by as much as
$1.2 billion because the governor is overestimating tax collections
and spending too much.
   ``The results are very sobering and very disquieting about the
future of this state,'' House Minority Leader Steven Pierce said
Thursday.
   Senate Minority Leader David Locke joined Pierce in calling once
again on Dukakis to demand that the legislature return to session
immediately to address the fiscal situation, auto insurance and
other concerns.
   Dukakis has touted the Massachusetts economy during his campaign
for the presidency.
   But Locke said, ``Based on our analysis, there is going to be a
shortfall that may exceed a billion dollars,'' and suggested
Dukakis and Democratic legislative leaders may be disguising
planned tax increases.
   Although the Legislature voted for the current $11.6 billion
budget in July and Dukakis does not have the power to
single-handedly summon the Legislature back to work, the
Republicans laid both problems at Dukakis' feet.
</TEXT>
