<HEAD>Humphrey Apologizes, Calls Remarks ``Just Plain Stupid''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saying he made a mistake and was ``just
plain stupid,'' Sen. Gordon Humphrey apologized to congressional
candidate Betty Tamposi for saying her place was at home with her
two small children.
   ``In plain English, I made a mistake, I am sorry, and I
apologize,'' Humphrey said in a statement released by his Concord
office on Thursday.
   Humphrey unleashed a firestorm of protests _ both by Tamposi
supporters and foes _ on Tuesday when he said it was ``self-evident
that you cannot work 12 to 14 hours a day in Congress and have time
left over for a child.''
   ``It's difficult enough being a father of a young child and a
member of Congress, as I am,'' said Humphrey, who has a 3-year-old
son. ``For the mother, who in our society is the primary care
giver, working 10-12 hours a day makes it impossible to give the
nurturing the child would need.''
   Humphrey suggested Tamposi was negligent to run for the House
with two daughters, ages 22 months and 4. Tamposi, a millionaire
officer in her father's real estate company, pays a nanny to care
for her children.
   On Thursday, Humphrey took it back even though he had insisted
for two days he would stand by his remarks.
   Humphrey apparently changed his mind after he got a call from
Chuck Douglas, Tamposi's strongest opponent in the 2nd District's
Republican primary on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Tobacco Program `Makes Sense'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis, a non-smoker and public health devotee, said the federal
tobacco price-support program ``makes sense and I support it,'' as
long as it costs taxpayers nothing.
   The tobacco program, a traditional litmus test for politicians
in burley-growing Kentucky, is ``essentially a no-cost program,''
Dukakis said Thursday in an interview with The Associated Press.
   ``I think it's something that's important to ... lots of small
farmers in Kentucky and other tobacco-growing areas of this
country. Obviously, I'm concerned about public health as well. ...
But, on its present basis, (the program) makes sense and I support
it,'' Dukakis said.
   Under the program tobacco farmers pay a per-pound assessment,
set annually by the U.S. Department of Agriculture. The money is
used to maintain a pool of tobacco stocks that fail to bring a
minimum, supported price at auction. Having their tobacco purchased
by the pool at least guarantees growers a minimum return.
</TEXT>
