<HEAD>Professors Approve New Contract, Return to Classroom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Professors at Hofstra University returned
to the classroom after overwhelmingly ratifying a new contract
following a week-old strike.
   The professors approved the agreement Thursday by a vote of 160
to 51 with two abstentions, according to Michael D'Innocenzo,
spokesman for the local chapter of the American Association of
University Professors.
   University spokesman Michael DeLuise said classes resumed
Thursday night.
   According to DeLuise, the three-year contract provides for
raising faculty salaries about 8 percent in the first year, 7
percent in the second year and 6 percent in the third.
   The contract also includes a 25 percent reduction in teaching
loads of about half the faculty members, he said.
   The strike at the university on Long Island began Sept. 1 on the
fourth day of the new fall term.
</TEXT>
