<2ND_LINE>PM-Undisclosed Death,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man's Family Notified Of Death By Parking Ticket To His Estate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of a man discovered dead in his car
by police wasn't notified until three weeks later, when they
received a towing bill addressed to his estate, authorities said.
   George Wood, 47, of Middletown, N.J., was found dead in the
parking lot of a Harlem restaurant Aug. 19, two days after he was
reported missing, said New York Police Sgt. Ray O'Donnell. An
autopsy showed he died of a heart attack.
   The New York Police Department notified Monmouth County Sheriff
Department, a routine procedure through which the Middletown Police
Department would have then been notified and contacted the family,
O'Donnell said.
   But Middletown police chief Joseph McCarthy said his department
was never notified.
   On Wednesday, the family received a letter from the New York
Police Department addressed to the estate of George Wood, said his
nephew, Pat Esposito. The letter contained a notice that Wood's car
had been towed, he said.
   Esposito said it was the first the family had heard of Wood's
body or that his car had been found.
   Officials at the sheriff's office could not be reached
immediately for comment.
</TEXT>
