<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh-Floods     09-09 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Floods,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Waters Receding But Sewage, Garbage Pose New Threat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Floodwaters that inundated
three-fourths of the nation receded today, but officials said
sewage and rotting garbage dumped into the stagnant waters posed
new health threats to millions of people.
   The government said 609 people had died since the floods began
June 13. The government's count, hampered by poor communications
and bureaucracy, is generally considered low.
   Dhaka newspapers, which publish their own daily tallies,
reported 101 new deaths today, bringing the unofficial death toll
to 1,402.
   The Information Ministry said most of the victims either
drowned, suffered snake bites or were killed when their houses
collapsed.
   The government's Health Center said 93 people died of diarrhea
contracted from drinking muddy floodwater. It said it knew of
135,537 cases of diarrhea nationwide, including 8,254 reported in
Dhaka, the capital of this impoverished country.
   Mohammad Azad, public relations officer at the International
Center for Diarrheal Distress, said that since Tuesday the hospital
had received between 300 and 400 diarreha cases a day, double the
number reported when the floods began.
   ``The hospital is overcrowded, with patients being treated in
corridors and officers' chambers. We have no place for patients any
more,'' Azad said.
   An official at the Flood Control Center said major rivers had
stopped rising but that five northern and southern districts were
facing new floods. Monsoon-swollen rivers in northeastern India
flow through Bangladesh into the Bay of Bengal.
   Health officials in Dhaka said that floodwaters combined with
sewage and rotting garbage posed another threat to the health of
the 6 million people in the capital.
   Nearly 40 million gallons of sewage and four tons of garbage
have been dumped into the stagnant water.
   The government has said at least 21 million of Bangladesh's 110
million people lost their homes in floodwaters that still range
from a few inches to at least 10 feet.
   Millions of people in the flooded areas or in relief camps do
not have enough food, drinking water or medicine.
   The Bangladesh Observer, an English-language daily, said 50,000
people marooned in Rupganj Upazila in Narayanganj district, about
20 miles south of Dhaka, were fighting ``a grim battle for their
survival as no relief material reached them yet.''
   The paper said many people were living on roofs and in trees.
   The country's two most influential opposition leaders,
meanwhile, accused the government of President Hussain Muhammad
Ershad of failing to ensure adequate rescue and relief operations.
   Sheikh Hasina and Kheleda Zia, who have been calling for
Ershad's ouster, claimed the government was obstructing relief
operations organized by political parties and volunteer
organizations in an effort to cover up mismanagement.
   Ershad has governed Bangladesh since seizing power in a
bloodless coup in March 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
