<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FatMan     09-09 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fat Man,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After Losing 680 Pounds, Man Walks Outside For First Time In 18
Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter Hudson, who walked out of his
house for the first time in 18 years after losing an estimated 680
pounds in a year, says he dreams of helping other fat people slim
down.
   ``I got a lot to live for,'' the 520-pound Long Island man said
after he lumbered into the sunshine Thursday. ``I want to help a
lot of people, people who are overweight or on drugs.''
   Hudson, 43, weighed about 1,200 pounds a year ago.
   Wearing a light blue toga with pants and sunglasses to protect
his eyes, Hudson walked through a widened doorway and onto a
specially constructed, elevated concrete patio. He sat on a
concrete block with a vinyl cushion.
   ``It feels good,'' he said. ``I shouldn't have waited this
long.''
   Hudson's fear that his legs would not support his weight kept
him confined mostly to his bed since he was 15 years old. He made
headlines last fall when he became wedged in a doorway and had to
be rescued by firefighters with saws.
   Hudson said Thursday that frightening episode was a blessing
because it made him realize something had to be done.
   ``I would have kept eating more and more,'' he said. ``That fall
saved my life. It was a gift from God.''
   He lost several hundred pounds under a diet regimen directed by
comedian-turned-nutritionist Dick Gregory, but when Gregory wanted
to bring him to his clinic in the Bahamas, Hudson balked. He didn't
want to leave the house.
   Hudson pressed ahead with his own diet. He drank his own liquid
diet formula, which he plans to market some day. Every other day,
he consumes nothing but water; every three days, he eats garlic,
onions and apple cider.
   In an average week, he loses three pounds. He hopes to reach 190
pounds.
   Hudson has been aided by a medical team led by Barbara Rosen, a
psychologist specializing in eating disorders.
   ``I am very proud of what Walter has accomplished in such a
short period of time,'' said Rosen. ``He knows now that anything he
sets his mind to do, he can do.''
   Hudson's goal is to visit his mother's grave in a cemetery a few
blocks from the small house he shares with his relatives.
   ``Mama knows I'm coming to see her,'' he said. ``It won't be
long now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
