<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Little Changed, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar changed little in light European
trading early today. Gold rose slightly.
   Dealers expected the dollar to trade within a narrow range at
least until release of the U.S. Producer Price Index, which
measures wholesale prices and is an important indicator of
inflation.
   Some dealers said the dollar could be boosted if producer prices
rise more than 0.5 percent and rekindle fears of a further rise in
interest rates.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 1.25 Japanese yen to a closing 132.95 yen.
Later, in London, it moved back up to 133.20 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Thursday:
   _1.8445 West German marks, down from 1.8485
   _1.5590 Swiss francs, down from 1.5600
   _6.2840 French francs, down from 6.3025
   _2.0815 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0855
   _1,378.50 Italian lire, down from 1,384.50
   _1.2390 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2395
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6985 from $1.6940 late
Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $428.85 a troy ounce, up
from $428 bid late Thursday. At mid-morning Friday, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $428.90.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $428.85, up from $428.50 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold edged up 4 cents to close at a bid
$430.55.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $6.63 a troy
ounce, up from $6.58 bid late Thursday.
