<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gulf-Talks 1stLd-Writethru   09-09 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0495,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Hints at Suspension Of Stalled Peace Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS graf after 3rd, `Velayati refused ...' to ADD no
response from Iraqis; SUBS 2nd graf to correct spelling of
Velayati. picks up 4th pvs, `In an ...'
^By TONY CZUCZKA</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran raised the possibility that the stalled peace
talks with Iraq could be suspended and shifted to New York, the
first public indication by either side that a break is near in the
2-week-old negotiations.
   Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran charged at a news
conference Thursday that Iraq tried to ``derail the discussions''
by introducing ``extraneous elements'' on the first day of talks
Aug. 25.
   He said the Tehran government agreed in principle _ ``with small
reservations'' _ to a compromise formula proposed by U.N. mediator
Jan Eliasson in an effort to move the talks ahead but that Iraq
refused to accept it. Velayati refused to elaborate on the proposal.
   There was no response from Iraqi officials. Iraq and Iran have
engaged in indirect peace talks all but one day since Aug. 25.
   In an interview with Iran's official Islamic Republic News
Agency, Velayati also accused the Iraqis of repeating past matters
``without showing the slightest cooperation and flexibility'' with
U.N. mediators.
   Asked at the news conference if he foresaw an early adjournment
of negotiations and a shift of venue to New York, he said:
   ``Yes, I think. It will start in maybe two or three weeks from
now, but the ending of this round of talks depends on the decision
of the (U.N.) secretary-general.''
   The talks are aimed at a lasting peace settlement after the
U.N.-sponsored cease-fire in the 8-year-old Persian Gulf war took
effect Aug. 20.
   The timing of the next round probably would coincide with
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar's presence in New York
for the U.N. General Assembly, opening Sept. 20.
   Perez de Cuellar personally mediated the first week of Iran-Iraq
talks, then named Eliasson, a Swedish diplomat, as his special
representative.
   The U.N. chief said Wednesday the talks were blocked and that no
quick solution was in sight.
   Velayati said Iran was ready to pursue peace efforts and to
resume face-to-face meetings, which were held only on the first two
days of talks.
   The London-based newsletter Mideast Mirror quoted Velayati in an
interview as urging third parties, including neighboring gulf Arab
states, to persuade the Baghdad government to ``confine the peace
talks to the agenda.''
   In Geneva, Velayati said Iraq deviated from the basis for the
talks, laid out mainly in a U.N. cease-fire resolution, by
demanding discussion of free navigation and the clearing of the
disputed Shatt-al-Arab waterway, which forms the countries'
southern border.
   Iran has consistently said these points should be dealt with
later.
   Velayati said clearing Shatt-al-Arab could not be discussed
before the forces of both sides withdraw to internationally
recognized borders.
   The problem is that Iran still considers valid a 1975 treaty
setting the Iran-Iraq border down the middle of Shatt-al-Arab,
Iraq's major sea outlet. Iraq has renounced the pact and claimed
the entire waterway.
   Shatt-al-Arab has been blocked by sunken ships almost since the
war began in September 1980 and has also become silted.
</TEXT>
