<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KingPapers     09-09 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-King Papers,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Calls For Trial in King Papers Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coretta Scott King can sue Boston University for
thousands of documents Martin Luther King Jr. gave the school, but
will have to explain why she waited 23 years to seek her late
husband's papers, a judge ruled.
   In a ruling made public Thursday, Suffolk Superior Court Judge
John L. Murphy Jr. said a 1964 letter by King bequeathing the
papers to BU is not a formal will, giving Mrs. King the right to
pursue her claim.
   A lawyer for Mrs. King, James O'Brien, said he was pleased with
the decision and would soon file a motion requesting a trial.
   Attorney Melvin Miller, a member of the BU Board of Trustees,
said Murphy's decision never touched on who should own the papers.
   The ruling dated Aug. 31 is the latest development in a legal
battle launched by Mrs. King in December. She wants the 83,000
documents held by BU transfered to the Martin Luther King Jr.
Center for Non-Violent Social Change in Atlanta, which holds
100,000 other King documents.
   The BU collection represents about one-third of King's surviving
documents and correspondence.
   A key issue in a trial, Murphy said, would be ``whether the
23-year delay in instituting this action was unreasonable and
resulted in some injury or prejudice to BU.''
   O'Brien said he was confident the question of any harm to BU in
the delayed filing of the claim can be easily handled. ``Boston
University has not been harmed in any way. It's actually benefited
by having the papers all this time,'' he said.
   The judge also rejected a counterclaim by BU to ownership of the
King papers stored in Atlanta.
   Miller labeled the decision ``very spurious,'' and said
university attorneys haven't decided whether to appeal.
   O'Brien said he was pleased the counterclaim was rejected.
``That's 90 percent of the case behind us in our favor,'' he said.
   Mrs. King is on vacation and was not available for comment.
   In the one-page, typewritten letter dated July 16, 1964, King,
who received his doctorate in theology from BU in 1955, wrote, ``In
the event of my death, all such materials deposited with the
university shall become from that date the absolute property of
Boston University.''
   The judge said BU was the rightful holder of the papers at the
time of King's death in April 1968, but agreed with Mrs. King's
argument that the letter didn't constitute a formal will.
   Mrs. King's suit claims the collection is not properly displayed
or preserved at BU.
   Some of the disputed documents are on display in the BU library.
Most of the collection, which is available to researchers and
scholars, is contained in 126 boxes in a climate-controlled room.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
