<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0480 09-09 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0480,520</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf to CORRECT Fort Worth to Dallas, based on
correction from Dukakis campaign.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Goes From T-shirt To Tuxedo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis heads south today, having
fattened the Democratic Party's coffers by $5 million while
acknowledging he faces ``formidable odds'' in his quest for the
White House.
   ``I won't kid you, this is not going to be an easy 60 days,''
Dukakis said at a black-tie fund raiser Thursday.
   Dukakis, whose campaign has been sinking in the polls since the
Republican National Convention last month in New Orleans, heads for
that city today, after first making a couple of stops in Texas.
   The Democratic presidential nominee was planning to stop first
at East Texas State College in Greenville, alma mater of the late
House Speaker Sam Rayburn, then address a convention of Baptist
ministers in Dallas.
   Thursday's fund-raiser, where supporters paid a minimum of
$1,000 each to attend, raised more than $5 million for the
Democratic Party, said Robert Farmer, in charge of raising money
for the Dukakis campaign.
   The Dukakis campaign so far has raised $30 million of its $50
million goal for the national party, Farmer said.
   The party can spend that money on activities related to the
election, such as drives to get out the vote.
   Dukakis also met briefly Thursday with Jesse Jackson, who was
among four of the unsuccessful Democratic presidential hopefuls
attending the dinner at a Manhattan hotel.
   The two men chatted for a few minutes as Jackson walked by
Dukakis' table in the hotel ballroom. The substance of the
discussion was not disclosed.
   The other former candidates at the event were Tennessee Sen.
Albert Gore Jr., Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt and former Arizona
Gov. Bruce Babbitt.
   Before the meeting, Jackson told reporters his support for the
ticket has not wavered since the Democratic convention in July, but
he said that the nominee's message was not getting through.
   ``I do know that we have a good message that needs to be an even
sharper message,'' Jackson said. ``If you write with the same
pencil for a long time sometimes the message gets blurred.''
   Dukakis, who said earlier in the day he was not worried about an
ABC-Washington Post poll showing him trailing Republican nominee
George Bush 51 percent to 43 percent, told his supporters the weeks
ahead will have ``good polls and not so good polls.''
   ``We are facing determined adversaries and formidable odds,''
Dukakis said.
   Dukakis was joined on the stage by his running mate, Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas.
   The tuxedos in Manhattan contrasted sharply with the T-shirts
and coveralls Dukakis encountered earlier Thursday at a General
Motors Corp. engine assembly plant at Tonawanda, N.Y.
   Dukakis strolled along the assembly line, shaking hands with the
workers, pausing briefly to cock his elbow atop a cart of fuel
injectors and talk.
   Later, with American flags and racks of completed V-6 engines
serving as a backdrop, Dukakis addressed a small but friendly crowd
of plant employees.
   He reminded them of a remark Bush made during a visit to the
Soviet Union, when he said workers there could come to the United
States to give Americans a lesson in quality.
   ``Those Republicans in Washington love to blame American workers
first,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
