<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Fires-Congress     09-09 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fires-Congress,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wallop Rejects White House Assurances, Calls For Park Service
Firing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The senior Republican senator from
flame-ravaged Wyoming insisted today that the Reagan administration
dismiss the head of the National Park Service over the
controversial policy that allowed fires to burn unhindered for
months in the West.
   Sen. Malcolm Wallop repeated his call for Park Service Director
William Penn Mott's dismissal despite a White House spokesman's
statement Thursday that, ``We have no plans to fire anybody.''
   Wallop, speaking on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America'' program,
said comments by Mott and other officials responsible for
maintaining the nation's forests have deeply harmed the morale of
those battling millions of acres of Western fires.
   ``Again, I would say Director Mott has reason to offer his
resignation,'' Wallop said in the interview.
   ``Their efforts to persuade the people of Wyoming and others
that they are doing what they can to control these fires are
completely undermined by the actions of Director Mott,'' said
Wallop.
   Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng, before leaving today with
Interior Secretary Donald Hodel for a tour of the burning lands,
said the policy of allowing natural fires to burn out has been
abandoned since July.
   And Lyng insisted on CBS-TV's ``This Morning,'' ``I don't think
there's going to be anyone fired.''
   ``In fairness I think these people have done what anyone
objectively looking at it would have to say a tremendous job of
trying to bring this very difficult situation under control,'' he
said.
   The calls for Mott's resignation came from Capitol Hill
Wednesday, and President Reagan moved to quell the discontent by
dispatching Hodel, Lyng and Deputy Defense Secretary William H.
Taft IV today to survey the damage.
   Almost all of Yellowstone National Park in Wyoming has been
closed because of fires that have burned 1.2 million acres.
</TEXT>
