<DOCNO> AP880909-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0839EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan-China     09-09 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-China,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan Inaugurates Ferry Service To China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KEELUNG, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sailors set off firecrackers and
passengers threw colorful streamers to shore as a luxury liner
pulled out of this northern port today in the first ferry service
between archrivals Taiwan and China.
   Many of the 68 Taiwanese passengers bound for Shanghai on the
Excelsior Neptune are visiting the Chinese mainland for the first
time since Taiwan's Nationalist government eased a four-decade-old
travel ban to China last year.
   Tsao Cheng-chih, president of the Excelsior Marine Transport
Inc., said the passengers would disembark at Okinawa early Saturday
and transfer to the Excelsior Mercury for the remainder of the
three-day journey to bypass the Nationalists' ban on direct
shipping links with China.
   ``We have been waiting for this sea voyage for months. It is
really convenient,'' said King Ta-wei, a clerk who left his native
Shanghai 42 years ago.
   King and his wife carried dozens of mooncakes, a traditional
snack of the Chinese Moon Festival that falls on Sept. 25, and
winter clothes as gifts for relatives.
   Among the passengers were 13 reporters, including a four-member
television crew, and about 30 retired servicemen, who came to
Taiwan in 1949 when the Chinese Nationalists fled the mainland
after losing a civil war to communist forces.
   ``I am anxious to know how my cousins are,'' said Wang Shi-wei,
a 65-year-old army veteran, who said he was excited at returning to
his hometown in northeastern Shandong province.
   More than 150,000 Taiwan residents have visited China since the
travel ban was eased in October to allow family reunions, first
flying to Hong Kong or other intermediate points because direct
travel remains forbidden by the Nationalist government.
   Shanghai is 370 miles northeast of Keelung, but the trip will
cover more than twice that distance because of the Okinawa stop.
   The Nationalists still ban official contacts with China but
decided at a July party congress to gradually open up more civilian
exchanges, such as allowing Chinese to visit sick relatives in
Taiwan.
   An 80-member Taiwanese and Philippine crew was aboard the liner,
which can carry 330 passengers, Tsao said. He blamed a poor
advertising campaign for the small number of passengers on the
maiden voyage.
   Tickets cost $517 for economy cabins and $590 for first-class
cabins. The 5,070-ton Soviet-made liner, which the Taiwan company
purchased through Hong Kong brokers earlier this year, features a
pool, music hall and bar.
   The Taiwan visitors will be welcomed by Shanghai city officials
and residents when the line arrives Monday, Tsao said.
   The liberal Liberty Times hailed the ferry service, which will
run once every four days, as a move that ``opens the door for
shipping exchanges across the Taiwan Straits.'' It said many
leading Taiwanese businessmen have visited various Chinese ports to
arrange for other ferry services.
   A Ministry of Communications official, Tony Tung, said the
liner's voyage to Okinawa was approved by Keelung Harbor Bureau
authorities because ``we consider it a regular shipping service
between two international ports. We don't question where and how
the passengers are trans-shipped after Okinawa.''
   Three other companies plan to inaugurate indirect passenger
ferry services to China later this month. On Saturday, the
Tokyo-based Naha Holiday Travel Center sent two liners, carrying
about 300 Taiwanese, from Keelung to the eastern Chinese coastal
city of Xiamen (Amoy) via Okinawa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
