<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Trotsky 2ndLd-Writethru   09-09 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Trotsky, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0541,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pravda Acknowledges Trotsky's Role in Russian Revolution</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to CLARIFY that article excerpted from
biography. Pickup 7th graf pvs, ``The headline...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN THOR-DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pravda today acknowledged for the first time in
decades that Leon Trotsky played a key role in the Russian
Revolution, but it said Lenin considered him a ``Judas.''
   For decades, Trotsky's name has been virtually banned from the
Soviet state-run press and his role in the creation of the world's
first socialist state virtually wiped from the historical record.
   The article in the government daily was an excerpt from a
biography of Josef Stalin being written by Col. Gen. Dmitri
Volkogonov. The biography described Trotsky in language that,
during Stalin's rule, might well have cost its author his life.
   ``Being quite a gifted publicist, speaker and organizer, Trotsky
played a well-known role in the October armed uprising and
eventually in the Civil War years when he was people's commissar
for military and naval affairs and chairman of the Revolutionary
Council,'' Pravda quoted the biography as saying.
   The words used to describe Trotsky would have been unimaginable
in the pages of the Communist Party daily as recently as a year
ago. Their publication in Pravda indicated high-level party support
for a reexamination of Trotsky.
   Although recognizing Trotsky's abilities and his deeds on behalf
of the revolution, the article noted that Vladimir Lenin, the
leader of the Bolsheviks, had called Trotsky a ``Judas'' in 1911.
   The headline of the full-page Pravda article called Trotsky
``the demon of the revolution,'' indicating that a full-blown
return to official favor is unlikely.
   By the time he was murdered in exile in Mexico City in 1940,
Trotsky's image had been cut or airbrushed from archive photographs
of the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution, and he was portrayed in official
histories solely as a revolutionary turncoat who opposed both Lenin
and Stalin.
   As part of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's drive for
``glasnost,'' or increased openness on some issues, Soviet
historians have been more frankly assessing their country's past,
including the role of Stalin foes like Nikolai Bukharin, Lev
Kamenev and Trotsky.
   In a major Kremlin speech last November, Gorbachev credited
Stalin with preventing a tae-over of the Communist Party by Trotsky
and his supporters in the late 1920s, and said Stalin was defending
the orthodox line set down by Lenin.
   But since then, the official state-run press has stepped up its
attacks on the bloody legacy left by Stalin's 29 years in power,
including a system of political and economic control based on
terror and purges in which millions died.
   ``During the years of revolution and Civil War, the most popular
leader after Lenin was Trotsky,'' the article said. ``There are
grounds to consider that Trotsky, during the years of his most
active participation in party life (1917-24), was not an enemy of
the revolution and of socialism. But already at that time, he was
an enemy of Stalin.''
   That phrasing is at odds with the way the Soviet press depicted
Trotsky for decades: as a turncoat and traitor to the working class
and to the revolution.
   Before Lenin died in 1924, he called Trotsky and Stalin
outstanding Communist Party officials but drew the attention of the
party to the ``serious negative personal qualities'' of both men,
the article said. ``The struggle between them became one of the
most dramatic pages of our history,'' it added.
   After Lenin's death, the article said, the Soviet founder's
appraisal of Trotsky as a ``self-confident, perennially dodging and
shifting and tricky politician became confirmed.''
   After being expelled from the party and the country, Trotsky
``slipped down to anti-Soviet and anti-Marxist positions,'' the
Pravda article said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
