<DOCNO> AP880909-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0856EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-HamadiTrial 1stLd-Writethru   09-09 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hamadi Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0542,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Says Hamadi Appeared to be Leader of Hijackers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to ADD quotes and details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American witness testified
today that Mohammed Ali Hamadi appeared to be the leader of the
1985 hijacking of a TWA jetliner and that Hamadi said throughout
the ordeal, ``One American must die.''
   The witness, Kurt Carlson, 41, of Rockford, Ill., testified in a
heavily guarded Frankfurt courtroom that Hamadi severely beat him
with an iron bar and left him for dead. ``I prayed to God that he
would take my life before the hijacker came back to shoot me,''
Carlson said.
   Hamadi has acknowledged during his trial on air piracy and
murder charges that he was one of the hijackers but insisted he was
not the leader.
   Carlson was among 39 Americans held hostage for 17 days aboard
the jetliner after it was seized and diverted to Beirut on June 14,
1985. Navy diver Robert Stethem was killed by the hijackers.
   ``It was very apparent to me from the beginning that Hamadi was
in charge,'' Carlson said as he described the hijacking ordeal for
the court. ``I assumed he was in charge since he gave the orders.''
   Carlson said the first words by the hijackers after they seized
TWA flight 847 were: ``Americans die, come to die.''
   The former hostage said the slogan was shouted by Hamadi's
fugitive accomplice, identified by the prosecutors as Hassan
Ezzeddine.
   Carlson said he was returning on the plane to the United States
from a week of reserve military duty for the U.S. Army in Egypt. He
said ticketing agents told him he got the last available seat in
Athens.
   Carlson said he was sitting in the first-class section and had
left his official red passport in his coat in a closet in the
section.
   After Hamadi found Carlson's passport, Carlson said he stood up.
   ``Hamadi took his gun and put it to my forehead. It was cocked.
He had his finger on the trigger. Hamadi said in English `CIA or
FBI?'''
   Carlson said he then explained to purser Uli Derickson that he
was a member of the Army reserve. Hamadi then told him to sit down.
   Carlson said that when the plane landed in Algiers the first
time ``Hamadi put the gun behind my ear and took me to the
first-class compartment.''
   He said Hamadi then tied his hands behind his back with a
necktie, put a handkerchief over his eyes, pushed him into the
cockpit and threw him on the floor. He said Hamadi talked to the
pilot, and Carlson said he could hear that there was difficulty in
the negotiating with the tower on refueling.
   ``Hamadi was screaming in Arabic and was hitting me on the
shoulders with the arm of the seat of the flight engineer,''
Carlson said. ``I began to pray, he (Hamadi) began to kick me. He
would jump up and down and kick.''
   ``He screamed `Marine' as he was kicking me,'' said Carlson.
``Then he set a deadline for my life. Fifteen minutes,'' said
Carlson.
   Hamadi several times extended the deadline for refueling with
the tower, Carlson said. He said Hamadi became more and more
agitated as the negotiations dragged on.
   ``Angry, he said in English `One American must die,''' Carlson
said. ``Suddenly I heard him scream `Marine' and I felt a metal bar
come down on my head twice. I knew that third blow would be the
death blow, because I heard him climb on a console.''
   Carlson said he managed to roll slightly on the floor and did
not take the full force of the blow.
   ``Hamadi then kicked me in the jaw to see if I was alive.''
   Carlson said that Hamadi then dragged him to the front passenger
door, opened the door, ``and with the gun at my head, extended the
deadline for another 10 minutes.''
   Hamadi then went back to the cockpit, and Carlson said he lost
feeling from the waist up and started to cough up blood. ``At that
point I felt that I'd certainly die within 10 minutes,'' Carlson
said.
   Carlson said that after the hijacking was over, stewardess Uli
Direckson told him that after the deadline passed ``Hamadi came
back to kill me, but both she and Hamadi thought I was already
dead.''
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt airport in 1987 after
explosives were discovered in his luggage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
