<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AirShowDisaster     09-09 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Show Disaster,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll In Ramstein Crash Climbs To 59</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAINZ, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll in last month's
Ramstein air show disaster climbed to 59 when three more people
died, including a young girl, officials said today.
   The state government spokesman, Juergen Dietzen, said two West
German men in their 40s died and ``the third was a 5-year-old
German girl.''
   More than 20 people remained hospitalized in critical condition.
   The disaster occurred Aug. 28 at the U.S. Air Force base in
Ramstein when three Italian stunt-flying jets collided at a low
altitute and one of them hurtled into a crowd of spectators and
exploded.
   Fifty-two Germans, two Americans, one person each from France
and the Netherlands, and the three Italian pilots died in the
disaster.
   Ramstein Air Base is located in Rhineland-Palatinate in the
southwestern part of the country. In Bonn, a committee of
Parliament met today to seek the causes of the tragedy, and to
determine who was responsible.
</TEXT>
