<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0909EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Turkey-Kurds 1stLd-Writethru   09-09 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turkey-Kurds, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0455,0744</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turks Worry About Long-Term Problems From Kurdish Refugees</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Foreign Ministry denying
Kurds forced into Iran. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``Security forces...''
TRIMS. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turks are expressing concern over
long-term problems that may have been caused by allowing about
60,000 Kurdish refugees fleeing Iraq to enter Turkey in the past
week.
   Primary concern is over security at a time when Turkey slowly
has been gaining the upper hand in a war of attrition against its
own band of Kurdish guerrillas known as the Kurdish Labor Party.
The Marxist group aims to set up an independent state in the
southeast provinces.
   Intelligence and military officials fear that members of the
party, often denied sanctuary or assistance by Turkey's Kurdish
minority of 10 million in the region, can now find a safe haven to
organize and recruit in the new refugee camps near the border.
   Today, the Foreign Ministry denied reports that several thousand
Kurdish refugees given sanctuary in Turkey had later been forced to
go to Iran.
   ``It is out of the question to send any of the refugees to
another country against their will. We categorically deny these
reports,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Nazim Belger said.
   On Sunday, the leftist Istanbul daily Cumhuriyet quoted a local
opposition politician in Semdinli township near the Iraqi border as
saying that 4,000 to 5,000 Kurdish refugees had been sent to Iran
against their will.
   The report was later picked up by foreign news media.
   Security forces are taking precautions to prevent infiltration
of the camps by the Kurdish Labor Party, regional governor Hayri
Kozakcioglu has said.
   Since 1984, about 700 people have died in clashes between
Turkish government forces and the guerrillas.
   Local residents feel Turkey's acceptance of the refugees, who
have relatives or other ties in Turkey, will win the loyalty of the
country's Kurds and reduce any motivation to cooperate with the
Kurdish Labor Party.
   ``All action against the government must now stop because of the
goodness shown our ethnic brothers,'' said Selim Kaya, a driver
from the Hakkari province where the refugee influx was centered.
   While the security problem was being debated over the past two
days, guerrillas killed eight soldiers and one police officer. Five
rebels were slain by the army.
   Another possible problem stemming from the admission of the
refugees could be the deterioration of Turkey's relations with
Baghdad, diplomats and officials say.
   Throughout the eight-year Iran-Iraq war, Turkey maintained good
relations with both sides, meeting their export needs but refusing
to sell arms.
   Iraq sees the Kurdish guerrillas as traitors who sided with the
enemy and attacked them when they were engaged with Iranian forces.
Seen in that context, Turkey's admission of the refugees can be
seen as rendering aid to the enemy.
   The refugees include many guerrillas. According to reports from
the border area, several thousand already have crossed into Iran,
from where they are likely to slip back into Iraq to fight again.
Iran has been supporting the guerrillas.
   Iraq launched its offensive against Kurds fighting for autonomy
in northern Iraq soon after Iran agreed to a U.N.-sponsored
ceasefire in the Iran-Iraq war. The cease-fire began Aug. 20.
   Iraq has declared amnesty for the Kurds, reportedly at Turkey's
urging, but Kurdish leaders have already said they will not accept
the promised pardon.
   ``The Kurds have not struggled to be pardoned but to achieve
their national and democratic rights within autonomy,'' said
Massoud Barzani, president of the Kurdish Democratic Party, one of
the major rebel groups in Iraq. ``Our struggle will continue until
these goals are fulfilled.''
   The refugees, originally spread along a 60-mile stretch of land
a few miles from the Iraqi border, are being resettled in tent
cities set up at five locations in Diyarbakir, Mardin and Hakkari
provinces.
   Protecting the refugees against the cold, feeding them and
providing for medical and other needs will severely strain Turkey's
resources which are scarcely sufficient for its own population in
the backward eastern region, commentators in Turkish newspapers
said.
   ``Do not be surprised if the condition of the camps one day is
criticized as `cruelty of the Turks' by some imaginative
anti-Turkish groups in Western Europe,'' columnist Hasan Pulur
wrote Thursday in the independent daily Milliyet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
