<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DressDiscrimination     09-09 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dress Discrimination,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saks Unfairly Charges Women for Alterations and Not Men, Suit
Alleges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney Gloria Allred wants Saks Fifth
Avenue to tailor a new policy for alterations on clothes, saying
the store discriminates against women.
   Ms. Allred, who filed a class-action suit in state court
Thursday, accused Saks stores of charging women but not men for
alterations.
   ``With this lawsuit we seek to cause Saks to mend their ways and
alter their policy. They should tailor their policies to fit
existing law, not sexually discriminatory tradition,'' she quipped.
   Martin Fischer, general manager of Saks' Beverly Hills store,
said, ``Our general policy at Saks Fifth Avenue is to charge the
customer equally based on sewing and the sewing task performed.
This applies to both men's and women's clothing.''
   The suit was filed on behalf of two executives of a career
counseling company.
   One of the women said she purchased a $1,500 evening gown at the
Costa Mesa store and was charged $40 for minor alterations, while
her husband bought a tuxedo and was not billed for extensive
alterations.
   Ms. Allred said similar policies were in effect at Saks Beverly
Hills and Saks in New York.
</TEXT>
