<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KodakCalendar     09-09 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kodak Calendar,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Abandoning Its 13-Month Calendar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Starting in 1990, Eastman Kodak Co.
employees will stop working 13 months a year.
   Kodak is abandoning the 13-month calendar developed by founder
George Eastman in 1928. The change follows a task force report that
concluded, ``It's time to harmonize the calendar.''
   The change actually makes little difference to Kodak employees,
except that department heads who make out 13 financial reports a
year now will fill out only 12.
   A Calendar Steering Committee has been formed ``to help ease the
transition and minimize the culture shock,'' according to Kodakery,
the company's internal newspaper.
   Eastman, a busy man, probably wished he could cram more than 24
hours into a day or seven days into a week. But his 13-month
calendar was intended to smooth out variations in the standard
calendar, in which months can be anywhere from 28 to 31 days long
and have four and sometimes five weekends.
   Those variations could cause Kodak's financial performance to
vary from one month to another, even though there was no real
change.
   So Kodak departments report expenses and revenues every four
weeks, with each month containing 20 work days and eight weekend
days. Thirteen of those periods make one year.
   Eastman was so convinced of the value of his calendar that he
and other business executives urged the federal government to adopt
it as the standard for all business. But the government stuck to
the traditional 12 months.
   The Eastman calendar has only 364 days in a year. Every five or
six years, the company had to add an extra week to get back in sync
with the rest of the world.
</TEXT>
