<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Humphrey-Tamposi 1stLd-Writethru a0556 09-09 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Humphrey-Tamposi, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0556,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Humphrey Apologizes, Calls Remarks `Just Plain Stupid'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS next-to-last graf, `Tamposi and ...' to CORRECT Douglas'
first name to Chuck.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BETSY HENDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Gordon Humphrey has apologized to a
congressional candidate for saying she should stay home with her
two children, a remark he called ``just plain stupid.''
   ``In plain English, I made a mistake, I am sorry, and I
apologize,'' the New Hampshire Republican said in a statement
Thursday.
   Humphrey unleashed protests _ both by foes and supporters of
Republican Betty Tamposi _ on Tuesday when he said it was
``self-evident that you cannot work 12 to 14 hours a day in
Congress and have time left over for a child.''
   ``It's difficult enough being a father of a young child and a
member of Congress, as I am,'' said Humphrey, who has a 3-year-old
son.
   ``For the mother, who in our society is the primary care giver,
working 10-12 hours a day makes it impossible to give the nurturing
the child would need.''
   Tamposi has two daughters, ages 22 months and 4. A millionaire
officer in her father's real estate company, she is married and has
a nanny care for her children.
   On Thursday, Humphrey retracted his statement even though he had
insisted for two days he stood by his remarks.
   ``While everyone knows of the strains congressional families
experience as a result of the long working days of members of
Congress, I had no right to impugn the motives of any person
wishing to serve in Congress,'' he said.
   ``My statements of Tuesday, that Betty Tamposi was prepared to
place her ambitions ahead of the welfare of her children, were
unjustified and just plain stupid,'' Humphrey said.
   Tamposi and Chuck Douglas are viewed as the front-runners in the
six-person GOP primary for a U.S. House seat on Tuesday. Humphrey
supports Douglas but cannot vote for him because he lives in a
different district.
   Tamposi campaign aide Clark Dumont had called Humphrey's
statement the lowest attack ``ever experienced in New Hampshire
politics.''
</TEXT>
