<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0543 09-09 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0543,0807</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fundamentalists Enforce Strike, Troops Seal West Bank Village</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to UPDATE with details on Gaza raid.
Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``The strike...'' EDITS thereafter to conform.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli security forces today arrested more
than 200 pro-PLO activists and claimed to have broken up a
clandestine network that organized subversive activities in the
Gaza Strip, the army said.
   The roundup came as Islamic militants mounted a strike that
closed most of the occupied lands in a challenge to the pro-PLO
United National Leadership of the Uprising. In some areas,
fundamentalists fought supporters of PLO chairman Yasser Arafat
with stones and fists.
   Meanwhile, police said a Palestinian who allegedly collaborated
with Israel was assassinated in Jaffa near Tel Aviv.
   In another development, hospital officials said four
Palestinians, including a 14-year-old boy, were shot and wounded in
clashes with Israeli troops near the West Bank town of Nablus.
   Elsewhere, several hundred Israeli soldiers, using a new tactic
to combat the 9-month old Palestinian uprising, sealed off the West
Bank village of Kfar Malik, 15 miles north of Jerusalem, at dawn
today and arrested about 25 Palestinians accused of anti-Israel
activities, Arab residents said.
   An army spokesman said soldiers carried lists of suspects who
allegedly carried out subversive activity and hostile acts such as
throwing rocks and bottles.
   On Tuesday, soldiers entered Qalqilya, a town of about 25,000,
and arrested about 200 Arabs. The town, located on a strategic
highway linking Israel and dozens of Jewish settlements, remained
under curfew today.
   The crackdown in Gaza broke up a regional leadership that
extended to 37 so-called popular committees, which organized
community affairs in towns, villages and city neighborhoods.
   An army spokesman said those arrested were linked with Fatah,
Arafat's faction of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   The army claimed to have captured the Gaza leader of the PLO
network, but the spokesman declined to identify him except to say
he had been arrested previously.
   Those detained in Gaza were responsible for 40 to 50 firebomb
attacks against the shops of merchants who failed to heed strike
calls, the army spokesman said, adding the groups also planned
about 30 attacks against Israeli army patrols.
   Maj. Gen. Yitzhak Mordechai, commander of the Gaza Strip, was
quoted by Israel radio as saying he may recommend deportation for
some of those detained. Israel has deported 33 Palestinians since
the uprising began in December, despite international protests.
   Israel radio said three members of the Gaza ring were suspected
of killing Rachel Weiss, an elderly woman found near her Negev
Desert home on Aug. 3.
   The army spokesman said the arrest campaign had severely
weakened the PLO. ``We are not saying that new leaders will not
emerge, but they will not have the same influence or
organization,'' said one spokesman who demanded anonymity.
   The strike called by the fundamentalist ``Hamas,'' or zeal,
stopped workers from going to jobs in Israel and closed stores and
businesses. But in some cases fundamentalists fought PLO supporters
with stones, fists and angry words.
   Shortly before today's strike was scheduled to begin, masked
youths rode bicycles through the largely Christian town of
Bethlehem, warning shopkeepers to close within five minutes. The
merchants complied reluctantly.
   ``If the strike is going to take place then I will observe it,
not because I want to but because I am afraid that my shop will be
burned,'' said Bassam Jaber, owner of a car spare parts store.
   Arguments broke out between Hamas supporters and shopkeepers
near Bethlehem's market after Islamic militants shouting ``Allahu
Akbar'' (God is Great) started burning tires and warning merchants
to observe the strike, witnesses said. The fighting ended when
Israeli troops approached.
   Most of Arab east Jerusalem, including the walled Old City,
remained open despite the strike call.
   The strike is part of a power struggle between Islamic militants
who oppose any negotiated settlement with the Jewish state and
supporters of the PLO who have been urging peace talks.
   Hamas has a large following among the 650,000 residents of the
Gaza Strip, but their support has traditionally been weaker in the
West Bank, where 850,000 Palestinians live.
   The Islamic fundamentalist strike was called to mark the start
of the 10th month of the Palestinian uprising. Since the rebellion
began Dec. 8, 260 Palestinians and five Israelis have been killed.
   In Jaffa, police said an assailant shot and killed Ahmed
Fanjari, 55. The assailant escaped. A police commander on Israel
army radio linked the shooting to a dispute in the Moslem community
over Fanjari's selling of land.
   Palestinian sources said graffitti seen on walls in the area
accused him of collaborating with Israeli officials.
</TEXT>
