<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0539,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Protestant On Commuter Train; 14 Injured In Bomb
Attack</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to ADD that victim was Protestant,
CORRECTS that train left from Coleraine, sted Londonderry. Pickup
7th graf pvs, ``Police said...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen shot and killed a
Protestant man on a Belfast-bound commuter train today, then fled a
suburban station in a waiting car, police said.
   Hours earlier, a bomb planted in a parked van exploded outside a
village police station, injuring five policemen and nine civilians
and heavily damaging the building and nearby houses, police said.
   The shooting occurred when the train, en route from Coleraine in
the north of the province, stopped at Balmoral station in southwest
Belfast, police said. Witnesses said the gunmen boarded the train a
few stops earlier and sat opposite the victim before shooting him.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility. The man, who was
pronounced dead on arrival at a nearby hospital, was not
immediately identified. Police said he was a Protestant.
   News reports identified the slain man as a senior member in the
Ulster Clubs, a Protestant protest group that sprang up in the wake
of the Anglo-Irish agreement. The 1985 accord gave the Irish
Republic an advisory role in the British province for the first
time.
   Police said a warning was telephoned to police in the County
Tyrone village of Coagh, 25 miles west of Belfast, shortly before a
bomb exploded Thursday night outside the police station. Police
were evacuating residents from nearby houses when the bomb went
off, they said.
   No one claimed responsibility for the explosion, but police said
they suspected the Irish Republican Army. The mainly Catholic IRA
recently has stepped up its campaign against authorities in the
British province.
   Two elderly men and a policeman remained hospitalized today, but
the spokesman said their injuries were minor. The others were
treated for injuries and released, he said.
   Police said the blast heavily damaged the police station and
nearby houses.
   More than 100 families were evacuated from their homes
overnight, said the police spokesman, who refused to give his name
in accordance with regulations.
   The IRA is fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland and
unite the Protestant-dominated province with the Catholic Republic
of Ireland under socialist rule.
</TEXT>
