<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 1002EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pope-Africa     09-09 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope-Africa,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vatican Offers Papal Visit to South Africa At Later Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS REDMONT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican today said that John Paul II,
who is skirting South Africa on a five-country pilgrimage starting
Saturday, hopes to visit the racially troubled nation at a later
date.
   In an unusual statement issued on the eve of his departure, the
Vatican emphasized that the pope would welcome such a stop ``so
that he may become more closely acquainted with the vast and varied
reality of their (South African) local church.
   ``As is well known, however, the conditions prevailing in that
country are marked by complex problems affecting the coexistence of
the various ethnic groups _ problems which give rise to anxiety and
considerable concern.''
   The Vatican statement appeared directed at reports the pope had
ruled out a visit to segregated South Africa, which has a white
minority government.
   The Vatican statement said that while the pope would have liked
to visit other nations in southern Africa on this trip ``the
intense program already arranged some time ago has made it
impossible.''
   In July, the pope said that South Africa's Roman Catholic
bishops had advised against a trip at this time but that maybe he
could visit the country some day. He didn't elaborate at the time.
   Many South Africans are expected to travel to the five countries
bordering South Africa which the pope will visit _ Zimbabwe,
Botswana, Lesotho, Swaziland and Mozambique.
   The Vatican statement pointed out that the South African bishops
whom the pope will meet in Zimbabwe had sent the pope an invitation
as long ago as 1982, and that the government had also extended its
own bid.
   Mentioning without elaborating the ``complex problems''
affecting the ethnic coexistence, the statement added: ``In such
circumstances, a visit by the pope could nevertheless favor a
positive development of the situation.''
   ``One of its many good results would be to encourage the efforts
of those _ especially the Catholics _ who are involved, with
generosity and good will, the quest for peaceful solutions for the
life of the whole of South African society.''
   South Africa dominates communications, trade, transportation and
politics in southern Africa and its influence will be felt strongly
during the 10-day trip. John Paul has been critical of South
African apartheid throughout his nearly 10-year-old pontificate.
   He has frequently visited countries whose policies local bishops
and the Vatican have criticized, ranging from Marxist Nicaragua to
authoritarian governments in Paraguay and Chile.
</TEXT>
