<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Koch-Judge     09-09 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koch-Judge,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Scolds Mayor Over Sentencing Appearance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch urged a judge to send
parking meter thieves to jail, but she rejected his advice and
scolded him for singling out ``the little people'' in his first
court appearance in 11 years.
   Then she made him sit in the courtroom, despite what he said was
important city business awaiting him.
   Supreme Court Justice Ruth Moskowitz said she thought Koch
should stay to learn more about the defendants and see the
sentencings.
   ``He has never appeared when a commissioner was being sentenced.
He has never appeared when a borough president or someone in high
political office was being sentenced,'' Moskowitz said Thursday.
   ``These are the little people and the little people commit
crimes, too,'' she said. ``Little people are going to be treated
just the way the big boys are treated. They are human beings and
they have rights, too.''
   Koch, in his statement to the court, said he was outraged by
Moskowitz's promise to spare some of the 34 former meter collectors
a jail term or probation.
   Koch then asked to leave to conduct important city business. But
the judge refused.
   ``If you are ordering me I will stay but I don't believe you
have the right to,'' Koch said, returning to his seat in the
gallery.
   About 10 minutes later, when the first sentencing, Moskowitz
said, ``I'm going to release the mayor from custody.''
   Koch and his entourage then left the courtroom.
   Koch called Moskowitz's comments about him never appearing in
court before a ``cheap shot.''
   He said he had previously submitted written statements to judges
in the Howard Beach racial attack and the case of a former Bronx
Democratic leader convicted of corruption.
   ``I believe that if you commit a crime against government,
whether you are in a high place or a low place, you deserve to go
to jail,'' he said.
   Inside the courtroom after the mayor had left, Moskowitz said,
``I have never had a victim come into court, make a speech for the
cameras and rush out again.''
</TEXT>
