<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Congo-Angola 1stLd-Writethru   09-09 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congo-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0548,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks On Angola-South Africa Peace End, New Talks To Be Scheduled</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Namibia clash, Pik Boths reax. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials from South Africa, Cuba and
Angola failed today to resolve the key issue of when Cuban troops
will withdraw from Angola, a South African official said.
   However, the official said some progress was made during the
two-day meeting that ended today and that a cease-fire remained in
force.
   Further talks were to be scheduled, he said.
   South Africa has made independence for South-West Africa
contingent on the withdrawl of Cuban troops from Angola, where
anti-Marxist rebels are fighting the Soviet-backed government.
   South Africa has administered the territory, also known as
Namibia, for 73 years in violation of U.N. resolutions. South
Africa's military said today that two pro-independence rebels and
two members of the security forces were killed in a shootout in the
northern Namibia town of Oshikati.
   The Wednesday skirmish between guerrillas of the South-West
Africa People's Organization and the security forces was the latest
of several battles between the two sides since SWAPO said it would
begin observing a cease-fire Sept. 1.
   South African President P.W. Botha had earlier said the Angolan
peace talks, one of a series of negotiations mediated by the United
States, would first deal with reports of recent Cuban troop
reinforcements in Angola.
   He said if the reports were true, they would constitute a
violation of the month-old cease-fire agreement.
   Cuba and Angola denied the claims, saying troop ships en route
to Angola carried replacements for the 50,000 soldiers already
there.
   The Cuban troops help Angola's Marxist government battle the
guerrillas and South African forces.
   The anti-Marxist force _ Jonas Savimbi's Union for the Total
Independence of Angola, or UNITA _ has been fighting the Marxist
government since Portugal granted Angola independence in 1975.
   The chief of the South African delegation, Neil Van Heerden,
said the talks allowed the two sides ``to make significant progress
on the problem.''
   ``We are going to study the proposals thatarose during the
course of the discussions'' and the parties will consult with their
governments before deciding on a date and venue for new talks, he
said.
   Van Heerden, director-general of the foreign affairs department,
declined to give details on the talks. He said, however, that South
Africa would continue with its plan to begin implementation of a
United Nations' plan for independence for South-West Africa.
   South African Foreign Minister Pik Botha, at a news briefing in
Pretoria after his country's delegation returned, said all parties
at the talks had agreed to intensify their efforts to agree on a
timetable.
   Also discussed, he said, were funding for the United Nations'
proposed independence plan for Namibia and South Africa's demand
that African National Congress guerrilla bases in Angola be removed.
</TEXT>
