<HEAD>Columnist Hospitalized After Speech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syndicated Columnist Carl T. Rowan was in good
condition today at Georgetown University Hospital after he fainted
walking out of an auditorium where he had delivered a speech.
   Tests were being run as a precaution, but a hospital spokeswoman
said the cause of Rowan's collapse appeared to be ``heat and
exhaustion.''
   ``There's no specific reason (for the fainting episode), except
that he was suffering from heat and exhaustion,'' said the
spokeswoman, who asked not to be identified. She said the columnist
was not expected to be hospitalized long.
   Rowan, 52, was leaving a lecture hall at American University
Thursday night after giving a speech on the presidential campaign
when he collapsed, a student who was nearby said.
   The columnist, an outspoken opponent of handgun use, is
scheduled to stand trial Sept. 22 on charges that he used an
unregistered handgun and ammunition in the June 14 wounding of a
teen-ager who was using Rowan's backyard swimming pool without
permission.
