<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-MarsProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0571 09-09 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Mars Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0571,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ground Control Error Leaves Soviet Mars Probe Worthless</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with space official saying mistake has
made Mars probe worthless. DELETES outdated material. ADDS byline.
No pickup.
^By ANDREW KATELL</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet space official said today that a ground
control operator sent an incorrect message to a Soviet space probe
bound for Mars, and the unmanned spacecraft is now worthless.
   ``Only a miracle can save it,'' Roald Z. Sagdeyev, head of the
Soviet Space Research Institute, said in an interview with The
Associated Press.
   Earlier, the official Tass news agency announced that ground
control had lost communications contact with the Phobos 1 probe,
which is millions of miles from Earth and racing toward a
rendezvous with the planet Mars.
   The Phobos 1 mishap follows a foul-up earlier in the week that
delayed the landing of a Soviet space capsule carrying a Soviet and
an Afghan cosmonaut.
   The unmanned Mars probe, Phobos 1, was launched July 7, and a
twin spacecraft, Phobos 2, on July 12.
   The probes were scheduled to go into orbit around Mars and in
January drop behind Phobos, the larger of the Red Planet's two
moons, to study the Martian surface, atmosphere and magnetic field.
   Sagdeyev, however, said that a ground control operator at the
Soviet Mission Control Center near Moscow sent an incorrect command
to Phobos 1 during the night of Aug. 29-30 that left the spacecraft
``sleeping'' and ``frozen.''
   He said the mistake was discovered three days later and that
ground control operators were trying to correct the problem by
sending new commands to Phobos 1. But the spacecraft was not
responding, he said.
   Sagdeyev said the probe could virtually be written off as a
total loss.
   The Soviet space research chief spoke to a reporter during an
afternoon reception at the U.S. ambassador's residence in honor of
Andrei D. Sakharov, the Soviet physicist and human rights activist
who is the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize laureate.
   Tass, in its report, indicated that Soviet space officials had
not had any contact with Phobos 1 for at least a week.
   ``In the two months that elapsed after the blastoff, the space
probes performed 75 radio communications sessions during which
measurings of trajectory parameters were made and operation on
onboard systems and scientific equipment was monitored,'' Tass said.
   ``On Sept. 2, another planned session of radio communication
with the Phobos 1 station failed to materialize,'' Tass said. ``At
that time, the station was 17 million kilometers (10.5 million
miles) from the Earth. On Sept. 9 (today), it was 19 million
kilometers (11.8 million miles) from the Earth.''
   Phobos 1 was supposed to navigate with a NASA navigation system,
and a NASA official, Raymond J. Amorose, said Thursday the Soviets
notified the National Aeronautics and Space Administration that
they had lost contact with the craft.
   Tass indicated that scientists were in normal contact with
Phobos 2, and said today it was 11.8 million miles from Earth.
   ``According to transmitted information, onboard systems and
instrumentation of the Phobos 2 station function smoothly,'' it
said.
   Regarding the Soviet space capsule, the state-run Soviet press
said both equipment problems and errors by the Soviet flight
commander, Vladimir Lyakhov, forced a postponement of the scheduled
Tuesday landing of the Soyuz TM-5 capsule. The spacecraft, also
carrying Afghanistan's first man in space, Ahad Abdul Mohmand,
landed safely Wednesday on its third attempt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880909-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 1120EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Thailand-Crash 7thLd-Writethru a0570 09-09 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thailand-Crash, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0570,0707</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Jetliner Crashed, 75 Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with details on nationality of
victims. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``Air Vietnam...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnamese jetliner trying to land
during a heavy storm crashed and exploded in a rice field near
Bangkok's airport today, killing 75 people and seriously injuring
six, officials said.
   The Soviet-made Tu-134 jet with 81 people aboard blew up after
hitting the field about four miles short of Don Muang International
Airport, said an air force spokesman, Sommot Sundaravej.
   The plane crashed three minutes before it was scheduled to land,
he said.
   India's ambassador to Vietnam, Arun Patwardhan, 48, was killed
along with his wife and son. Eight other Indians also died.
   A second secretary of the Japanese Embassy in Hanoi, Kiyokata
Ida, was also believed dead, said the Japanese Embassy in Bangkok.
The other Japanese passengers believed killed were two staffers of
the Tokyo headquarters of Mitsubishi Corp., Japan's largest trading
firm.
   Diplomats said two Frenchmen, two Swedes, one Briton and two
Finns also died.
   Air Vietnam Flight 831, which left Vietnam's capital of Hanoi at
10 a.m. (11 p.m. EDT), is frequently taken by foreign diplomats and
relief workers.
   The U.S. Embassy in Bangkok said no Americans were aboard the
plane.
   ``I heard an explosion louder than lightning,'' said Orn
Chuayklintes, a villager who witnessed the crash from his wooden
house nearby. ``It fell into the paddy field and a ball of fire
rolled for a kilometer (half mile).''
   Sommot said the dead included both Vietnamese and citizens of
other countries, but he did not have details.
   There was no word on what caused the crash. Both the cockpit and
flight recorders were retrieved in excellent condition, said Maj.
Gen. Sopol Savigamin, the regional police commander leading the
rescue effort.
   The cockpit recorder contains the conversation between the crew
and control tower and the other recorder contains flight data.
   The pilot lost contact with the Bangkok control tower at 11:26
a.m., and the plane soon disappeared from radar screens, said Group
Capt. Charoon Peetong, director general of the Airports Authority
of Thailand.
   The plane crashed 11 minutes later.
   Sopol said a total of 81 people, including six crew members,
were aboard. He said workers retrieved 75 bodies. Six people,
including a boy and a girl, were taken to Bhumibol Hospital with
serious injuries.
   Rescue workers pumped dry the roadside pond where the cockpit
and fuselage were lodged to retrieve bodies. Hundreds of police and
air force workers and volunteers hauled up bodies from the pond,
wrapping them in the thin beige-colored cloth customarily used for
corpses. A policeman posed for photographers holding up a severed
leg.
   The third major piece of wreckage, the tail section with the
airline's yellow star insignia, sat on the dirt road, muddied by
rains. More debris was scattered over a rice field on the other
side of the road.
   Scattered over the area were hundreds of pairs of earrings, a
shell necklace, toy plastic gun, tennis shoe, Indian passports, the
passports of two Polish students and more than 10 bags of
diplomatic mail for the Australian Embassy in Bangkok.
   The plane crashed in a sparsely populated, isolated area.
   A U.S. military team was to have taken the return flight to
Hanoi in the afternoon for talks on recently resumed efforts to
account for U.S. servicemen missing in the Vietnam War, U.S.
Embassy spokesman Ross Petzing said. There is no U.S. mission in
Hanoi.
   According to Jane's All The World's Aircraft, various versions
of the twin-engine Tu-134 jet seat 80 to 96 people. The Tu-134 is
Air Vietnam's mainstay aircraft, and Vietnamese officials have said
they would like to switch to newer planes but do not have the money.
   The last major air crash in Thailand was Aug. 31, 1987, when a
Thai Airways domestic airliner crashed into the sea off the
southern resort island of Phuket. All 83 people aboard died in the
crash of the Boeing 737. The accident was blamed on errors by the
pilot and control tower.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
