<DOCNO> AP880909-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 1124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0476 09-09 0818</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0476,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Dukakis Confused on Star Wars</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 13 grafs new with Bush comments today; pick up 6th graf
pvs bgng ``Meanwhile Bush...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKFORD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush today charged opponent Michael
Dukakis with shifting positions on military programs and said
``it's sometimes hard to keep up'' with the Democrat's line on
defense.
   ``Does he believe in defense against strategic missiles or
doesn't he?'' Bush asked in a speech to the Illinois Federation of
Republican Women.
   Dukakis in Louisville on Thursday told a news conference he
would consider deploying the Strategic Defense Initiative _ or Star
Wars _ if research showed it would work and if it were in the
national interest.
   It was the first time the Democrat had suggested any
circumstances under which he would support deployment of the Reagan
administration's space-shield proposal, designed to destroy
incoming Soviet missiles in space.
   ``His position on SDI, calling it a fantasy one day, something
he won't rule out the next ... suggests a confusion on basic
facts,'' Bush told his audience.
   He also questioned Dukakis' claims that he would modernize
land-based weapons if essential, while re-examining the MX and
Midgetman missiles.
   ``How do you modernize the land-based leg if you oppose the MX
and Midgetman?'' Bush asked.
   ``I've tried to be fair and accurate as to my opponent's
positions, but lately they seem to have been shifting so rapidly
it's sometimes hard to keep up,'' Bush said.
   Bush's sharp criticism comes a day after he accused Dukakis of
seeking to restrain the nuclear capability of the United States
when he advocated a nuclear freeze.
   While insisting he wasn't challenging Dukakis' patriotism, Bush
slammed the Democratic presidential nominee after overseeing the
destruction of two U.S. Pershing nuclear missile engines on
Thursday.
   The engines were destroyed under a U.S.-Soviet arms-reduction
pact the vice president claimed could not have been negotiated
under a Dukakis presidency.
   In his speech today to the GOP women's group, Bush said what he
witnessed at the Army ammunition plant in east Texas the day before
``was unforgettable.''
   ``These acts of destruction were acts of peace,'' he said. But,
he added: ``yesterday would not have been possible'' had Dukakis
been in office.
   Meanwhile, Bush said he was pleased with the agreement with the
Dukakis camp to have two presidential and one vice presidential
debates.
   ``It sounds very good. Got the right number,'' Bush told
reporters upon his airport arrival here late Thursday.
   The Bush campaign had held out for only two presidential
debates, while Dukakis forces had sought three or more.
   Bush said he believed the more modest schedule finally adopted
``will have widespread support of the American voters.''
   The missiles _ actually the solid-fuel rocket first stages _
were among 859 such missiles the United States has agreed to
destroy over the next three years under the agreement to eliminate
intermediate-range nuclear missiles. The Soviets agreed to destroy
1,752 under the pact and began the process last July.
   Bush, in a somber and nonpartisan address to a group of U.S.,
European and Soviet officials who witnessed the fiery destruction
of the rocket engines, called it ``a moment we will be able to tell
our children and grandchildren about.''
   ``This was the day we began to reverse the arms race, this was
the day we began destroying the weapons of destruction,'' Bush said
at the Longhorn Army Ammunition Plant in Karnack, Tex.
   But Bush quickly shed his non-political tone at a
convention-center rally a few hours later in nearby Tyler, Texas.
   Bush cited Dukakis's past support freeze on nuclear weapons,
asserting Dukakis had taken such a stand to keep the United States
from expanding its nuclear arsenal.
   ``He wanted to restrain us, not the Soviet Union,'' Bush said.
``Therein lies a big difference between George Bush and the
governor of Massachusetts.''
   ``I don't question his patriotism,'' Bush said. ``I question his
judgement.''
   ``I want to build on the record of peace through strength. And
it can't be done if we have a naive view of the Soviet Union,''
Bush said. Reminding audience that he was met with Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, Bush described the Soviet leader as ``tough.''
   ``We must not, and if I am elected I will not, make unilateral
concessions to Mr. Gorbachev or to the Soviet Union,'' he said.
   Bush also praised Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind., calling him ``my
young, vigorous running mate who understands defense.''
   However, Bush has not appeared with Quayle since right after the
GOP convention last month and aides said that there are currently
no plans for any joint appearances.
   After arriving in Rockford last night, Bush and his entourage
went unannounced to a local Italian restaurant, where he spent
about two hours eating and posing for snapshots. Afterwards, Bush
plunged into the crowd that had gathered outside, shaking hands and
lifting several toddlers into his arms.
</TEXT>
