<1ST_LINE>u w PM-CavazosHearing 1stLd-Writethru a0418 09-09 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cavazos Hearing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0418,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cavazos Vows to Continue Education Reforms</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with details from hearing.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lauro F. Cavazos promised today that as
education secretary he would continue the reforms he said were
started by outgoing Secretary William Bennett.
   ``In the last seven years we have arrested the decline in
American education, but as commendable as this effort has been, we
still have much to accomplish,'' Cavazos told a committee
considering his nomination.
   The Texas Tech University president, who if approved would
become the first Hispanic ever appointed to the Cabinet, credited
the Reagan administration with spearheading education reform by
creating the National Commission on Excellence in Education which
issued the report, ``A Nation at Risk.''
   ``Secretary (T.H.) Bell issued the warning, Secretary Bennett
took up the challenge and offered solutions, and I'm here to ensure
that educational reform proceeds and that educational excellence
once again returns to America,'' he said.
   Cavazos, the son of a foreman on the huge King Ranch of South
Texas, was praised by senators and congressmen today as a hands-on
educator, a consistent friend of education and an excellent choice
to fill the post being vacated by Bennett later this month.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, told the Senate Labor and Human
Resources Committee that Cavazos had ``gilt-edged credentials.''
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, called the nominee ``living proof the
American dream is alive and well in Texas and throughout the
nation.''
   Gramm said Cavazos would provide excellent leadership in
education, making education ``an engine for opportunity, prosperity
and growth for all Americans.''
   Committee Chairman Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said he
expects Cavazos' nomination to be voted on by the committee
sometime next week.
   Kennedy said he believes the administration has been
``profoundly hostile to the federal government's role in education.
They have relentlessly sought to slash federal education spending
and weaken the programs designed to help the most vulnerable
members of our society.''
   Before the hearing, Gramm said he didn't expect Cavazos'
nomination to be controversial.
   ``You're talking about the dean of a major medical school, the
president of a great university who has served this nation on
numerous boards and commissions around the world. He is clearly
loved by everybody that knows him. This (confirmation) is a
certainty,'' said Gramm.
   A Senate education subcommittee staff member added: ``I don't
anticipate he'll have any trouble. There's a very good chance it
will be unanimous.''
   The aide, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said a
strong committee vote likely would herald a quick and easy
confirmation in the full Senate, possibly next week.
   Cavazos would serve only until January when the next
administration takes over, unless the new president reappoints him
to the post.
   He was the first Hispanic to serve as president of Texas Tech.
He also serves as the president of its medical school, but is not a
medical doctor.
   A registered Democrat, Cavazos has opposed cuts in student
financial aid. He is described by colleagues as a skilled
administrator, a delegator and a consensus-builder.
   ``His leadership in education on a nationwide basis is well
known,'' Gramm said.
   Known informally as Larry, Cavazos is one of three brothers who
left the King Ranch to attend what was then Texas Technological
College.
   His brother, Bobby, was an All-American running back in football
who now has his own ranch, while the third brother, Dick, became a
four-star Army general.
   Cavazos has a bachelor's degree in zoology and a master's degree
in cytology _ the study of cells _ from Texas Tech and a 1954
doctorate in physiology from Iowa State University.
   He has been Texas Tech president since 1980, and seven of his 10
children have Texas Tech degrees.
</TEXT>
