<2ND_LINE>PM-Ferry Fire,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ferry Fire Forces Evacuation of 230 Passengers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HORTEN, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire broke out early today aboard a
Norwegian ferry sailing to Oslo, and all 230 passengers were safely
evacuated in lifeboats, the national news agency said.
   No major injuries were reported. The smoky blaze started in the
dining room of the Holger Danske ferry at about 4:50 a.m., but the
cause was not known.
   The ship was off the city of Horten when the fire occurred, the
NTB agency said. The vessel was heading for Oslo from the Danish
port of Fredrikshavn.
   The 42-member crew stayed on board during the evacuation, and
the fire was put out by 6 a.m., NTB said. The ship was towed into
Horten harbor for inspection.
   Seven lifeboats, some from other ferries, were used to bring the
passengers ashore. The seas were calm at the time.
   The Holger Danske usually carries Norwegians going to
Fredrikshavn to buy tax-free liquor, tobacco, cigarettes and other
goods on board and cheap Danish meat in Fredrikshavn.
   Ragnar Hagen, managing director of DA-NO Line, said the flames
damaged the pantry and restaurant on board the 3,500-ton ferry.
</TEXT>
