<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gibraltar-IRA     09-09 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gibraltar-IRA,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gibraltar Police Chief Confirms British Commandos Killed IRA Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Commissioner Joseph Canepa said today
that seven British commandos who shot to death three unarmed IRA
members in March belonged to the Special Air Services, an elite
military unit used to fight terrorism.
   Canepa also said police passed up several chances to arrest the
IRA members before they were shot. He testified on the fourth day
of an inquest on the shootings by Coroner Feliz Pizzarello and an
11-member jury.
   The Irish Republican Army has acknowledged the three _ Sean
Savage, 24, Mairead Farrell, 31, and Daniel McCann, 30 _ were IRA
members on active service when killed by soldiers in this British
colony March 6.
   Under cross-examination by Patrick McGrory, the attorney for the
families, Canepa said the seven soldiers involved in the shootings
belonged to the SAS.
   Critics of British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher have accused
her government of enforcing an unofficial ``shoot-to-kill'' policy
against IRA members believed to be on attack missions against
British troops.
   The inquest, which began Tuesday and has no power of
prosecution, is to determine whether the SAS action was lawful.
   If the jury determines the killings were unlawful, the attorney
general is expected to return criminal indictments.
   Asked by McGrory why Savage was not arrested when he parked a
car near an assembly hall on the day of the shootings, Canepa said
authorities expected other members of the IRA unit to come into
Gibraltar and preferred to arrest them all at the same time.
   Canepa said the shooting took place after a police-military
advisory group concluded that the car contained a bomb.
   The outlawed IRA is fighting to drive the British out of
Northern Ireland and unite the province with the Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
