<DOCNO> AP880909-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 1201EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Argentina-Strike     09-09 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Argentina-Strike,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trains Halted; No-Shows at Government Offices; Huge Rally Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest labor
federation staged an eight-hour strike today that interrupted
public transportation and stopped thousands of people from getting
to work.
   The 3.5-million member General Labor Confederation also
organized a huge rally in the plaza outside Government House.
   The strike _ the 12th since President Raul Alfonsin took office
in December 1983 _ was called to protest the economic policies of
the government.
   ``We want people to publicly show their desire for a change,
their repudiation of the selling off of national assets, and their
rejection of using our funds for interest payments'' on the foreign
debt, the confederation's general-secretary, Saul Ubaldini, said
Thursday.
   The strike and rally were endorsed by the opposition Peronist
and Communist political parties, and a variety of business and
labor groups.
   Supporters of Alfonsin's Radical Civic Union have said the
strike is a ploy to undermine an anti-inflation plan implemented
last month and coalesce support for Peronist presidential candidate
Carlos Menem in the elections in May.
   The economic plan _ Alfonsin's third in less than five years _
devalued the austral, cut government spending, implemented
voluntary wage and price controls and lifted restrictions on some
imports.
   The goal was to reduce inflation that amounted to a combined
53.2 percent in July and August, and to secure new loans from the
International Monetary Fund and commercial banks to help repay
interest on Argentina's $56 billion foreign debt. Alfonsin predicts
inflation this month will be below 10 percent.
   A component of Alfonsin's general economic plan is the
privatization of some of the dozens of state companies, including
the phone company, the national carrier Aerolineas Argentinas and
the national shipping line.
   Unions representing workers at the companies generally oppose
privatization, fearing that jobs will be cut.
   The opposition Peronist Party, closely tied to the unions, has
raised obstacles in Congress to the sale of state-owned companies.
   Interest on Argentina's foreign debt amounts to about $4.6
billion this year. It is a political as well as economic burden to
repay, given peoples' clamor for more public services at lower
costs.
   Early today, train signalmen went on their own 24-hour strike
that forced thousands of suburban commuters to drive to work or
stay home. City buses were to go on strike beginning at noon.
   Unions in the provinces outside the capital of Buenos Aires also
called 24-hour strikes.
   The General Labor Confederation called for an eight-hour strike
so people would come to work as usual, walk off the job at noon,
attend the rally, and be able to take public transportation home
beginning at 8 p.m.
   Union supporters plastered the walls of the capital with posters
saying, ``Don't Mess With the People.''
   Private businesses _ bakeries, offices, hardware and department
stores _ opened as usual today. They have generally ignored the
past several strikes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
