<HEAD>Students Injured When High School Bleachers Collapse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with comment from administrator, officials
saying injuries did not appear to be life threatening. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>POMFRET, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gymnasium bleachers collapsed at a high
school this morning during an assembly, injuring as many as 52
people, authorities said.
   Hospital officials said none of the injuries appeared to be life
threatening.
   The steel bleachers gave way at 8:11 a.m. at Maurice J.
McDonough High School, said Charles County police Lt. David
Gladwell. The students were all 11th graders, school officials said.
   Injuries ranged from bumps and bruises to broken legs and ankles
and some suspected spinal injuries, said county Fire Chief Ken
Chaplin.
   Tony DeStefano, a spokesman for the Prince George's County Fire
Department, said Charles County officials told him they had 25
people in need of emergency room treatment and 27 more who needed
medical examinations.
   ``The staff and students have been absolutely wonderful. They
reacted like clockwork,'' said Linda Dent-Brown, administrative
assistant to the superintendent at the county Board of Education.
``There was no hysteria. They're comforting each other and helping
each other.''
   Mary S. Haag, spokeswoman for Physicians Memorial Hospital in La
Plata, said 29 people arrived there, all in stable condition.
   Four students were taken by helicopter to Prince George's
Hospital Center and admitted in good condition, hospital
spokeswoman Carol Cox said. Some complained of back pain and could
have broken bones, she said.
   ``They're all in very good condition,'' she said. ``They're all
awake and alert and talking.''
   Twelve others with minor injuries were taken to a hospital in
Clinton, Mrs. Haag said.
   Pomfret is about 80 miles south of Baltimore. Classes began
Sept. 1.
