<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh-Flood     09-09 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh-Flood,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospitals Crowded by Flood-related Illnesses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patients with flood-related diseases
clog the hospitals of Dhaka, and millions of gallons of raw sewage
is being poured into stagnant waters where children swim and people
wade.
   Water levels in major rivers continued falling Friday but
remained far above flood stage, thwarting relief efforts. The
floods have covered three-quarters of Bangladesh, and up to
one-fourth of its 110 million people are homeless.
   Helicopters can land only in dry areas, and even short distances
are difficult by boat. As a foreign diplomat put it in one case:
``It's only 30 miles by crow, but you can't get there by crow.''
   Dhaka newspapers reported 101 more deaths in 24 hours and put
the total at 1,402. The government count remained at 609 and is
considered far too low.
   The government health center said 135,537 diarrhea cases have
been reported nationwide, including at least 8,254 among Dhaka's 6
million people.
   Official statistics put the death toll from diarrhea at 93
across the country, but reports of illness and death come only from
areas that can communicate with the capital.
   Health officials estimated 40 million gallons of raw sewage a
day was being dumped into stagnating flood waters where children
swim for fun and adults wade to food markets and relief centers.
   Doctors at the International Center for Diarrheal Disease
Control said the number of patients admitted has more than doubled
since Dhaka was flooded two weeks ago.
   They said 376 patients, most of them babies and small children,
were admitted to the hospital in the previous 24 hours compared
with an average 155 a day during all of August. Floods began in
June with the monsoon season, abated, then became devastating late
last month.
   Cots with green plastic sheets filled the wards and halls of the
center, which is financed by foreign donors.
   Rajia Begum sat cross-legged on a cot tending her 9-day-old son,
not yet named. The whites of her eyes were yellow with jaundice,
which Dr. M.D. Abdus Salam said probably was caused by hepatitis.
   She brought her wan infant to the hospital three days ago, after
neighbors with a boat rescued them from her flooded home.
   Abdus Salam, chief physician at the hospital, said the baby's
chances of survival were good because he received medical attention
in time.
   The diarrhea center pioneered the manufacture of a simple saline
rehydration solution in Bangladesh, and in normal times supplies it
to other hospitals. Abdus Salam said Friday, however, that the lab
now works around the clock just to supply the center's own needs.
   At least two large cargo planes brought in relief supplies
Friday, but the problem still was how to get the material to people
marooned in spots where even helicopters cannot land. Normal
operations resumed Thursday at the Dhaka airport, which was closed
to all but small aircraft for six days.
   Among the places in desperate need was the Rupganj area 20 miles
south of Dhaka. The English-language Bangladesh Observer said
50,000 people were stranded there, ``fighting a grim battle for
their survival as no relief material has reached them yet.''
   Such relatively short distances are difficult to cover by boat
because a craft large enough to carry a useful amount of relief
goods must follow rivers with water deep enough to support it.
   The diplomat who said ``you can't get there by crow'' was
recounting the plight of a flooded hospital whose nurses and
doctors put their patients in boats. ``A speed boat would take 2{
hours'' to reach the hospital, he said, ``but a relief launch will
take all day.''
</TEXT>
