<HEAD>Oranges Crushed Before Football Game</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocates for the hungry didn't see the
humor in a stunt in which a 12-ton steamroller crushed 1,460
oranges Friday as a symbol of what fans hope will happen at the
Ohio State football opener.
   Radio station WBNS-AM sponsored the event because the Ohio State
University Buckeyes play the Syracuse University Orangemen here
Saturday. The station is at 1460 on the radio dial.
   There were no protesters among the 20 people watching the stunt,
but the station received a couple of calls from critics, and people
who provide food for the hungry expressed concern.
   ``Any waste of food to us is wasting a valuable resource,'' Matt
Habash of the Mid-Ohio Food Bank, said.
   Sue Stanton, WBNS promotions director, said pulp and rind
salvaged from the crushing would be donated to feed animals at the
Columbus Zoo. The oranges were either green or old and not fit for
people to eat, she said.
   ``We're really not wasting any food,'' she said. ``We don't
encourage wasting of food by anyone.''
   Ms. Stanton said the event was in the spirit of football, and
``we're very sorry anybody takes it in any other light or manner.''
   Another radio station, WSNY, held a contest Friday in which nine
people tried to impress judges with the most unusual way to crush
an orange.
