<2ND_LINE>PM-Tropical Weather, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0645,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hurricane Bears Down on Gulf Coast</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Florence reaching hurricane strength.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical Storm Florence grew into a hurricane today
and headed for the Gulf Coast between Louisiana and the Florida
Panhandle with wind of 80 mph, the National Hurricane Center said.
   The storm was expected to hit land this evening with wind up to
100 mph. Gusts of 50 mph buffeted the Louisiana coast by early
afternoon.
   Up to 10 inches of rain were forecast in southern Lousiana,
Mississippi and Alabama and the Florida Panhandle, and hurricane
warnings were posted from Cameron, La., to Pensacola.
   Maximum sustained winds near the storm's center were 80 mph at 2
p.m. EDT, well over the 74 mph threshhold at which a tropical storm
becomes a hurricane, said Bob Sheets, director of the hurricane
center.
   Florence is the sixth storm and the second hurricane of the 1988
Atlantic hurricane season.
   At 2 p.m., Florence was near latitude 27.5 north, longitude 89.2
west, or about 180 miles south of New Orleans. It was moving north
at near 15 mph.
   If the storm maintains its course, it will probably reach land
in the Mississippi River Delta area, southeast of New Orleans,
according to the storm center. But forecasters warned that the
course was unpredictable.
   Mayor Andy Valens of Grand Isle, La., a town of 2,000 on a
barrier island, ordered residents to evacuate. Grand Isle State
Park, a camping area, was closed. ``If they don't move out, they
will be arrested,'' said Valens.
   New Orleans, which is almost surrounded by the Mississippi River
and Lakes Pontchartrain and Borgne, prepared for an onslaught of
wind and rain.
   ``We've got full crews out closing flood gates along the
industrial canal and the lakefront,'' said Levee Board spokesman
Jean LaPlace.
   Thousands of oil workers on offshore rigs were ordered ashore.
``Everything off the coast of Louisiana has been or will be
evacuated,'' said Chevron spokeswoman Julia Freeman.
   Tropical storm warnings of winds to 50 mph were posted from east
of Pensacola to Apalachicola, Fla., and a hurricane watch _ which
is less serious than a warning and advises residents that a
hurricane is possible _ was in effect from Cameron west to Port
Arthur, Texas.
   Near where the storm hits, tides could be up to 9 feet above
normal, the weather service said. Tides from Pensacola westward to
Morgan City, La., were expected to be 3 to 5 feet above normal
today.
</TEXT>
