<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880909-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 2015EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SilverFox     09-09 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Silver Fox,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Silver-Haired Con-Man Woos, Steals From Lonely Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tall, silver-haired man who
drives a new Lincoln Town Car and flashes a wallet full of cash has
been wooing lonely older women around Florida, then making off with
their money, cars and jewels.
   ``This guy is slick,'' said Palm Beach County Sheriff's
Detective Dave Hoyt. ``He could charm the socks off a dead guy.''
   Police say Artie Frankford, alias James Ferguson, is a
smooth-talking former condominium maintenance man in his middle 60s
to early 70s. Arrest warrants against him date back over a decade.
   The latest victim, a 61-year-old widow from suburban North Palm
Beach, told police she let him move in for a month, and came home
one day to find $4,000 worth of jewelry missing.
   ``He was unbelievably smooth,'' she said Thursday. ``It was
wining, dining, dancing and trips. He mixed with the family, and he
was a very giving guy who always paid for things. You would never
have known.''
   Frankford told the woman he was a federal government retiree who
just returned from 28 years in Alaska, which explained his lack of
friends.
   ``My kids said he was too good to be true, and he was,'' said
the woman, who asked not to be indentified.
   Frankford disappeared a day before they were to start a
three-week vacation in Tennessee and the Carolinas, she said.
   ``This woman's husband died four years ago, and she's a really
nice lady,'' Hoyt said. ``He met her at a church singles dance
where he came across as a worldly guy who's been around.''
   Hoyt believes other women may be too embarrassed to come
forward. Manya Joyce of North Palm Beach, director of the U.S.
Senior Athletic Games in the county, shares that belief.
   ``Late last fall I got a call from him, and he said he wanted to
volunteer to help the games,'' Joyce said. ``So I introduced him to
the people I was working with. And one day he said he had to go
back to Tampa.''
   But then from April through July, she got calls from three
distraught women trying to find him because of property he had
taken, they said. He had told them he was vice president of the
Senior Athletic Games, Joyce said.
   ``They were pretty upset, so I told them to go to law
enforcement,'' she said. ``These people take him in. That's the sad
part.''
   Police agencies across the state on the Gulf Coast also are
seeking Frankford. The earliest arrest warrant dates to February
1979. A Sarasota socialite told police that Frankford, then known
as James Ferguson, met her at a church function, moved in and then
stole her Mercedes-Benz.
   Sarasota Detective Stanton Hayes said a man matching Ferguson's
description later moved to Lakeland and married a prominent woman.
   ``Then he left with about everything she had,'' Hayes said.
   Largo detective Jack Pressmar said an arrest warrant was issued
for Ferguson about 10 years ago when he was a condominium
maintenance man.
   ``He house-sat for a couple, and when they came back, their
silver and crystal sets were gone,'' the detective said. ``The
people were just flabbergasted. He's got his trade down pat.''
   ``This guy is always about two steps ahead of us,'' Hayes said.
``He's very low-profile, he keeps disappearing, and he does all the
right things. Why shouldn't they trust him?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
