<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CheckWoes     09-09 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Check Woes,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bad Checks Cost Innocent Man Dearly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Stasiowski is free of a two-year
nightmare that began when a box of checks was stolen from him.
   After 10 trips to court, 19 days in jail, loss of his
$30,000-a-year job and his girlfriend, he was exonerated Thursday.
   In September 1986, a thief wrote thousands of dollars in bad
checks at supermarkets and convenience stores. Stasiowski's lawyer
believes a box of 250 checks was stolen almost immediately after
they arrived at the victim's address.
   Stasiowski, a 29-year-old apartment maintenance supervisor,
decided to open a new bank account at Benjamin Franklin Savings
when he changed jobs and addresses. He made a $1,100 deposit and
ordered checks printed with his name, new address and driver's
license number.
   ``All of a sudden I was receiving 10 or 15 insufficient-funds
notices a day in my mailbox,'' Stasiowski said.
   Bank officials didn't believe his story. When a policeman
stopped him for a traffic violation in January and learned arrest
warrants had been issued, Stasiowski was put in jail for 19 days.
   During that time, his apartment was burglarized and $1,000 worth
of electronics gear was stolen. He was fired from his job. His
girlfriend, who works for a bank, decided to end their relationship.
   Finally, on Thursday, visiting state District Judge E.W.
Patterson dismissed theft-by-check charges at the urging of
prosecutor Joan Huffman.
   ``According to the handwriting experts, he didn't write the
checks,'' Ms. Huffman said.
   Ms. Huffman said Stasiowski's problems might have ended sooner
had he gone to his bank and executed a forgery affidavit, swearing
he had never received the checks mailed to him.
</TEXT>
