<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     09-09 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Battle Riot Police with Firebombs and Rocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of radical students shouting
slogans against the government and Olympic games hurled firebombs
and rocks at riot police Friday.
   The battle began at Yonsei University in western Seoul when
police stopped about 600 students from marching off the campus to
protest the arrest Thursday of the head of the student association.
He was charged with leading an anti-Olympic campaign.
   Students attacked about 1,000 riot officers, who responded by
firing tear gas grenades and flinging rocks back at the protesters.
   Thousands of students remained indifferent inside the campus
during the melee along the fences, which lasted about half an hour.
At least five students were seen bleeding, hit in the face by
stones. No arrests were reported.
   ``Oppose dictatorial Olympics suppressing democratic forces!''
protesters shouted.
   Radicals claim the government is using the Olympics, scheduled
for Sept. 17-Oct. 2 in Seoul, to perpetuate division of the Korean
Peninsula and what they describe as dictatorship.
   They say the games heighten the risk of war with communist North
Korea, which decided to boycott them after its demand to be co-host
was rejected.
   The radical students are a small, powerful minority on campus
but lack public support.
   Authorities ordered a crackdown Friday leaflets denouncing the
Olympics and demanding they be shared with North Korea.
   Police said security guards arrested a student volunteer at the
main Olympic stadium Thursday who was caught trying to bring in
about 100 of the leaflets.
   Special squads stand ready to cover campuses in Seoul and
security forces are posted throughout Olympic venues in case of
terrorism.
   President Kim Il Sung of North Korea said in a speech marking
his nation's 40th anniversary Friday he would welcome a visit by a
South Korean delegation to discuss national reunification.
   Many officials in Seoul believe his proposal responded to an
offer Aug. 15 by President Roh Tae-woo of South Korea to improve
relations with the North. Roh said he is willing to meet Kim ``at
any time, any place, without any condition'' to discuss all pending
issues.
   South Korean reaction to Kim's remarks was cautious. ``We need
time to scrutinize the proposal,'' one senior government official
said privately.
   A summit would be the first between the heads of the two Korean
states since partition at the end of World War II.
   If a South Korean delegation visits Pyongyang, Kim said, its
sole purpose should be to discuss his long-standing ``confederate
system'' of unification.
   That calls for the two Koreas to retain their own political
structures while operating as one nation internationally. South
Korea calls it an attempt to unify the peninsula under a communist
government.
</TEXT>
