<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-DeathPenalty     09-09 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Death Penalty,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Calls Wounded Drug Agent, Pushes Capital Punishment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs for item slugged AM-Reagan-Courts in AM-News Advisory.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan made a telephone call to a
drug enforcement agent seriously wounded in the line of duty Friday
and said the call makes him want to take on congressmen opposed to
the death penalty in drug cases.
   Reagan described his telephone call to Bruce Travis, a special
agent with the Drug Enforcement Administration who was shot during
a drug arrest in New York City Tuesday night, as he ended a speech
to the Federalist Society, a lawyers' organization.
   Reagan told the audience he had just received word of the
shooting. He said the agent ``was sitting in a car; he was actually
providing protection to a home where the people in the home had
been threatened, their lives threatened, because of their work
against drugs.''
   ``Just before coming over, I made a telephone call to the
hospital,'' he said.
   The president said Travis was shot in the head and the bullet
``came out from the forehead, very close to the eye.''
   ``The voice on the phone turned out to be his father's, because
he cannot speak,'' the president said. ``It will probably be a year
of continuous surgery before he is able to come back among us.''
   Reagan said the agent's father, identified by the White House as
Buddy Travis, ``told me his son couldn't speak, but could hear. So
he said, `I'll hold the phone to his ear and when you hear the
tapping, that means he is on and listening.'
   ``So I was able to tell him of our pride in him, how much we
appreciated his sacrifice and how much he would be in our prayers.''
   Then, the president said, he said goodby and the wounded agent
tapped on the telephone to show he had heard.
   ``Well, in this morning's paper, I had read some of the
statements by the opposition in Congress to the death penalty
amendment that was passed yesterday (expressing) sheer horror at
the idea that we should be taking someone's life away in connection
with drugs,'' Reagan said.
   ``I have been thinking about that ever since this telephone
call,'' he said. ``I would like to engage some of them in personal
conversation. ``In fact, I'll go out of my way to do it.''
   The House approved by a vote of 299-111 on Thursday an
administration-backed amendment to an omnibus drug bill that calls
for a federal death penalty for persons who kill in the course of a
drug-related felony. Opponents in the Senate have said they may
stage a filibuster if a similar amendment is proposed there.
   During the House debate, Rep. Charles B. Rangel, D-N.Y.,
chairman of the House select committee on narcotics, opposed the
amendment, saying, ``The bums who are out there every day dealing
in drugs, they have no fear of death.''
   Rep. William Clay, D-Mo., also opposing the death penalty,
asked, ``How can you kill people who kill people to teach people
who kill people that killing people is wrong?''
   Reagan, in his speech, said his administration hired more than
4,000 new drug enforcement agents and prosecutors with Vice
President George Bush overseeing a program to coordinate federal,
state and local efforts to combat drug trafficking.
   ``But we're not satisfied,'' he said. ``We're proposing to step
up the pressure.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
