<DOCNO> AP880909-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 2058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EthnicGermans     09-09 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethnic Germans,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germany Seeking Solutions For Record Ethnic German Influx</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of ethnic Germans from
eastern Europe are coming to West Germany, and state officials are
seeking ways to cope with the burden on schools, housing and social
services.
   Several state leaders met Friday with federal officials to
discuss the crisis. They are demanding the government pay a larger
share of the added costs.
   More than 200,000 people, almost all of them ethnic Germans, are
expected to arrive in West Germany this year from the Soviet Union,
Poland and other east European countries. The same number is
expected next year.
   Although German by heritage, many do not speak the German
language.
   Government facilities have long since overflowed, and many
newcomers are housed in gymnasiums and other makeshift quarters.
   The influx is in large part the result of a change of policy in
many East bloc countries. Although the Bonn government has worked
for years to gain permission for ethnic Germans to emigrate, it was
not prepared for the response.
   ``We've got to get these people out of gymnasiums,'' Herbert
Schnoor, interior minister for North Rhein Westfalia state, told
reporters at a press conference in Bonn.
   Schnoor was among the state officials who met with government
leaders Friday.
   The federal government has proposed a $450 million program to
build 30,000 new apartments. State leaders are demanding a $1.9
billion program to build 54,000 new apartments.
   ``These people are being found housing, but not in the manner we
would like,'' Schnoor said.
   He said the government must provide an additional $405 million
in emergency help.
   ``Without this money, we can't begin to solve the problem,''
Schnoor said.
   Schnoor said Chancellor Helmut Kohl was receptive to the
suggestions and that he made it clear that solutions ``would not
break down because of financial disputes.''
   The majority of the ethnic Germans are from Poland and the
Soviet Union, government officials said. The Soviet Union alone has
granted exit visas to 15,715 ethnic Germans this year.
   Bavarian Interior Minister Max Streibl said the federal
government should pay two-thirds of the costs, leaving the states
to pay the final third.
   Three government crisis groups have been formed, and the
Interior Ministry is developing an overall program in conjunction
with the Housing Ministry. The Chancellor's Office is working on a
program of language instruction and job placement for the
immigrants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880909-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 2100EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Family     09-09 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Family,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Seeks To Build Family Cohesiveness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, seeking a greater federal
role in promoting the family institution, ordered departments and
agencies Friday to report quickly on ways the government can better
protect men, women, children and the unborn.
   Following up on his 1986 State of the Union pledge to thoroughly
analyze the state of families in America, Reagan accepted a series
of recommendations by his White House Office of Policy Development
on how to build family cohesiveness.
   Several of the new initiatives would be focused on the drug
abuse problem, and Reagan embraced a call for making the receipt of
federal funds contingent on the willingness of educational and
other institutions to promote drug-free environments.
   He also backed a proposal to find safeguards designed to protect
the newborn and the unborn against possible exploitation in medical
research experimentation and organ transplantation.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said no final decisions
had been made on a possible executive order to ban the use of
tissue from intentionally aborted fetuses.
   He labeled as ``premature'' news accounts to that such decisions
had been made.
   Reagan's directive to several departments and agencies was aimed
at implementing, among other things, these policy changes:
   _Ensure that family violence ``be treated by law enforcement
agencies as a criminal law violation, not primarily a social
service problem.''
   _Require that legislation being considered by either the House
or the Senate be accompanied by a ``family impact'' statement.
   _Make the receipt of federal grant funds for education and other
purposes contingent on an institution's demonstrated ability to
move toward creation of a drug-free environment.
   _Create new federal initiatives, particularly within the
Agriculture Department, to push the use of housing vouchers to
improve housing opportunities in rural America.
   _Seek to have federal human sexuality and family planning
educational and informational materials promote sexual abstinence
among young people and to prevent the use of federal money for the
distribution of contraceptives in schools without parental
permission.
   _Have the Department of Housing and Urban Development find a way
to ``substantially increase resident management and ownership of
public housing projects.''
   _Develop legislative proposals requiring mandatory minimum
sentences for those who sell and distribute drugs to minors and
those who use adolescents in the trafficking of drugs.
   _Reassess how current tax laws affect the institution of the
family.
   The White House report voiced reservations about a push by
Congress to have the federal government play a larger role in
supporting and financing day care centers.
   ``Many proposals currently pending in Congress would subsidize
only daycare centers but would provide no assistance for families
who choose other child care options such as an extended family
member or neighbor,'' it said.
   Reagan instructed the various departments and agencies to report
back to him no later than December, one month before he leaves
office.
   Fitzwater acknowledged that the Reagan family initiatives were
coming late in the administration but said many could be achieved
by executive orders and actions rather than through congressional
legislation.
   The move to protect newborns and unborns against medical
experimentation was among the most controversial of the initiatives
laid out in the report on families.
   The administration moved to prohibit the use of tissue from
intentionally aborted fetuses in research before a special National
Institutes of Health advisory committee meets on this matter Sept.
14 and 15.
   Gary L. Bauer, Reagan's assistant for policy development and
principal author of the report on families, told Health and Human
Services Secretary Otis R. Bowen he wanted the secretary's comments
on a proposed executive order quickly.
   A copy of Bauer's memo, dated Sept. 2, along with a copy of a
draft presidential executive order that Reagan would sign, was
obtained Thursday by The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
