<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Quayle     09-09 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Gets Skeptical Reception From Ohio Steelworkers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MASSILLON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle got a polite but skeptical
reception from largely pro-Democratic steelworkers Friday at a
factory where the Republican vice presidential nominee touted his
support for job training and curbs on foreign steel imports.
   His motorcade whizzed past about 150 union demonstrators who
chanted ``Go Home'' at an entrance to the Mercury Stainless Inc.
plant, which he toured wearing a hard hat.
   Other protesters carried placards reading ``Open Season on
Quayle'' and ``I Toured Nam, Not Indiana,'' a reference to Quayle's
service in the Indiana National Guard during the Vietnam War.
   The Indiana senator told the workers, many of whom stood
silently wearing Dukakis-Bentsen T-shirts, that he had fought to
protect American steelworkers against foreign imports. He also said
the Job Partnership Training Act he had cosponsored in the Senate
had helped their plant when it emerged from bankruptcy.
   He later told a Canton, Ohio, Rotary Club luncheon that 88,000
people had received job training under the law, and that 62 percent
had found work.
   Some of the Mercury demonstrators joined several hundred
supporters of Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis who picketed the
luncheon site.
   ``You are to be congratuled,'' Quayle told the Mercury
employees, who applauded politely. ``You are a success story and
you did it yourself. You did it through partnership, a partnership
of labor and management.''
   The plant was closed because of bankruptcy in February 1985,
shortly after the Justice Department ordered it sold to facilitate
the merger of LTD and Republic Steel. Mercury then bought the plant
and reopened it in October 1986.
   Plant vice president Rick Harbert said 193 workers had been
trained under the law, using $191,000 in federal funds.
   Quayle took credit for lobbying President Reagan to support
so-called voluntary restraint agreements under which foreign steel
imports are restricted.
   He said he had preferred import quota legislation, which Reagan
didn't like, but that the restraint agreements ``did offer some
relief.''
   ``I wasn't afraid to co-sponsor that (quota) bill,'' he said.
``I wasn't afraid to stand up for the steelworkers of Indiana or
the steelworkers of Ohio or the steelworkers of America because we
said `enough is enough'.''
   Though silent during Quayle's speech, some Mercury employees
were not reticent about expressing their opinions to reporters.
   ``Hogwash. We don't buy it,'' said plant electrician Mike
McElfresh after Quayle spoke.
   Others said Quayle and GOP presidential nominee George Bush
would have trouble justifying Quayle's vigorous opposition to
legislation requiring 60 days' advance notice of mass layoffs or
plant closings, which Reagan vetoed in its original form.
   ``They've come to the wrong place,'' fumed machinery operator
John Ledrich, who criticized Quayle for his position on the
plant-closings bill. But Ledrich said Mercury management had asked
Dukakis supporters to be polite to Quayle and ``make him feel at
home.''
   Said mechanic Brian Reamy: ``It takes a lot of courage to come
in here in the middle of a highly unionized place.''
   Quayle adviser Jim Cicconi said he was pleased with the
candidate's performance in Massillon. He said that at Quayle's
pre-speech meeting with plant officials and union leaders, ``we
were told he would get more boos than cheers.''
</TEXT>
