<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MudSlide     09-09 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mud Slide,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Fear More Mud Slides After 76 Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT MORESBY, Papua New Guinea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chunk of a mountain
nearly two miles wide that collapsed and killed 76 people has
created a dam across two swollen rivers, and floods could hit
nearby villages, officials said Friday.
   Authorities evacuated hundreds of people after the mud slide
Tuesday, which swept away five villages.
   John Giheno, the minister for state, said an unknown number of
people were still missing. Officials said the death toll would have
been higher if children had not been at school when the slide hit.
   National Broadcasting Radio said geologists expect more
landslides that could lead to a higher death toll in remote Morobe
Province, about 185 miles north of Port Moresby, the capital.
   Local radio reports said Tuesday's mud slide sent millions of
tons of mud and debris into two valleys and created an artifical
dam across two flooded rivers. The water buildup is threatening
more villages, and army engineers joined rescue workers in trying
to release the flood waters, the radio said.
   Officials were trying to resettle more than 600 people left
homeless, and crosses were erected to mark the site as an official
burial ground, the radio said.
   The Australian Associated Press said the slide appeared caused
by volcanic activity, not heavy rains. The news agency said the
debris filled the valleys to a depth of 500 feet and covered an
estimated nine square miles.
   It said the body of a young woman was recovered shortly after
the landslide while a man was pulled alive from the dirt by his
wife, who watched two of their children disappear.
   The villages are about 4,950 feet above sea level. Houses in the
area are mainly flimsy traditional grass-thatched structures built
on stilts. Villagers exist by raising pigs and farming sweet
potatoes.
   The AAP reported that relief supplies were arriving in the area,
and a national disaster relief committee appealed for clothing,
blankets and food for the victims.
   Two Royal Australian Air Force planes were standing by to
airlift supplies to Lae, the nearest town, officials said.
   Papua New Guinea, north of Australia, has a mainly Melanesian
population of 3.3 million.
</TEXT>
