<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Floods     09-09 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Floods,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>58 Dead, 300,000 Stranded In Floods In Southern China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A week of rains in southern China has left 58
people dead, 505 injured and about 300,000 residents stranded, the
official Xinhua News Agency said Friday.
   It was the first official word of casualties in the flooding,
which followed heavy rains in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region
that borders Vietnam. The report said the floods have caused about
$250 million in damage.
   The deaths bring to 1,464 the official count of people killed in
flooding in China this summer, the rainy season in much of the
country.
   The toll is believed to be the highest since 1981, when floods
in southwest China killed 3,000 people.
   Xinhua said the Guangxi Zhuang government has set aside $2.7
million to rebuild damaged transportation, communications and power
stations. But shortages of building materials were hampering the
work.
   About 300,000 people were stranded by the flooding of the
Hongshui and Liujiang rivers or were forced to evacuate their
homes, Xinhua said.
   Nearly 3 million acres of cropland, 250,000 houses, and hundreds
of factories and schools were flooded, it said.
   Previous Xinhua reports on the flooding said it was the worst in
the region since 1949.
</TEXT>
