<1ST_LINE>u w AM-MedicaidAbortions     09-09 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medicaid Abortions,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Prolongs Impasse Over Social Spending Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Friday refused to go along with a
Senate expansion of Medicaid to cover abortions for rape and incest
victims, prolonging an impasse over a $140 billion social spending
bill.
   The vote, after several hours of impassioned debate, was 216-166.
   House and Senate negotiators came to agreement on every aspect
of the massive Labor, Education and Health and Human Services
spending bill except the abortion section.
   The controversy stems from Senate approval on July 27 of an
amendment permitting Medicaid funding in cases of promptly reported
rape or incest. States would still have the option of barring
payments for all abortions except those necessary to save a woman's
life.
   It was the first time either chamber had voted to liberalize
Medicaid abortion eligibility since 1981. Existing law permits
federal Medicaid money to be spent on abortions only where the life
of the mother is endangered.
   President Reagan is threatening to veto the entire
appropriations bill over the abortion provision, putting the Senate
under enormous pressure to surrender to the House and retain
existing law.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said the Senate
could take up the spending bill and the abortion amendment as early
as Monday.
   Much of the House debate reflected the conflicting bedrock
beliefs of the members. Some argued for compassionate and humane
treatment of women victimized by brutal crimes; others focused on
the welfare of the fetus.
   ``You can't avoid injustice in a rape situation. You can't avoid
injustice in an incest situation. But why compound the injustice by
putting on top of it exterminating an innocent human life?'' asked
Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., author of the existing Medicaid abortion
policy.
   ``Don't make us a part of that double tragedy,'' Hyde said.
``Out of great, great tragedy, some good can come.''
   Hyde allies also said medical procedures are available to
prevent conception after rapes or incest, and contended the
proposed exceptions would turn women into liars in their efforts to
secure government-funded abortions.
   Proponents of the expanded eligibility said it was only fair to
give a poor woman the same medical choices available to a woman
with money.
   ``All this amendment says is that ... she, not I, not you,
should be able to make that choice... without regard to whether she
is rich or poor, if her state allows that choice,'' said Rep. David
Obey, D-Wis.
   Kate Michaelman, president of the National Abortion Rights
Action League, issued a statement that assumed the Senate would
give in to the House next week. ``We are disappointed but not
defeated,'' she said. ``We shall redouble our efforts with the new
Congress and the new administration and we'll try again.''
   Before embarking on the abortion debate, the House voted 335-60
to approve the other portions of the $140 billion, fiscal 1989
spending bill for the three federal agencies.
   The bill includes, among other things, $1.2 billion for AIDS
research, treatment, prevention and education; $4.3 billion in
education grants for disadvantaged students; $5.5 billion in
college student financial assistance, and $3.7 billion for the Job
Training Partnership Act.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
