<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Iraq     09-09 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Iraq,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq to Consider Impartial Inquiry Into Chemical Weapons Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This includes material from AM-Senate-Kurds for those
desiring one story</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Iraqi diplomat, again rejecting U.S.
charges his country attacked Kurdish guerrillas with chemical
weapons, offered Friday to consider an impartial inquiry into the
allegations.
   But the State Department showed no immediate interest in the
offer. Spokesman Charles E. Redman insisted that Iraq issue a
declaration disavowing the use of chemical weapons in the future.
   And on Capitol Hill, the Senate gave swift voice-vote approval
to a bill imposing stiff economic sanctions on the Arab country.
``The Iraqi army is waging a campaign against the Kurdish
population that can only be described as genocide,'' said the
measure's sponsor, Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I.
   Sadoon Hamadi, minister of state for foreign affairs, said
observers would not be permitted in the northern border area of
Iraq, where many of the Kurds live, so long as hostilities
persisted there.
   But, he said, if the fighting subsided, ``this is a possibility,
which we will not rule out.''
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz told Hamadi on Thursday he
was convinced that Iraq had used poison gas against Kurdish
guerrillas. He condemned its use as ``abhorrent and unjustifiable.''
   Hamadi, at a news conference Friday, said Shultz had not
substantiated the allegation. ``No evidence was produced to us,''
he said. ``We have seen no evidence at all.''
   The Iraqi diplomat, whose meeting with Shultz initially was
scheduled to deal with sputtering efforts to end the Iran-Iraq war,
said he told Shultz the allegation was not true.
   ``I said categorically we deny this,'' he told reporters.
   Hamadi said he did not ask Shultz to provide evidence and said
he hoped U.S. relations with Iraq would continue to improve.
   The Iraqi official again accused Kurds ``manipulated'' by Iran
of spreading the accusation that Iraq used cyanide and other
chemical weapons against Kurds, killing or injuring thousands of
them.
   He said negotiations to end the eight-year Persian Gulf war were
in ``a difficult stage'' because Iran was unwilling to accept the
principle of free shipping.
   Hamadi said Iraq must have access to Shatt al Arab, historically
its only access to the gulf. Despite Iran's opposition, he said,
``We will resist any attempt to suspend the negotiations.''
   Redman, the State Department spokesman, was asked later if the
Iraqi demand for freedom of shipping had U.S. support. Noting the
United Nations is overseeing the negotiations, he replied that ``we
are not attempting to insert ourselves into these kinds of
details.''
   The sanctions bill offered by Pell, chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, and sent to the House, would:
   _Require the U.S. representative to international financial
institutions top vote against all loans to Iraq.
   _Bar all U.S. financial credits or guarantees to Iraq.
   _Ban the importation of Iraqi oil.
   _Forbid U.S. economic and military aid.
   _Bar the transfer of sensitive high-technology items subject to
U.S. export controls.
   ``I think this is as strong a set of sanctions as has ever been
passed,'' Pell told reporters.
</TEXT>
