<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Corn-Soviets     09-09 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Corn-Soviets,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Make Additional Purchase of American Corn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought an additional
350,000 metric tons of U.S. corn for delivery in the coming year,
the Agriculture Department said Friday.
   The sale brought total corn sold to the Soviets in the last nine
days for delivery in the 1988-89 year that started Sept. 1 to more
than 2.6 million tons.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 350,000 tons of
corn would be about 13.8 million bushels.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.75 per bushel at the
farm level, according to USDA estimates, meaning that the latest
sale could have a farm value of around $38 million.
   As with the other recent sales, no indication was given whether
the new sales of corn to the Soviets would count under the current
long-term grain supply agreement between the two countries or be
carried forward separately in case a new pact is forthcoming.
   The current five-year pact is set to expire Sept. 30 and
negotiators are trying to work out a new one, or at least an
extension of the current agreement, to take effect Oct. 1.
   According to the agreement, the annual purchases are supposed to
include a minimum 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. The
Soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as
wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two
tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain
equivalent.
   Prior to sales announced since Sept. 1, the Soviet Union had
purchased 9.05 million tons of wheat and 5.17 million tons of corn
for delivery in the fifth year of the agreement, plus 830,000 tons
of soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
