<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSReporting     09-09 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Reporting,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young Hemophiliac Afraid Of AIDS Test; Wants Change In
Name-Disclosure Rule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old hemophiliac says he is
afraid to be tested for AIDS because he might lose his friends and
he wants the state to stop mandatory identification of those who
test positive for the AIDS virus.
   The boy said he worries constantly that he is infected with
AIDS, but is afraid that if he tests positive his name might be
leaked from state files.
   The boy and his mother agreed to be interviewed by The Arizona
Daily Star on the condition that they not be identified by name.
   ``I told this friend I have hemophilia and he went and told his
mom, and she said I couldn't come over no more,'' he said.
   Twenty-nine doctors, lawyers and others have signed a petition
on the boy's behalf, and it is to be presented Monday to state
Health Director Ted Williams.
   The petition asks that the state drop the requirement for
reporting by name those people who test positive for the human
immunodeficiency virus that causes to AIDS.
   ``I'd be helping all the other hemophiliacs and all the people
with AIDS in Arizona,'' the boy said.
   Hemophilia is a hereditary condition in which one of the normal
blood-clotting factors is absent, causing prolonged bleeding from
even minor cuts and injuries. It occurs in males, and is
transmitted by females.
   Hemophiliacs and others who received blood transfusions before
1985, when screening became available, were at risk of being
infected with the AIDS virus.
   The boy has had at least 45 transfusions since 1981, his mother
said.
   Williams told The Associated Press on Friday that his department
is working on strengthening the confidentiality policy for AIDS
patients, rather than dropping the requirement that names be
reported.
   ``This child is making our case for us,'' Williams said. ``He's
concerned about getting tested because he's worried the information
will somehow leak out.''
   The boy, who moved from Indiana to Tucson this summer, is a
former schoolmate of Ryan White, the Indiana boy who was barred
from public school in 1985 after he contracted AIDS from a blood
transfusion.
   White, also a hemophiliac, returned to school under court order,
and he and his family later moved to another Indiana town.
   The 11-year-old talked of being harassed and shunned by
schoolmates in Indiana who thought that because he was a
hemophiliac, he must also have AIDS.
   ``Before you know it, you're sitting on one end of the
playground and nobody's sitting with you, and you don't know why,''
he said.
   Williams would not discuss the specifics of the proposed changes
in the law because they are still in draft form. One change would
allow the state to notify school districts of students who had
tested positive.
   Williams said any changes would require public hearings.
   ``We want people to come and get tested. We want them to know.
That's the best way we have to fight this epidemic,'' Williams
added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880909-0145 </DOCNO>
