<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gibraltar-IRA     09-09 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gibraltar-IRA,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Officer Testifies at Inquest into IRA Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British officer involved in the shooting
deaths of three IRA agents told an inquest Friday his commando
unit's mission was to arrest the three, disarm them and defuse a
car bomb they were believed ready to detonate.
   He said intelligence received in Gibraltar two days before the
shootings described the IRA members as ``dedicated and ruthless
terrorists who were likely to carry arms and who had explosives
ready to construct a bomb.''
   The three proved to be unarmed. Critics of British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher's government cited the shootings as
evidence that her government is implementing an unofficial
``shoot-to-kill'' policy against IRA active members believed on
attack missions against British targets.
   The officer testified on the fourth day of the inquest by
Coroner Felix Pizzarello and an 11-member jury into the March 6
shooting deaths of Sean Savage, 24, Mairead Farrell, 31, and Daniel
McCann, 31.
   The IRA has acknowledged the three were on active service when
killed.
   The witness was one of seven British Special Air Services (SAS)
officers involved in the incident in this British fortress colony.
His elite regiment is used by Britain in anti-terrorist operations
against the Irish Republican Army.
   He was identified only as `F'' for security reasons and was
concealed from the view of public and press by a curtain.
   The officer testified that when the Gibraltar police commisioner
turned over control to the military to detain the IRA suspects,
just before the shootings, they were given permission to use
``lethal force in the preservation of life.''
   ``We had been told that the IRA was under pressure to produce a
spectacular attack,'' `F' testified, adding that it was believed
the attack would consist of setting off a car bomb March 8 during a
ceremonial changing of the guard in the center of Gibraltar.
   ``We were also informed that the (IRA) active service unit was
made up of McCann, Farrell and Savage.''
   The inquest has no power of prosecution. If the inquest jury
hands down a verdict of unlawful killing, the Gibraltar attorney
general is expected to return criminal indictments.
</TEXT>
