<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 2132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AIDS     09-09 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Up to 111,854 Officially, Could Be 300,000, WHO Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of AIDS cases worldwide reported to the
World Health Organization rose to 111,854 at the end of August, but
the true number of victims is likely to be as high as 300,000, the
U.N. agency said Friday.
   The figure of 111,854, a cumulative total since officials began
recording cases in the early 1980s, represents an increase of 3,678
reported cases in August, WHO said in a news release.
   It said the WHO's Global Program on AIDS ``now estimates the
actual cumulative number of AIDS cases to date at approximately
250,000-300,000, or more than twice the number of officially
reported cases.''
   Of 177 countries which report to the WHO, 140 report having AIDS
victims while 37 say they have no cases, it said.
   Of the total cases reported, 19,097 were diagnosed so far this
year, the news release said.
   Among countries reporting an increase in victims during August
were the United States, up 2,086 to 71,171, France, up 583 to
4,211, and Italy, up 368 to 2,233 cases.
   No Latin American countries provided updated figures in August.
Brazil had the highest number of cases, 2,956 reported in April of
1988, followed by Mexico with 1,302, also reported in April.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is caused by a
virus that attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread most often
through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers,
infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their
unborn babies.
</TEXT>
