<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 2133EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Fires-Lookout     09-09 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fires-Lookout,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smoke Doesn't Deter Fire Lookouts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fires Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHOSHONE NATIONAL FOREST, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atop Clay Butte Lookout
near the northern border of the Shoshone National Forest, Pat Moore
can't see the fires for the smoke.
   But she knows the flames are out there, burning wildly in and
around Yellowstone National Park to the west, southwest and south
of the U.S. Forest Service lookout tower built in 1942.
   Moore, a Forest Service secretary normally based in Atlanta, and
Verna Nachu, a Bureau of Indian Affairs employee from White River,
Ariz., help fight the flames by relaying communications between
fire camps.
   ``They normally use us for repeater service,'' Nachu, said
between communications Thursday evening. ``They call us human
repeaters.''
   Sitting at 9,811 feet, the lookout tower's radio messages are
unimpeded by the surrounding mountains, which frequently block
communications among the fire camps based on the forest floor.
   On clear days from their glassy perch Moore and Nachu can see
the huge columns of smoke rising from forest fires in both the
Shoshone and adjacent Yellowstone. At night, flames dance wildly in
the dark.
   On Thursday, though, wind from the west encapsulated the lookout
in a thick haze of smoke, visibility to several hundred yards.
   ``We had beautiful weather until the wind changed and the smoke
came this way. We really had a beautiful vantage point for
watching,'' Moore said.
   Before fires surrounded nearby Cooke City and Silver Gate,
Mont., the two women had frequent visitors when townspeople stopped
by to watch the fires.
   ``They ask a lot of questions about the fire,'' said Moore.
``Naturally they were concerned about their homes, their friends'
homes.''
   Moore, who spent 30 days in California last summer during the
fire season, is in the middle of her third week in Wyoming, her
first visit to the Rockies, and is in no rush to leave.
   ``It is magnificent,'' she said of of the surrounding
countryside. ``It's so different from what I'm used to. I've never
seen the wildlife that I see here.''
   She said she daily spots moose, deer, elk and grouse, although
she has yet to spot a grizzly bear.
   She does admit, though, that at times the lookout post can be
quite boring.
   ``We're pretty well stuck up here with no driver, no truck, no
nothing,'' said Moore. ``It can be very boring. ... after a while
when there's no radio communications, it can get slow, really
slow.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
