<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-09 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tropical Storm Florence Becomes Hurricane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane warnings went up Friday from Cameron, La., to
Pensacola, Fla., as Tropical Storm Florence developed into a
hurricane and churned its way northward toward the central Gulf
Coast.
   Florence was expected to reach the coast of southeast Louisiana
sometime Friday night. It was 150 miles south of New Orleans and
moving north at 15 mph.
   There were also tropical storm warnings for winds greater than
50 mph from Pensacola to Apalachicola, Fla.
   Rain from Florence was spreading across southeast Louisiana and
along the Alabama coast.
   Thunderstorms along a stationary front along the coast of the
Carolinas and Georgia dumped heavy amounts of rain. Local street
flooding was reported in various areas of the South Carolina coast
and at Charleston, S.C.
   Rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT included over
2 inches at Tyndall Air Force Base in Panama City, Fla.; 2 inches
at Charleston, S.C.; over 1}-inches at Beaufort, S.C. Marine Corps
Air Station; and over 1 inch at Tallahassee, Fla.
   Temperatures Friday afternoon were in the 60s along the Pacific
Coast, over the northern Rockies, from northern Montana across
North Dakota into northern portions of the upper Great Lakes
states. Temperatures were in the 60s due to clouds and rain from
northwest Florida into western portions of the Carolinas. Readings
were in the 90s over southwest Texas, north-central Texas, and over
the desert Southwest. The rest of the nation had temperatures in
the 70s and 80s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 52
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 106 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
   The low in the nation Friday was 24 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   Saturday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
Virginia and the southern Atlantic Coast states across Florida and
Alabama into Louisiana. Thunderstorms were expected over southeast
Louisiana and southern Mississippi from Florence. Widely scattered
showers and thunderstorms were expected in the northern Rocky
Mountain states.
   High temperatures were to be in the 60s over northern portions
of the upper Great Lakes and along coastal sections of the Pacific
Northwest. Highs were to be in the 90s over the Florida peninsula,
the southern and central Plains, the central and southern Rockies,
the southern Plateau region and the inland valleys of California.
Temperatures were expected to be between 100 and 105 in the desert
Southwest. The rest of the nation were to have highs in the 70s and
80s.
</TEXT>
