<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissAmerica-Judges     09-09 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miss America-Judges,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pageant Judges Say Enhanced Bodies Are OK</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If would-be Miss Americas use tape or
surgery to improve their figures, that's OK, pageant judges say, as
long as the contestants also show they're modern, articulate women.
   The pageant's six preliminary-rounds judges agreed Friday that
they have no qualms about figure-enhancing techniques.
   Such techniques, often questioned during this
scholarship-awarding pageant, have been a consistent topic of
discussion in the first days of the 1988 competition here this week.
   A new Miss America will be picked on Saturday by a panel of
celebrity judges. They'll choose from among 10 semi-finalists
picked this week by the preliminary judges.
   The preliminary judges say they wouldn't be put off if some
contestants used unnatural gimmicks.
   Those techniques _ long discussed on the pageant circuit _
include surgical breast implants, adhesive-taped chests, and a
sticky spray used to make swimsuits cling.
   ``Does it really matter if her breasts are taped?'' asked judge
Trudy Haynes, an entertainment reporter on Philadelphia television.
   ``It's their choice,'' added William Goldman, a screenwriter
whose credits include ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid.''
   According to the judges, figure enhancing is fine, so as long as
it's done with overall appearance in mind and not specifically to
win the Miss America title.
   Such techniques aren't against pageant rules. Even if they were,
the judges say they probably wouldn't know which contestants were
using the gimmicks.
   Cosmetic surgery ``is a product of the '80's,'' said judge Mary
Jennings, an opera soprano and former third runner-up in the
pageant.
   Miss Mississippi Carla Haag, who won a preliminary swimsuit
event Thursday, also endorsed the use of artificial techniques to
make bodies look better. She declined to say whether she had had
cosmetic surgery.
   Miss Haag said surgery could be considered if it helped make a
woman ``a much better person and to feel better about yourself.''
   The judges said they support retaining the swimsuit event,
despite continung criticism that it undermines the pageant's
credibility as a scholarship competition.
   The event, where competitors must walk the 200-foot-long runway
clad only in a taut suit and high-heeled shoes, is designed to
gauge physical fitness and poise, pageant officials say.
   Pageant executive director Leonard Horn has said he will
consider replacing the swimsuits with another measure of fitness.
   But Miss America insiders believe the swimsuits help draw the
annual television audience so important to the pageant's financial
success.
   Judges said the fitness and poise evidenced in the event help
indicate how able a Miss America a young woman might be.
   As important is a contestant's showing in the talent event, and
in a seven-minute interview with the judges behind closed doors.
   ``She probably won't have to put a swimming suit on with high
heels again. But she's got to be able to put a noun and verb
together,'' said judge Rick Lester, managing director of the San
Antonio (Texas) Symphony Orchestra.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
