<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SentencingGuidelines     09-09 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sentencing Guidelines,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Challenges Sentencing Guidelines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge said Friday he won't follow federal
sentencing guidelines to calculate prison terms for two men
convicted of the same drug offense because the defendants would
receive vastly different sentences.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson made the ruling in
the case of two men who pleaded guilty to selling a vial of
``crack'' to an undercover police officer for $25.
   Under the guidelines, one defendant would receive a prison term
of 12 to 18 months while the other would be sentenced to 17{ to 21
years for the same offense, Jackson said.
   ``The presentence reports reveal that both defendants are in
their early 30s. They have similar prior criminal records and
similar personal histories, and they are, for practical purposes,
on the basis of information presently known, indistinguishable as
co-participants in a routine small-quantity drug sale such as occur
daily in distressing numbers,'' Jackson said.
   Jackson said the disparity in the two sentences under the
guidelines ``derives primarily'' from ``evidence identifying only
McDuffie'' with possession of drugs found in a nearby car.
   The judge said he would not apply the guidelines when the two
defendants appear to be sentenced on Sept. 14.
   The guidelines, which were established by a commission set up
under the 1984 Sentencing Reform Act, provide an elaborate formula
for calculating prison terms according to a defendant's criminal
history and the severity of his offense.
   The Supreme Court is scheduled to hear arguments Oct. 5 on the
constitutionality of the sentencing guidelines, which provide for
prison terms without parole.
   Federal judges began sentencing prisoners under the guidelines
late last year. Since then, 142 federal district judges have
declared them unconstitutional while another 104 have upheld their
constitutionality, according to figures compiled by the U.S.
Sentencing Commission.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals also voted 2-1 to strike
them down.
   In the case before Jackson, Gary D. McDuffie and Aubrey F.
Martin pleaded guilty to distribution of a controlled substance
after they were arrested April 16 after selling a vial of ``crack''
to an undercover officer.
   Officers who searched a nearby automobile, which was registered
to McDuffie's girlfriend, found personal papers bearing McDuffie's
name, a .38-caliber revolver and 109 grams of ``crack.''
   McDuffie also pleaded guilty to possession of a firearm in
connection with narcotics trafficking _ for which he will receive a
mandatory five-year prison term that must be served after he
completes the prison term for the drug conviction.
   Another difference, the judge noted, was that McDuffie was still
on parole for a seven- to 21-year sentence at the time of his
arrest. Martin received three year's probation in 1978 instead of a
five- to 15-year prison sentence for a felony conviction that was
suspended.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880909-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 2210EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Mail     09-09 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Mail,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report tentative agreement to end postal strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for the Post Office and striking union
members reached a tentative agreement Friday to end a 9-day-old
national strike by 90,000 workers, postal officials reported.
   But after a day of talks Alan Tuffin, general secretary of the
Union of Communication Workers, said ``a number of points'' needed
clarification and union leaders would meet with their negotiators
Monday to reconsider the agreement.
   ``There can be no misunderstandings between the Post Office and
ourselves,'' Tuffin said.
   Bill Cockburn, managing director of the Post Office, approved
the pact earlier Friday, according to a spokesman who was not
identified in line with Post Office rules. ``The document calls for
ending the strike as soon as possible,'' he said.
   The tentative agreement schedules further talks on the central
strike issue of bonuses for new employees in London and southeast
England, where the cost of living is higher than in the rest of
Britain.
   The union, which represents most of the service's 180,000
workers, wants the bonuses paid throughout Britain.
   More than 100 million pieces of mail remain unsorted by the
90,000 sorters and deliverers who walked out in a 24-hour work
stoppage Aug. 31. The strike continued after Post Office officials
hired temporary workers.
   Counter workers who belong to the same union but have not been
involved in the bonus dispute said Friday they had taken a strike
vote over a different issue but their mail ballots became lost in
the backlog of unsorted letters.
   The union's 22,000 counter workers voted whether to strike over
the Post Office plan to close 750 branch offices or convert them
into private suboffices, said a union official.
   The official said the results of the strike vote were to have
been announced early next week but had been postponed.
   A Post Office spokeswoman said half of the country's 1,500
sorting offices were shut and the Belfast office was the only one
of 82 main sorting offices open.
</TEXT>
