<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0638 09-09 0826</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0638,0848</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Round Up 225 Palestinians in Crackdown in Territories</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: subs grafs 8-14 `A crackdown ... Aug. 3' with 8 grafs
attributing identities of some suspects to commander; picks up 15th
`In Kfar Malik' and edits to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KFAR MALIK, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops arrested
225 Palestinian activists in the occupied lands Friday during a
crackdown that smashed a Gaza Strip network accused of organizing
subversion.
   Fights broke out between Islamic fundamentalists and supporters
of PLO chief Yasser Arafat throughout the West Bank and Gaza, where
the fundamentalists mounted a strike to challenge the pro-PLO
uprising leadership.
   The strike called by Hamas, which means zeal, shut down
businesses and transportation in most of the occupied lands and
stopped workers from going to jobs in Israel.
   The fundamentalists oppose any negotiated settlement with Israel
while some supporters of the Palestine Liberation Organizxation
have been urging peace talks.
   Police said an Arab who allegedly collaborated with Israel was
assassinated in Jaffa. Twelve Palestinians, including two 14
year-olds and a 13-year-old, were reported wounded in clashes with
troops in Gaza City and the West Bank city of Nablus.
   Since the uprising began Dec. 8 in the occupied territories 260
Palestinians have been killed, most by Israeli gunfire. Five
Israelis also have been slain.
   Using a new tactic, hundreds of soldiers surrounded the West
Bank village of Kfar Malik, 15 miles north of Jerusalem, at dawn
Friday and arrested 25 Palestinians accused of anti-Israeli
activities, Arab witnesses said.
   A crackdown in Gaza broke up a clandestine ring of 200
Palestinian members of 37 committees responsible for organizing
anti-Israeli activity in communities throughout the coastal strip,
the army said.
   It said the suspects were linked to Arafat's Fatah faction of
the PLO.
   Maj. Gen. Yitzhak Mordechai, Gaza Strip commander, said the
detainees were accused of taking part in 45 arson and firebomb
attacks on Arab shopowners who failed to heed strike calls and on
alleged collaborators.
   Mordechai said the Gaza leader of the PLO network was among
those captured but he declined to identify him.
   Israeli television identified the suspect as Abdallah Abu
Samhadaneh and Arab sources said he was a Gaza City resident who
has spent 10 years in Israeli prisons.
   The televlision report said other detainees included Aata Abu
Kirsh, an engineer it said was a senior Fatah executive in Gaza;
Mohammed Saadi, head of Gaza City's popular committees, and Ayish
Abu Saada, a teacher who led the communist committees.
   Mordechai said the sweep was ``certainly a decisive blow to the
committees in Gaza and to their activity in the field. This does
not say there will be no other committees but their influence will
not be the same.''
   He said he would recommend expulsion for some of the detainees.
Israel has deported 33 Palestinians since the uprising began
despite international protests.
   Israel radio said three members of the Gaza ring were suspected
of killing Rachel Weiss, an elderly woman found near her Negev
desert collective farm on Aug. 3.
   In Kfar Malik, Ibrahim Saleh, 25, a farmer whose 21-year-old
brother Jamal was arrested Friday, said many village youths managed
to elude troops and escape into the foot hills after town gards
whistled the alarm about 3 a.m.
   ``A lot of people managed to get away because they heard the
whistling,'' Saleh said.
   Villagers said troops backed by helicopters searched
house-to-house for Palestinians included on a 50-name list took the
suspects away handcuffed and blindfolded in jeeps.
   ``The soldiers broke into the houses and smashed windows. They
also threw tear gas into the houses,'' said Baher Mohammed, 32, who
pointed to a ground floor room still thick with gas.
   Islamic fundamentalists and rival PLO supporters fought each
other with stones, knives and fists in a number of areas, including
the West Bank's Al Amari refugee camp and Bethlehem, Arab witnesses
said.
   They said the fighting in Bethlehem broke out after masked
youths loyal to the fundamentalists rode bicycles through the town
warning shopkeepers to close their businesses or face reprisals.
   ``Anyone who doesn't close his shop will find it burned
tonight,'' said one youth who wore a black garbage bag over his
head.
   At least one Hamas supporter was injured in Bethlehem when
pro-PLO youths loyal shoved him onto a burning tire, the witnesses
said.
   Also Friday, the army announced it would free 150 Arabs being
held without trial in a Negev desert prison camp at Ketziot. It
said the releases were a humanitarian gesture for the Jewish New
Year that begins Monday.
   On the political front Foreign Minister Shimon Peres sent a
letter to Washington accepting an invitation to talks Sept. 26 on
the Middle East peace process.
   The invitation brought charges from members of Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir's conservative Likud bloc that Peres, leader of the
liberal Labor Party, engineered the invitation to advance his
candidacy in Israel's Nov. 1 parliamentary election.
</TEXT>
