<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Fires     09-09 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Fires,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Forest Fire Assistance Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed legislation Friday
designed to pave the way for Canadian assistance in fighting the
rash of forest fires in Western states, promising ``every action
possible'' to minimize the damage.
   Meanwhile, a Cabinet-level team named by the president will fly
west Saturday and visit Yellowstone National Park, the Cody, Wyo.,
area and Boise, Idaho, to assess the situation and formulate
recommendations on more federal assistance in firefighting.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Agriculture
Secretary Richard Lyng and Deputy Defense Secretary William H. Taft
IV would fly from Andrews Air Force Base, Md., and be joined in
Denver by Interior Secretary Donald Hodel, who was in Dallas on
other business.
   Fitzwater said they would go first to West Yellowstone, Mont.,
for a briefing by the Yellowstone Area Command, then to the Old
Faithful Geyser area and on to Cody before flying to Boise for a
tour of the Interagency Fire Center there. They will return to
Washington on Sunday.
   The legislation signed by the president authorizes mutual
agreements with foreign fire organizations for wildlife protection.
   ``This allows us to bring in needed equipment and personnel from
our Canadian neighbors to help combat these wildfires,'' Reagan
said.
   The legislation was passed on Thursday.
   ``I applaud the leadership and members of both the House and
Senate for their rapid passage of this emergency legislation,'' the
president said. ``I will take every action possible to control the
remaining fires and prepare for the fires that may yet come.''
</TEXT>
