<HEAD>Quotes From the Presidential Campaign Trail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some comments Thursday from the
presidential campaign trail:
   
   DAN QUAYLE, pelted with questions about a story published in
Friday's (Cleveland) Plain Dealer reporting that Quayle got into
the University of Indiana Law School on an affirmative action
program for the poor and minorities: ``I got into law school fair
and square. No rules were broken.''
   
   GEORGE BUSH, reacting to Dukakis' statement Thursday that the
Democratic nominee would consider deploying Star Wars if research
shows it works and if it is in the interest of national security:
``Calling it a fantasy one day, something he won't rule out the
next ... suggests a confusion in my view on the basic facts.
Confusion in terms of what he really believes and where he would
take this country.''
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, in a stinging rebuttal to Bush's recent attacks
on him:
   ``Just as (the Republicans) did to Franklin Roosevelt and
(former U.S. House Speaker) Sam Rayburn, they're now attacking my
patriotism. And just as they did in the 1930s and the 1950s, the
American people can smell the garbage.''
   
   LLOYD BENTSEN, speaking to hundreds of farmers in Iowa: ``It's
time for a change from the policies and personalities that
devastated our farms, punished our farmers and left rural America
in the dust.''
   
  
