<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-IranianProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0726 09-09 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Iranian Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0726,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Burns Self in Protest as Others Denounce Executions in
Iran</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with victim's
background, scene, other. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian man poured gasoline over his
head Friday and set himself afire outside U.N. headquarters, and
Iranian dissidents said it was to protest executions of government
opponents in his homeland.
   The man, Mehrdad Imen, 32, a registered alien living in Los
Angeles, was taken to the burn center at New York University
Hospital where he was listed in critical condition with burns over
his entire body.
   The immolation took place about noon outside the United Nations
building at 42nd Street and First Avenue as other Iranians
protested in a nearby park, police said.
   ``He considered it the best way to draw attention to the recent
wave of executions in Iran,'' said Mohammad Sedaghat, a spokesman
for People's Mujahedeen, the Iranian opposition group that
organized the park rally.
   Ten pint-sized plastic bottles that had contained gasoline
remained on the sidewalk by evening, along with ashes, a
half-burned blue shirt with white stripes, a charred suitcase and
the remnants of a Manhattan bus map showing the route to the United
Nations.
   Imen was known in the Iranian community as an activist against
the government ruled by Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini. Imen flew to
New York on Friday with other Iranians from Los Angeles who joined
the organized protest at Dag Hammarskjold Plaza at 47th Street,
said Sedaghat.
   On the flight to New York, Imen told fellow Iranians of his
outrage over the executions and his intention to carry out a
personal protest, but did not reveal his plans, Sedaghat reported.
   Rally organizers said 1,200 people attended the Friday protest,
but journalists on the scene estimated up to 500 people were in the
crowd.
   Twenty years ago, a Buddhist monk set himself on fire just
outside the U.N. gates but survived, said U.N. spokeswoman Nadia
Yousef. At the time, monks in South Vietnam were immolating
themselves to protest corruption in President Nguyen Van Thieu's
government.
   The People's Mujahedeen, a group of Iranian exiles dedicated to
overthrowing the Khomeini government, claims that nearly 1,210
dissidents have been executed in Iran since midsummer.
   The group said in a statement that Tehran is trying to crush
resistance because of Iran's acceptance of the cease-fire in its
8-year-old war with Iraq. The People's Mujahedeen (holy warriors)
says the truce demonstrates to the Iranian people that Iran's
religious rulers pursued a lost cause in the war.
   Amnesty International, the London-based human rights
organization, appealed to its members on Sept. 2 to pressure Iran
to halt the executions.
   Amnesty said most victims belonged to the People's Mujahedeen
but about 20 supporters of other opposition groups were also
reported to have been executed.
   It did not estimate the number of people killed but said a ban
on family visits to political prisoners in Evin Prison in Tehran,
the Iranian capital, ``fueled speculation that hundreds of
political prisoners have been executed.''
   Amnesty noted that Iranian official news media said 15 People's
Mujahedeen members were executed Aug. 5.
   The People's Mujahedeen has a military wing, the National
Liberation Army, which conducted raids on July 25-28 in which it
claimed to have captured the cities of Kerend and Islamabad in Iran
and to have inflicted 50,000 casualties on Iranian troops.
   Most of the executions followed the raids.
   The People's Mujahedeen asked Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar to investigate. No U.N. mission could enter Iran without
being invited, however.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
