<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 2336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Tutu     09-09 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Tutu,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tutu Prays for Bombers of Church Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Desmond Tutu
inspected the bombed headquarters of the South African Council of
Churches on Friday, then prayed for those who planted the
explosives.
   Police later surrounded and entered the nearby Central Methodist
Church, where the black prelate gave a news conference and tried to
hold a private meeting with members of the church council staff.
   ``The only surprising thing is it took so long,'' Tutu said of
the bombing while a security police video team filmed him.
   An explosion before dawn Aug. 31 heavily damaged Khotso House,
where the council and several other anti-apartheid groups have
their offices. More than 20 people in the area suffered slight
injuries and the building was declared unsafe for further use.
   The council moved into Khotso House during Tutu's tenure as
general secretary 1978-1984. Tutu won the 1984 Nobel Peace Prize
for his work against South Africa's apartheid policy of racial
discrimination and now heads the Anglican church in southern Africa.
   ``Foul, foul foul!'' Tutu muttered, bending under crumpled
doorways and crunching shattered glass beneath his feet during a
tour of three of the building's six floors.
   Tutu and the church council's current general secretary, the
Rev. Frank Chikane, entered through a balcony from a temporary
metal staircase over the wrecked main entrance.
   They went to each floor via the back fire escape because the
building's staircases were impassable. Walls were knocked down,
glass was broken and doors were blown out in every room.
   Surveying the elevator shaft, which apparently took the brunt of
the explosion, Tutu said: ``It was done by an expert.''
   He stepped on a small table as he entered his old office and it
collapsed, then a partition fell over next to him. ``I left this
office in better shape,'' he told Chikane.
   At the news conference, Tutu said ``the forces of darkness''
were behind the bombing and declared that ``the government, and its
supporters have tried before to destroy'' the council.
   When asked who he held was responsible, Tutu said: ``Sometimes I
amaze myself at how diplomatic I can be. But people who are wise,
like yourselves, know exactly who we mean.''
   Police have not reported significant progress in their
investigation. Anti-apartheid activists believe the attackers were
right-wing vigilantes or a covert security force unit.
   If the police make arrests in the case ``I will give them a
prize,'' Tutu said.
   Police allowed a crowd of blacks to sing and dance in the street
outside Khotso House for nearly an hour. Riot police moved in as
Tutu came out to deliver his prayer for the bombers but took no
action.
   Soon afterward, however, officers scuffled with a guard at the
door of the Methodist Church conference hall when he tried to keep
them out of the meeting.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880909-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 2338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina     09-09 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Break Up Anti-Government Rally; Dozens Reported Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers staged a general strike
in Argentina Friday and dozens of people were reported hurt in
Buenos Aires as police fired tear gas and rubber bullets to scatter
thousands of demonstrators.
   The independent news agency Diarios y Noticias said four people
were seriously injured when a rally in the broad Plaza de Mayo
outside Government House turned into a street brawl, including
fights between members of rival unions. It said 23 policemen were
hurt and 60 demonstratorsprotesters were treated for injuries at
the scene.
   The strike was organized by the country's largest labor
federation to protest Argentina's deteriorating economy and the
policies of President Raul Alfonsin.
   ``This is a referendum of the people against the hunger and
misery the government is trying to impose on us!,''
Secretary-General Saul Ubaldini of the General Labor Confederation
told the Plaza de Mayo rally.
   ``Every day there's less work and my family can't live on what I
earn,'' said Daniel Rio, a truck driver who attended the rally.
``That's why I'm here.''
   The strike was called for noon to 8 p.m. so people would show up
for work and then take part in rallies and demonstrations.
   Striking signalmen shut down commuter trains before dawn,
however, and many bus drivers took a long midday break. Some
businesses closed early, particularly the expensive shops on
Florida Street, a pedestrian mall near the Plaza de Mayo.
   Strikes shut down or interrupted business in Cordoba, San Miguel
de Tucuman, Rio Negro, Santa Fe and other cities.
   The rally in this capital city began peacefully, with unions and
political parties waving banners and chanting slogans to the beat
of rubber hoses on bass drums.
   Demonstrators from rival unions began quarreling and then
fighting and police fired tear gas and rubber bullets. At one point
club-swinging police waded into the crowd.
   Ubaldini, rubbing his eyes smarting from tear gas, pleaded from
the stage for order as police trucks with water cannon scattered
the remaining crowd. Some protesters broke store windows as they
left.
   Argentina is suffering inflation in which prices increased 53
percent in the past two months. Unemployment and underemployment
are near 14-year highs. Real personal income has declined for three
straight years, the government acknowleges.
   Five weeks ago Alfonsin implemented his third major
anti-inflation plan in five years. It included devaluation of the
austral, Argentina's currency; the lifting of restrictions on some
imports, and voluntary controls on wages and prices.
   In addition to reducing inflation, the goal was to secure new
loans from the International Monetary Fund and commercial banks to
help repay interest on Argentina's $56 billion foreign debt.
   The General Labor Confederation and member unions complained
that prices were rising despite the controls and pressed for higher
wages. The federation, to which virtually every union belongs, also
demanded that Economy Minister Juan Sourrouille resign.
   ``I want the government out of the International Monetary
Fund,'' said Oscar Zanetich, a 41-year-old public school teacher
when questioned on the street by a reporter. He also complained
about teachers' salaries.
   Argentina's debt, the third-highest in the developing world, and
the billions of dollars it pays every year in interest are
criticized by leftists, unions and the opposition Peronist Party.
   ``I repudiate the economic policies of the government,'' said
23-year-old history student Faviana as she spray-painted ``People
Power'' on the wall of a building outside the plaza. She would not
give her last name.
   The strike was the 12th staged by the labor federation since
Alfonsin took office in December 1983, ending years of military
rule.
   Supporters of Alfonsin's centrist Radical Civic Union said the
strike was meant to undermine the anti-inflation plan and to unite
support for Peronist presidential candidate Carlos Menem in
national elections set for next May.
   One component of Alfonsin's general economic plan is the
privatization of some of the dozens of state companies, including
the telephone company, the national air carrier Aerolineas
Argentinas and the national shipping line.
   Unions representing workers at the companies generally oppose
privatization, fearing that jobs would be cut. The Peronist Party,
closely tied to the unions, has raised obstacles in Congress to the
sale of state-owned companies.
</TEXT>
