<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 2342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Politics     09-09 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Politics,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Says Govternment Undersold California Property</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile
said Friday the government may have lost up to $5 million on the
sale of a building in California and he demanded an investigation.
   In a speech to the Senate, Enrile claimed the government
violated laws that require government property be sold by public
bidding.
   President Corazon Aquino said in a statement the $10 million
price for the building, which housed offices of Philippine
Airlines, was ``deemed the best practicably obtainable in the
circumstances because of building restrictions in San Francisco.''
She did not elaborate.
   The building was sold in April 1986, two months after Mrs.
Aquino assumed office after a civilian-military uprising drove
President Ferdinand Marcos into exile.
   A week ago, Enrile accused relatives of Mrs. Aquino of the
``systematic looting'' of state-run companies. The president and
her family denied the charges and challenged Enrile to present
proof.
   Senate President Jovito Salonga and Sen. Rene Saguisag, both
members of Mrs. Aquino's Cabinet when the building was sold, said
they would welcome an investigation.
   Enrile presented documents at a news conference after his speech
that he said showed Mrs. Aquino and the board of the Government
Service Insurance System, owner of the building, gave official
approval four months after the sale.
   ``I am not enjoying this work because I have to assault the
sensibilities of my fellow human beings,'' Enrile said. ``The fact
is this property was sold hastily at a loss, almost
surreptitiously.''
   The documents showed the building on the corner of Stockton and
Geary streets was purchased in 1982 for $10 million, the same price
for which it was sold four years later. Enrile said it should have
brought $12-$15 million.
   One of the documents Enrile presented quoted Feliciano Belmont,
manager of the government insurance system, as telling Mrs. Aquino
irregularities may have been involved in the 1982 purchase by the
Marcos administration because the building was worth only $6-$8
million.
   In defending the sale, Saguisag said, ``There was an urgent need
to sell the property to cut losses.'' He did not elaborate.
   Tourism Secretary Jose Antonio Gonzalez, who also was involved
in the sale, told reporters the sale was necessary even at a loss
because the building was heavily mortgaged and the government could
not afford the payments.
</TEXT>
