<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Irish 1stLd-Writethru a0625 09-09 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0625,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Protestant Activist</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with IRA said to claim reponsibility,
explosives found, police say wave of attacks expected before year
ends. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two gunmen disguised as mailmen
boarded a train outside Belfast on Friday and killed a commuter,
the second Protestant activist slain this week, police and
witnesses said.
   The Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility, according to
news reports, which did not specify how the claim was made.
   Police said 30-year-old Colin Abernathy was shot once in the
head as the train drew into a suburban station at Finaghy, four
miles southwest of Belfast, during the morning rush hour.
   Witnesses told police the assailants boarded the train a few
stops earlier and sat across from their victim before shooting him.
   The attackers fled to a waiting car, which later was found
abandoned in Andersonstown in mainly Catholic west Belfast, a
police spokesman said.
   The train, coming to Belfast from Coleraine in the north,
proceeded to the next station, near City Hospital. Abernathy was
pronounced dead on arrival at the hospital, the spokesman said.
   Abernathy, a clerk with the Northern Ireland Electricity Board,
was a district treasurer in the Ulster Clubs. The Protestant
protest group was organized to resist the 1985 Anglo-Irish
agreement, which gives the Republic of Ireland an advisory role in
the province.
   On Wednesday, gunmen killed Billy Quee, 32, a leading member of
the Ulster Defense Association, an umbrella organization of
Protestant vigilante groups formed in the 1970s.
   The Irish People's Liberation Organization, a shadowy extremist
group, claimed responsibility.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary, the British province's police
force, said it expected IRA violence to intensify before the end of
the year and urged citizens to be on guard.
   The outlawed IRA is fighting to end British rule in Northern
Ireland and unite the predominantly Protestant province with the
Republic of Ireland, which is 95 percent Roman Catholic.
   The IRA recently stepped up its campaign against security
forces, using large quantities of Czechoslovak-made Semtex
explosive that police believe reached the IRA through Libya.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary said in a statement Friday, ``All
the information in the possession of the police indicates that the
threat from the Provisional IRA is escalating and their intention
is an horrific remainder to 1988.''
   Sgt. James Green of the constabulary said that police on Friday
arrested several people after finding one pound of Semtex and 200
pounds of fertilizer during searches in west Belfast. Those
arrested were not identified.
   Bomb-makers extract the nitrates from fertilizer to make
explosives, Green said.
   Police said they suspected the IRA was responsible for a bomb
that exploded in a parked van Thursday night outside a police
station in Coagh, County Tyrone, injuring five police and nine
civilians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
