<HEAD>Brountas Says Agreement Reached On Los Angeles As Second Debate
Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the campaigns of George Bush and
Michael Dukakis have agreed on Los Angeles as the site of the
second debate between the Republican and Democratic presidential
nominees, Dukakis' campaign chairman Paul Brountas said Friday.
   Previously, they settled on having the first presidential debate
in Winston-Salem, N.C., on Sept. 25, and to follow with a second
one elsewhere on either Oct. 13 or Oct. 14, depending on the length
of the American League baseball playoff series which will be
televised in prime time.
   Brountas said he talked with Bush campaign chairman James Baker
by phone Friday and they reached an agreement on having the second
debate in Los Angeles.
   Both debates are expected to be general in subject matter.
