<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0699 09-09 1072</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0699,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Campaign Swings Into Illinois and Pennsylvania</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs pvs grafs 13-14, bgng ``Later in,'' with new grafs
13-15, bgng ``Bush later,'' updating with Bush in York, quote on
patriotism, transition to pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEKIN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush said Friday his
opposition to abortion should not be ``a litmus test that everybody
has to agree with.''
   Bush reiterated that he opposes abortion except in cases of
rape, incest or when the life of the mother is endangered. He said
many of his key supporters disagree with him on the subject while
there are ``a lot that agree with me.''
   Commenting on numerous subjects at the beginning of a campaign
swing through Illinois and Pennsylvania, Bush also:
   _Said the government should re-examine its policy of letting
wilderness fires burn.
   _Tried to distance himself from a man fired from a campaign
advisory committee after complaints about anti-Semitism.
   _Ridiculed Democratic rival Michael Dukakis' recent statements
on the Strategic Defense Initiative, accusing him of contradictions
and confusion.
   With more than 1 million acres charred at Yellowstone National
Park, Bush said, ``I think we ought to take another look at the
policy. ... Nobody can argue this is the best way to do it.''
   He commented briefly on the anti-Semitism issue one day after
his campaign fired a member of a Bush committee after disclosure
that the man had defended Ohio autoworker John Demjanjuk, who was
convicted in Israel as a Nazi war criminal.
   ``He wasn't on my staff,'' Bush said of Jerome Brentar,
cochairman of the Bush '88 Coalition of American Nationalities.
``It was an advisory committee. The list came over from the
Republican National Committee.''
   Bush said, ``I just don't want people associated with me who
have a record of bigotry of any kind, racial bigotry. religious
bigotry, whatever it is.''
   ``I don't know this person, but if that's the record, why we're
better not to have any question raised of that nature and have the
person do something else.''
   Bush made his comments in an interview in Rockford, Ill., before
flying to Pekin, near Peoria, where he attended a courthouse rally
and was applauded by a large crowd.
   Bush later closed his campaign week with a rally before a
cheering, flag-waving crowd of thousands in York, Pa. ``I
understand that today the liberal governor of Massachusetts
attacked me for questioning the patriotism, his patriotism. I'm not
questioning his patriotism,'' Bush said. ``I'm questioning his
judgment,'' he added.
   Dukakis had compared Bush's attacks on him to Joseph McCarthy's
accusations in the 1950s. Dukakis said of Bush: ``I don't question
his patriotism, but I do question his judgment.'' The Democratic
nominee said Republicans were returning to tactics of the 1930s and
1950s in ``attacking my patriotism (but) the American people can
smell the garbage.''
   Earlier, in Illinois, at one point after Bush spelled out his
position on abortion, a reporter noted that Rep. Lynn Martin,
R-Ill., the co-chairman of his campaign who joined him in Rockford,
is pro-choice on the subject.
   ``I have a lot of key supporters who agree with Lynn and a lot
that agree with me,'' Bush said.
   Saying he was proud to have her in a leadership role, Bush said,
``Who's going to have a litmus test that everybody has to agree
with everybody on every single issue?''
   When it was noted that the GOP platform takes a hardline stand
against abortion, Bush said, ``The platform states the position of
the platform but nobody in our party takes a litmus test that says
that everybody has to agree on every issue. I expect the Democrats
could say the same thing.''
   On other points:
   _Bush refused to comment on a report that his running mate, Dan
Quayle, a wealthy Indiana senator, got into Indiana University Law
School on an affirmative action program for the poor and
minorities. ``I never comment on rumors and thank God I didn't when
they were all flying around back there (at the Republican
convention) about my running mate and everyone now sees that they
were grossly unfair. So I don't.''
   _He said he has not decided how much the minimum wage should be
increased. Bush, who has long opposed any increase, is expected to
announce a change in position soon. ``Well, I'm talking to some of
our experts and I'm going to do what's fair. I'll tell you one
thing, though, I will insist that there be a minimum wage
differential.'' He did not elaborate.
   In a speech in Rockford, Bush accused Dukakis of changing his
position on the Star Wars missile-defense program.
   Dukakis said Thursday he would consider deploying Star Wars if
research showed that it worked and was essential to the national
interest. A day earlier, Dukakis, a frequent critic of the program,
had called it a ``fantasy in the sky.''
   Bush, who supports the program, said, ``Calling it a fantasy one
day, something he won't rule out the next ... suggests a confusion
in my view on the basic facts. Confusion in terms of what he really
believes and where he would take this country.''
   Bush spoke before the Illinois Federation of Republican Women in
Rockford before flying to Peoria for the rally at the Tazewell
County Courthouse in Pekin and then on to Pennsylvania.
   Illinois and Pennsyvlania are key states in the presidential
race, commanding a total of 49 electoral votes. The race is close
in both states, with Dukakis believed to have an edge in
Pennsylvania.
   Bush's campaign had considered a stop at Peoria's Caterpillar
plant, but after the hostile reaction he got from a union audience
in Portland, Ore., earlier in the week, decided on going to Pekin.
   Addressing the GOP women's group, Bush hinted at a new proposal
that could help close the ``gender gap'' in support among women for
his campaign.
   Departing from his text, Bush said, ``Look, we also need to
assure that women don't have to worry about getting their jobs back
after having a child or caring for a child during a serious
illness.'' He did not spell out what he had in mind.
   Bush devoted a good chunk of his speech to chiding Dukakis for
seeming to soften his position on Star Wars, which is formally
known as the Strategic Defense Intiative, and on modernization of
strategic weapons.
   ``Does he believe in defense against strategic missiles or
doesn't he?'' Bush asked.
</TEXT>
