<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Jackson     09-09 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Jackson,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Appears With Jackson, Supports D.C. Statehood</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis endorsed ``full
statehood'' for the District of Columbia on Friday and won a strong
statement of support from former rival Jesse Jackson in an
appearance before a black religious group.
   ``Accept my recommendation,'' Jackson said of Dukakis. ``He can
be trusted to help keep hope alive.''
   Both appeared before the Baptist National Convention USA, the
largest black religious denomination with 8 million members. The
group is politically active, and most in attendance stood up to
demonstrate their endorsement of the Democratic presidential
nominee following the speech.
   Dukakis and Jackson also met privately for about 15 minutes
before addressing the group.
   ``In just 60 days, we can elect a president who will strengthen
our voting rights laws, not undermine them,'' Dukakis said, ``who
will fight for the universal voter registration bill now before the
Congress, and who will stand by the people of the District of
Columbia in their struggle for full statehood and equal rights.''
   Statehood for the District of Columbia would give Washington,
D.C., voting representation in the House of Representatives plus
two members of the Senate. It is an issue Jackson has pressed
Dukakis to highlight.
   Jackson delivered a stirring endorsement of Dukakis and blasted
Republican George Bush as insensitive to the needs of the poor and
minorities.
   ``Bush sees America from the penthouse down. Somebody must be
concerned about the basement, the foundation, where the common
people live,'' Jackson said.
   ``Why do I support Michael Dukakis? Why do I ask you to go and
support him with fervor? Because Bush does not care and (GOP
running mate Dan) Quayle does not understand. Dukakis cares and
understands,'' Jackson said.
   Dukakis won one of his warmest receptions of the campaign from
the predominantly black audience. He repeatedly reminded the crowd
that the election was in 60 days and, in spontaneous responses, the
audience _ comprised largely of black ministers _ responded with
loud shouts of ``Just 60 days.''
   The president of the group, Rev. T.J. Jemison, endorsed Dukakis
and asked those in the audience who would agree to back Dukakis to
stand up. Nearly everyone in the crowd of 1,000 people stood up.
</TEXT>
