<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Florence-Shelter     09-09 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Florence-Shelter,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Out Of The Storm: A Dry Place With a Pot Of Gumbo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. BERNARD, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evacuees who fled Hurricane Florence sat
around tables at the high school refugee center Friday night,
eating gumbo and talking about the storms they have known.
   ``It seems like you have to leave every time you turn around,''
said Joe Gonzales, 66, of Delacroix Island. ``We're evacuees.''
   ``It's aggravating,'' said Lazarus Gonzales, 48, a distant
relative who also lives at Delacroix Island.
   ``You know you're leaving home and you might not have a home to
come back to,'' said Joe Gonzales.
   So why not move away?
   ``Where we live is God's Little Acre,'' said Joe's wife Ruth,
65. ``It's the best place to live even though every time a storm
comes through, we've got to go.
   ``If our home's destroyed, we'll make another government loan
and build again.''
   Lazarus Gonzales added, ``When I leave there, it'll be in a
box.''
   They were among about 100 people who found refuge at the St.
Bernard High School cafeteria. Most were families, wise in the way
of hurricane survival. They had their blankets. Some brought TVs.
The Red Cross furnished plastic lounge chairs for makeshift beds.
   Dolores Lucas, 50, of Poydras, brought her sheet, blanket,
pillow and medicine.
   ``And I had to make sure I had my soft drinks and enough
cigarettes,'' she said.
   Lorance Evans, 61, also of Poydras, warned: ``Always fear a
storm. Don't try to be superman and fight it.''
   Lucas and Evans are brother and sister and came together. They
brought enough to stay two days.
   ``I've been through this so many times, I know I better come to
the shelter,'' Evans said.
</TEXT>
