<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0664 09-09 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0664,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says Reagan, Bush Have ``Punished Our Farmers''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs final 2 grafs pvs with 4 grafs, bgng ``Bentsen then,''
to recast with arrival and quotes at rally at union hall in
California</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMANA, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate Lloyd
Bentsen told farmers on Friday that his party would reverse
Republican trade and market policies that have ``punished our
farmers'' in the past eight years.
   Bentsen, speaking to hundreds of farmers and their families
sitting on hay bales at the World Ag Expo, said, ``235,000 farmers
have been ... driven off the land while George Bush has been vice
president.''
   ``It's time for a change from the policies and personalities
that devastated our farms, punished our farmers and left rural
America in the dust,'' he said.
   The Democrats, he said, would pursue an aggressive trade policy
that Bush and the Republicans have fought, and work to research new
uses for agricultural products to expand farm product demand.
   ``I've worked around farmers all my life, and the farmers I know
would much rather be making their money from the market place''
than from the government though subsidies, he said.
   Bush and Sen. Dan Quayle, his running mate, are not what farmers
want, Bentsen said.
   Republican Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., ``hit the nail on the head
when he said Bush doesn't know what's going on'' when it comes to
agriculture, Bentsen said.
   He continued, saying he was still quoting Dole, ``Agriculture is
not his strong suit. I don't know what it is, but it's not
agriculture.''
   As for Quayle, Bentsen noted that the Indiana senator passed up
an invitation to speak at the huge agriculture exposition. Farmers,
Bentsen said, ``just might ask him about agricultural policy and if
you did, he just might not have an answer.''
   The Texas senator was making his first trip to Iowa since
receiving his nomination.
   A poll in June by the Des Moines Register showed Dukakis with a
60 percent to 28 percent lead over Bush in the state. However, a
new poll released by the newspaper last weekend showed the edge had
shrunk to just 47 to 42.
   Bentsen, who was raised on a south Texas ranch, joined in the
spirit of the agricultural fair by mounting a big green John Deere
tractor with an eight-bottom plow and driving it for about 20 feet.
A highlight of the expo is a furrow-digging contest.
   Afterward, Bentsen met with reporters and said he was confident
Dukakis now knows more about Midwest agriculture since he made
controversial remarks in the primaries about how farmers should
start looking into Belgian endives.
   ``I'm sure he does,'' Bentsen said.
   Rep. Neal Smith, D-Iowa, told reporters the big early lead in
the polls for Dukakis was inaccurate, based on ``soft'' voter
opinions. The latest poll was probably more accurate, he said.
``Having a Democrat lead in Iowa is an unusual event,'' he said.
   Bentsen then went to California to take part in the Democrats'
day of giving the Republicans 60 days' notice of getting voted out
of office, a play on the plant closing bill that President Reagan,
Bush and Quayle fought before Reagan allowed it to become law.
   At a rally in a union hall in Bloomington, Calif., Bentsen told
a cheering crowd that ``we're here today to give the Republicans a
better break than they give the American worker.''
   ``Sure, we could provide notice the Republican way,'' he said.
``We could go there election eve and change the locks on the door.
   ``We could take the vice president's White House mess card and
cancel that. And we could take away Air Force II,'' he said. ``But
we agree with the vast majority of the American people who say 60
days' notice is fair.''
</TEXT>
