<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Germany-NaziHunters 1stLd-Writethru a0771 09-09 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Nazi Hunters, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0771,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nazi Hunters Lament Many War Criminals Dying Unpunished</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to fix typos in States and aggressive. ADDS 4 grafs
with Czech official criticizing West Germany's handling of war
crimes probes.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUDWIGSBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the world's leading
Nazi hunters predicted many war criminals would die unpunished and
said the United States was not aggressive enough in tracking down
former Nazis.
   ``We must do all that is possible so that we don't give Adolf
Hitler a posthumous victory,'' said Neal Sher, director of the U.S.
Justice Department's Office of Special Investigations.
   Sher was among dozens of war crimes investigators attending a
conference marking the 30th anniversary of West Germany's Central
Office for the Investigation of Nazi War Crimes.
   Others at the meeting, held in 18th century Ludwigsburg Palace,
included renowned Nazi expert Simon Wiesenthal and Shmuel
Krakowski, director of the Yad Vashem Holocaust Archives in
Jerusalem.
   Sher rejected any suggestions that investigators should end
their work just because many of the more notorious Nazis who
participated in large-scale massacres have been convicted, are dead
or have disappeared.
   ``Sometimes I hear that only the small fry are left,'' he told
The Associated Press before addressing the conference, ``but for
each of the victims there was a family that suffered. And if the
family members weren't themselves killed, they were emotionaly
scarred.''
   Sher said the United States did not do enough to find Nazi
criminals in the first decade after the war.
   ``I believe that the United States dropped the ball in not
pursuing as vigorously as we should have war criminals in the
United States,'' he said.
   One example he gave was Klaus Barbie, the ``Butcher of Lyon''
who succeeded in entering the United States after the war and is
now in a French prison.
   ``Tragically, for every visa that was granted to a persecutor, a
legitimate refugee was denied an opportunity to come to the United
States,'' Sher said.
   Wiesenthal told the AP: ``There were such big possibilities
after the war. The ones who have escaped _ they are a special
chapter, the lost possibilities.''
   Of the remaining war criminals, he said: ``They are getting old.
This is my daily problem. We have cases we can never bring to
court. They may die, but they won't die innocent,'' Wiesenthal said.
   In his speech to the conference, Sher said: ``We have to accept
the fact that vast numbers of those involved in crimes of
persecution will never be brought to justice in any form.''
   He said Nazi leaders' policies of killing witnesses and
destroying documents has hindered investigators and survivors of
the atrocities are dying from old age.
   ``The efficiency of the Third Reich's genocidal policies made it
a virtual certainty that many would go to their graves never having
been called to account for their pasts,'' Sher said.
   A Czech speaker, Karel Kamis, earlier accused West Germany of
not doing enough to prosecute Czech cases in the 1960s and 70s.
   Kamis, an official with Czechoslovakia's Commission for the
Investigation of Nazi Crimes, said that during those years his
country turned over 89 reports on suspected war criminals who were
living in West Germany.
   ``But not one of those cases resulted in prosecution,'' Kamis
said. ``The testimony of witnesses from Czechoslovakia was not
believed.''
   He said cooperation between the two countries in Nazi
investigations has improved in recent years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
