<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-President 2ndLd-Writethru a0775 09-09 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-President, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0775,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Tries To Stall Confirmation Of New President</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 6th pvs, `His party...' with PRI
delegate saying debate will continue to conclusion; PICKS up 7th
pvs `Cardenas and ..' SUBS grafs 12-14 pvs, `On Thursday ...' with
3 grafs, with PRI statement and demonstration outside palace</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDAJOY FENLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition delegates made a last-ditch
attempt Friday to stall Chamber of Deputies confirmation of ruling
party candidate Carlos Salinas de Gortari as Mexico's next
president.
   Through weeks of stormy debate, the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, known as the PRI for its initials in Spanish, has brushed
aside opposition claims that the election was rigged.
   An elderly opposition deputy, Alejandro Martinez Camberos of the
northern state of Durango, fell ill about 1:30 a.m. while waiting
for a chance to speak and was rushed to the hospital, according to
a spokesman for Martinez Camberos' Popular Socialist Party.
   The raucous debates reflect the largest opposition presence in
the legislature since the PRI was founded nearly 60 years ago. The
ruling party has a majority in the chamber, however, and the
opposition is diverse.
   ``If it's up to us, it (the confirmation) could last three days.
We plan to destroy their arguments one by one,'' Francisco Ortiz
Mendoza, a Popular Socialist spokesman, said shortly before the
session resumed Friday afternoon, several hours late. ``If they
allow an open debate, 200 speakers will go up to the podium.''
   His party belongs to the left-of-center Democratic Front
coalition headed by presidential candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas,
leader of a democratic reform movement.
   Orlando Arvizu, a PRI deputy from Hidalgo state, told The
Associated Press Friday evening the chamber debate would continue
without further interruption ``until we certify the presidential
election.''
   Asked how long that could take, he noted the chamber had worked
24 hours straight to certify the results of the congressional
elections.
   Cardenas and the rightist opposition say the confirmation
session is the last chance for the PRI and the government it has
controlled since 1929 to set a fraud-tainted election right.
   Opposition delegates walked out on a key legislative committee
but failed to prevent the panel from recommending confirmation
early Friday.
   The PRI members of the committee declared the July 6 election
valid and said Salinas won with 50.74 percent, slightly more than
the 50.36 the PRI-dominated Federal Election Commission gave him a
week after the election.
   It said Cardenas received 31.06 percent and Manuel Clouthier of
the rightist National Action Party, or PAN, got 16.81 percent.
   The PRI and the government have consistently rejected opposition
charges.
   On Friday, the party accused the opposition of trying to derail
an orderly presidential transition. ``What they are seeking is to
destabilize the government and degrade the republic, its
institutions and its politics,'' a PRI statement said.
   The 500-member chamber has been sitting as an electoral college
since mid-August, certifying the results of the legislative races.
It began working on the presidential certification Friday.
   About 150 riot police looked on as several thousand opposition
supporters gathered outside the Legislative Palace on Friday,
yelling chants against fraud, as they have every day the chamber
has met.
</TEXT>
