<DOCNO> AP880909-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 2243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-YonkersDeseg 2ndLd-Writethru a0743 09-09 0933</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yonkers Deseg, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0743,0957</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 11 grafs to UPDATE with judge refusing to consider
compromise offer, council meeting set for 11:55 p.m., picksup 3rd
pvs bgng ``We're only''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Yonkers Divided As Fines Hit $1 Million A Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With contempt fines at $1 million a day and
massive layoffs a day away, the City Council scheduled an
eleventh-hour meeting Friday night for yet another vote on a
court-ordered desegregation plan.
   The Council, which has refused to implement the plan for
low-income housing, planned a meeting at 11:55 p.m., said Mayor
Nicholas Wasicsko. If the plan is approved, the city could avoid
the layoffs and the $1 million fine.
   A lawyer for the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, Michael Sussman, said late Friday that the civil
rights group and the council had ``hammered out a fairly complex
agreement'' but the judge who imposed the potentially bankrupting
fines refused to consider the revised plan.
   ``He's not even going to listen to us,'' Sussman said of federal
District Judge Leonard Sand. ``I asked to present the proposal to
him and he didn't want to hear the details or the outline. He asked
only if the city was in compliance.''
   The city is being held in contempt of court for the City
Council's refusal, in a 4-3 vote, to carry out a housing
desegregation order.
   The biggest stumbling block remains the four recalcitrant
councilmen, Sussman said.
   ``Their position is they can't go in and vote on the ordinance
unless the changes we agreed to are made, and the judge just won't
give that agreement. His position is, you comply and after you
comply, you can come to me and I will consider your proposal,''
Sussman said.
   He would not disclose the proposed modifications.
   Changes in the plan also would have to be approved by the
Justice Department, which brought suit against the city with the
NAACP, and the department of Housing and Urban Development.
   Earlier, two of the defiant councilmen, spurning the chance to
change their stance on the issue, stayed away from a noon meeting
at which another vote on the plan was scheduled.
   But councilmen Peter Chema and Nicholas Longo showed up at City
Hall more than an hour later, with Longo confirming negotiations
were under way to end the segregation stalemate.
   ``We're only closer to the degree that there's communication
going on, and that's certainly a lot better than what was going on
a week ago, a month ago, a year ago,'' said Longo. ``They're not
hostile conversations.''
   Longo and Chema, along with councilmen Henry Spallone and Edward
Fagan Jr., have refused to accept a federally ordered housing plan.
   The entire council and Mayor Nicholas Wasicsko gathered Friday
afternoon and voted to transfer $819,200 to pay Thursday's fine.
   As the councilmen entered City Hall, some of the crowd outside _
angered by the report of negotiations _ shouted, ``Sellout!
Sellout!'' But another section applauded the vote to pay the fine.
   ``While I appreciate the sentiment of the cheers, there is
nothing to cheer about,'' the mayor said. ``We've just authorized
to pay fines in excess of $800,000. ... I sincerely hope this is
the last time we have to make such a transfer.''
   The fine payment came as support for opposition to Sand's plan
was starting to wane.
   ``We've done all we can. We went to the Supreme Court and didn't
get anywhere,'' said Henry Knetter, 65, a northeast Yonkers
resident. ``There's no garbage pickup. There might not be any
police protection. It may be time to wise up.''
   Knetter spoke for an increasing number of residents whose
opposition to low-income housing has softened as the realities of
Sand's fines began hitting home.
   Phone lines at City Hall were jammed this week with callers
urging one councilman to change his vote, Wasicsko said.
Uncollected garbage sits outside many homes; children going to
school have no crossing guards; the three town libraries close
Saturday.
   But at a contentious meeting Thursday, Fagan and other
councilmen criticized Sand, saying ``I hope there's a God up there
that will strike him down.''
   The fines, which began at $100 per day, doubling daily until
hitting a $1 million cap on Friday, forced the state Emergency
Financial Control Board to impose a ``Doomsday Plan'' aimed at
providing public safety services while delaying bankruptcy.
   Phase One starts Saturday, with 447 of the city's 1,834
employees receiving layoff notices as part of a $20 million savings
package. The Parks and Recreation Department will close; the
Panning Department will be slashed to two employees.
   Other layoffs will come from the departments of real estate,
civil service, fiscal services and public works. Control board
Chairwoman Gail Shaffer, New York's secretary of state, said the
cuts will keep Yonkers solvent until 1989.
   If the council refuses to back down, additional cuts are set for
Sept. 17 and 24, Oct. 8 and 22, and Nov. 5, Shaffer said.
   Sand, who in 1985 ruled the city had practiced segregation in
housing and education for 40 years, imposed the fines after the
four councilmen refused to implement part of his plan.
   City schools were desegregated under a plan approved by Sand,
and the City Council initially agreed to build 1,000 units of
low-income housing in January. But they rejected the housing plan
at an Aug. 1 meeting, prompting Sand to impose fines which would
double every day.
   The U.S. Supreme Court upheld Sand's fines on appeal, but placed
a $1 million cap on the daily amount.
</TEXT>
