<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0013EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WorldBank-Africa     09-09 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Bank-Africa,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>African Governments Coping Despite Setbacks, Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite continuing economic setbacks, African
governments are coping well with vital tasks of adjustment for the
future, the World Bank's vice president for Africa said Thursday.
   ``Those things which were manageable were being managed very
well by the Africans'' during the past year, Vice President Edward
V.K. Jaycox told reporters.
   Still, the general economic situation in Africa south of the
Sahara Desert continues to cause concern because the regional gross
product declined in 1987, a reversal of 1986 attributed mainly to
drought, he said.
   ``But recognizing that ``there is nothing we can do about
weather, war or terms of trade ... it was an extremely positive
year,'' Jaycox said.
   In the last two or three years about 30 governments have
undertaken structural economic adjustments and ``have seriously
come to grips with problems'' that were blocking economic growth,
he said.
   Jaycox, an American, was named to head the new World Bank
department for all African countries south of the Sahara formed in
the 1987 reorganization of the Washington-based lending
institution. The bank has been working with governments in the
region to reduce subsidies, promote realistic pricing and exchange
rates and encourage private initiative.
   Governments that once trumpeted support for a new world economic
order, ``rather than waiting for the day when somehow there is a
change in the economic order, are in fact coping'' with the
existing system and ``it's going to pay off,'' he said.
   With substantial reforms under way in half to two-thirds of the
countries south of the Sahara Desert, evidence is growing that
``sustained reforms do lead to improved economic performance and
growth,'' Jaycox said.
   He added that ``in contrast to generally shrinking world market
shares in the past, Africa actually increased its share of world
exports of some commodities in 1986-87.''
   The best real growth performances were registered by Ghana,
Guinea, Guinea-Bissau and Kenya, with 5 to 6 percent increases in
gross national product, Jaycox said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
