<1ST_LINE>r p AM-MassachusettsDeficit     09-09 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Massachusetts Deficit,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Leaders Say FY89 State Budget Could be $1.2 Billion Short</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican legislators said Thursday that the
state budget signed by Gov. Michael S. Dukakis in July is out of
balance by as much as $1.2 billion because the Democratic
presidential candidate is overestimating tax collections and is
spending too much.
   ``The results are very sobering and very disquieting about the
future of this state,'' House Minority Leader Steven Pierce said.
   Senate Minority Leader David Locke joined Pierce in calling once
again on Dukakis to demand that the Legislature return to session
immediately to address the fiscal situation and other concerns.
   Noting that the House and Senate have been in recess since early
July and may remain on vacation until after the Nov. 8 election,
Locke denounced ``what has to be the longest vacation of any
legislative body in the history of mankind.''
   Although the Legislature voted for the current $11.6 billion
budget in July and Dukakis does not have the power to
single-handedly summon the Legislature back to work, the
Republicans laid both problems at Dukakis' feet.
   Dukakis has made the federal deficit a leading theme of his
presidential campaign.
   ``Based on our analysis, there is going to be a shortfall that
may exceed a billion dollars,'' Locke, R-Sherborn, said, adding
that the voters have a right to know whether Dukakis and Democratic
legislative leaders plan tax increases.
   Michael Lellyveld, spokesman for Finance Secretary Frank Keefe,
insisted that the budget was balanced. ``Their numbers don't add
up,'' Lellyveld said.
   The fiscal year, which began in July, is now two months old.
According to the Revenue Department, tax receipts in July dropped
15.6 percent from July 1987 and rose 2.8 percent in August compared
to the same month in 1987.
   According to the Republican analysis, the two-month average
increase of 1.4 percent is far below the traditional pace of
receipts in the first two months of the fiscal year. Indeed, based
on the traditional proportion of all taxes brought in during those
two months, the 12-month total could be off by more than $437
million.
   Moreover, the Republicans assert that the governor is depending
on ``ephemeral'' and ``flimsy'' projections of $245 million in
extra revenues this year, based on stepped-up enforcement by the
Revenue Department and the state auditor.
</TEXT>
