<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Carlucci,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci, Chinese Discuss Arms Sales Opposed By Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China said Thursday it told visiting U.S. Defense
Secretary Frank Carlucci it exports weapons in a responsible manner
but did not say if it halted missile shipments to Iran and Saudi
Arabia _ sales Washington opposes.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Jin Guihua told a weekly briefing:
``In meeting with Mr. Carlucci, the Chinese leaders reiterated the
policy of the Chinese government on the question of China's export
of military products.''
   He repeated China's assurances that it follows a ``serious and
responsible'' policy in selling arms and that there was no reason
to be concerned about China's arms trade.
   Carlucci told reporters Wednesday after two days of talks that
he was ``fully satisfied'' with Chinese assertions that its growing
arms sales to the Middle East and other areas of the world would
not have a destabilizing effect on those regions.
   He declined to say if China had changed its stand on arms sales
that include supplying Iran with Silkworm anti-ship missiles and
Saudi Arabia with medium-range ballistic missiles.
   The sales have strained Chinese-U.S. relations.
   Carlucci said Wednesday night that his talks with senior leader
Deng Xiaoping, Premier Li Peng, National Defense Minister Qin Jiwei
and others leaders were the ``best discussions we have ever had''
on arms sales, adding: ``I hope we can put this issue behind us.''
   Carlucci, on his first visit to China, left Beijing Thursday for
the ancient capital of Xian. He is also to visit a naval base in
Shanghai before concluding his five-day visit Saturday.
   At the Wednesday meeting with Deng, the 84-year-old leader said
he hoped Vice President George Bush, who headed the American
liaison office in Beijing in 1974-75, would win the presidential
election in November.
   Jin declined to clarify whether Deng's statement was personal or
reflected China's official position on the presidential race,
saying only that the elections were the internal affairs of the
United States.
</TEXT>
