<HEAD>Congress Approves U.S.-Canadian Firefighting Mission</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs:SUBS 1st graf include full congressional approval and CORRECT
day from Wednesday to Thursday. Pickup 2nd graf pvs bgng ``The
legislation...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress adopted on Thursday a bill that would
allow the U.S. government to contract with Canada to use that
country's firefighting resources to battle Western forest fires.
   The legislation would allow the U.S. Forrest Service to
reimburse Canada, thereby allowing that nation to send firemen,
aircraft and other equipment. House Agriculture Committee staffers
said Canada has 35 planes ready and available.
   The U.S. government does not currently have the authority to
compensate the Canadians.
   ``The devastating forest fires we're seeing throughout the
Northwest are causing a devastating impact on the firefighting
capabilities of the U.S. government,'' said Rep. Kika de la Garza,
D-Texas, chairman of the Agriculture Committee.
