<2ND_LINE>AM-City Opera,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Keene To Succeed Sills as Head of City Opera</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christopher Keene, a 41-year-old conductor who
served as musical director of the New York City Opera, will succeed
Beverly Sills as the company's general director, an opera official
said Thursday.
   The City Opera board decided to appoint Keene at a Thursday
afternoon meeting, said Martin Oppenheimer, vice chairman of the
board.
   ``I can confirm that he was appointed as (general) director with
great enthusiasm by the board, and that enthusiasm is shared not
only by board members but by the staff and Beverly Sills,'' he said
in a telephone interview.
   Miss Sills, 59, announced in May that she would be resigning
effective Jan. 1 as general director of the nation's second-largest
opera company in terms of budget and number of performances.
   Oppenheimer called Keene ``one of the outstanding young
conductors of this country'' and noted that he was ``particularly
well known for his conducting of modern works.''
   Keene, who began his association with City Opera as winner of
the first Julias Rudel Award in 1969, was music director of the
company from 1983 to 1986, when he resigned the post.
   Since then, he has been head of a performing arts center in
Buffalo, N.Y., and head of the Long Island Philharmonic, said
Oppenheimer.
   The 44-year-old City Opera, with a budget of $26 million for
fiscal 1989 and a 20-week summer-fall season plus a spring musical
comedy season, is second in size to the Metropolitan Opera in New
York.
</TEXT>
