<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NaziHunters     09-09 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nazi Hunters,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nazi Hunters Meet To Honor West German Associates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUDWIGSBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nazi hunters from the United
States, Israel and other countries gathered Thursday to pay tribute
to a West German office that has helped track down war criminals
for 30 years.
   At a Thursday night reception at the Ludwigsburg Palace, West
German officials praised the office's work and said their
countrymen must remember the Nazi era so that such atrocities are
never committed again.
   ``We owe this office profound thanks for 30 years of work,''
said Ulrich Hartmann, a regional administrative official.
   The West German Central Office for the Investigation of Nazi War
Crimes has helped convict more than 6,000 people on various war
crimes charges since its founding in 1958.
   A total of 160 war criminals have been sentenced to life
imprisonment because of the office's work. Life in prison is the
highest possible sentence in West Germany, which has no death
penalty.
   Speakers at the reception said the search for Nazi war criminals
was far from over.
   ``Today, 30 years after the creation of the central office, the
job is still not done,'' said Heinz Eyrich, Baden Wuerttemberg
state's justice minister.
   Nazi hunters, including Simon Wiesenthal, traveled to
Ludwigsburg to attend a special symposium Friday marking the
anniversary of the Central Office. Others gathering for the event
were Nazi hunters from Austria, Israel and East bloc countries.
Neill Sher, from the office of special investigations for the U.S.
Justice Department, was also attending.
   Despite its successes, the Central Office _ like other groups
that track down suspected Nazi war criminals _ is having increasing
difficulty in its work because the crimes happened so long ago,
said Alfred Streim, head of the Ludwigsburg-based office.
   ``It is becoming more and more difficult to have a successful
case, because witnesses are dead or they don't want to talk
anymore,'' Streim told The Associated Press.
   ``Some of them (witnesses) just say `Please let me have my
peace,''' he said.
   Streim pointed to the Aug. 29 acquittal of former SS sergeant
Wolfgang Otto on charges of participating in the 1944 execution of
Ernst Thaelmann, head of Germany's Communist Party.
   Otto was convicted in 1986 but a higher court overturned the
verdict saying there was no evidence to prove that Otto had been at
the scene of Thaelmann's execution.
   The appeals court acquitted Otto for the same reason, having to
rely on evidence from the original trial.
   But Streim's office continues to contribute to some significant
successes even though the crimes occurred long ago.
   In January of this year, a West German court convicted Gottfried
Weise, a former SS guard at the Nazis' Auschwitz concentration camp.
   The 66-year-old Weise, charged with fatally shooting five
Auschwitz inmates including an 8-year-old child, was sentenced to
life in prison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880909-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0053EDT</FILEID>
