<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ForestFires-Polebridge     09-09 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires-Polebridge,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents, Ignoring Evacuation Order, Save Tiny Town's Buildings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fires Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POLEBRIDGE, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wind-driven flames of a raging
forest fire were raining down on this remote northwestern Montana
town the other night when some of its people ignored the evacuation
order and made a stand.
   ``The way the fire was burning and the way it came over those
trees, I didn't expect anything to be here,'' Buck Kates said
Thursday. ``It looked like it was raining embers all over those
trees. It hit and just bounced and the whole works went up.''
   But when the flames had passed Wednesday night, the town's only
businesses were still standing, thanks to Kates and others who
braved a wall of fire to hose down the buildings.
   Polebridge, tucked into the forest on the west edge of Glacier
National Park, has a general store listed on the National Register
of Historic Places, a bar, restaurant and a dozen other buildings.
   Residents were told Wednesday to evacuate as the 14,000-acre Red
Bench fire drew near, but Kates and several others stayed behind
with a tanker truck to save Polebridge while the fire devastated
the surrounding countryside.
   ``I seen what they were doing, and I figured, hell, if they're
going to stay, I will, too,'' he said. ``You're too busy to get
scared.''
   Kates said the crew made two-mile runs to Hay Creek, filled the
truck with water and then drove back to hose down the buildings.
They didn't stop until their path to the creek was blocked by
flames.
   The historic Polebridge Mercantile was saved, as was the Great
Northern Saloon and restaurant.
   The fire was burning Thursday in Glacier National Park, having
jumped the North Fork of the Flathead River on Wednesday. Dozens of
cabins, homes and ranch buildings were destroyed north of
Polebridge, authorities said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
