<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cuba-Honduras     09-09 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-Honduras,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Leader Says U.S., Contra Presence in Honduras
Temporary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The presence of U.S. military forces and
Nicaraguan rebels in Honduras is temporary, the vice president of
the Honduran Congress said Thursday in the Cuban capital of Havana.
   ``There is no support in the Honduran Congress for a permanent
U.S. military base,'' Jose Antonio Fernandez Guzman was quoted as
saying by the Cuban government news agency Prensa Latina.
   In a dispatch monitored in Mexico City, Prensa Latina quoted
Fernandez Guzman as saying that irregular forces of any nationality
must not remain in his country.
   Honduras has served as a staging ground and supply route for
U.S.-backed Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras, since 1981. U.S.
troops there routinely conduct military exercises with Honduran
forces.
   ``Any convention or treaty to install U.S. military bases in
Honduran territory necessarily would have to be approved by the
legislature, where there is no support for a project of this
nature,'' Fernandez Guzman said.
   Guzman heads an 11-member Honduran congressional delegation
visiting Cuba at the invitation of Cuba's National Popular Power
Assembly, a legislative organ of the island nation's communist
government.
   It is the first visit to Cuba by a Honduran congressional
delegation since the government of President Fidel Castro took
power in 1959.
   The Hondurans plan to tour scientific, cultural and economic
projects throughout Cuba before leaving on Sept. 15, Prensa Latina
said.
</TEXT>
