<DOCNO> AP880909-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Australia-Koalas     09-09 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Australia-Koalas,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koala, Platypus Exports Banned By State of New South Wales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New South Wales on Friday became the
first state in Australia to ban koala and platypus exports, saying
that sending the marsupials to zoos overseas amounted to a virtual
death sentence.
   ``Their survival rate is unacceptable,'' said New South Wales
Environment Minister Tim Moore. ``We simply cannot guarantee their
safety.''
   News reports noted that Moore announced the ban after a Japanese
request for three more koalas and a pair of platypuses to boost
Japan's breeding program.
   At least eight koalas have died in overseas zoos in the last
three years, five of them in Japan. Besides Japan, the only other
overseas zoos with koalas are at San Diego and Los Angeles.
   Moore also ruled that no platypuses be sent overseas until more
research is done into their failure to breed in captivity.
Zoologists said only one pair of platypuses had bred in captivity
in Australia during the past 40 years.
   The pouched animals are unique to Australia.
   Moore said he was not suggesting there is anything wrong with
conditions in Japanese zoos but that Australia was probably the
only country with veterinary surgeons skilled in the treatment of
koalas.
   He said most deaths seemed to be caused by stress and chlamydia,
a venereal disease that has been ravaging koala colonies in recent
years. Moore did not mention old age as a cause of death.
   Moore said the export ban would remain in force until there is
an immunization program for chlamydia or methods found to deal with
koala stress.
   Koalas feed on only a few varieties of eucalyptus trees and are
found only on the east coast of Australia.
   A spokesman for federal Environment Minister Graham Richardson
said exports of koalas and platypuses already are restricted
because the animals fall under the category of rare or endangered
species.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880909-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Rosson     09-09 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Rosson,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hal Rosson, Pioneering Cinematographer Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oscar-winning cinematographer Hal
Rosson, director of photography for such classic films as ``The
Wizard of Oz'' and ``Singin' In The Rain,'' has died at age 93.
   Rosson, who died Tuesday, is credited with work on at least 133
films in a career spanning the early days of silent films to the
talkies to the golden age of the new megastudios.
   His film credits also include such movies as ``Tarzan the Ape
Man,'' ``No Time for Sergeants,'' ``Treasure Island,'' and ``El
Dorado,'' his last film.
   Born in New York, he got his first work in films about 1912 with
Metro Pictures Corp.
   The first color film that he worked on, ``The Gardens of
Allah,'' won the Academy Award for color in 1936.
   His use of black-and-white turning to startling color in ``The
Wizard Of Oz'' was copied by dozens of other filmmakers.
   ``He really was a wonderful person and a wonderful contributor
here in Hollywood,'' said Jean Turner, spokesman for the American
Society of Cinematographers in Los Angeles.
   Briefly married to actress Jean Harlow in the 1930s, Rosson had
a family tradition of involvement in film. His brother Arthur
Rosson was a successful director and his sister was secretary to
film magnate Cecil B. DeMille for 35 years.
   Rosson came out of retirement to work on the 1967 John Wayne
film, ``El Dorado.'' He moved to Palm Beach in 1973.
   Funeral arrangements were planned in Hollywood, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880909-0196 </DOCNO>
