<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BargeAground 1stLd-Writethru a0816 09-09 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Barge Aground, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0816,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Barge Splits, Spills Thousands of Gallons of Chemical</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with spill downgraded, river to
reopen early Friday; picks up 3rd graf: `The barge ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A barge ran aground and cracked open Thursday
near Natchez, Miss., spilling more than 5,000 gallons of a
flammable chemical into the Mississippi River, the U.S. Coast Guard
said.
   The Coast Guard revised its initial estimate of a 40,000-gallon
spill after closing a 50-mile stretch of the river to shipping _
from the point of the spill to Angola, La. The river would reopen
early Friday, officials said.
   The barge was loaded with styrene, a clear chemical which floats
on water and catches fire easily, Meidt said. Authorities said the
vapors can irritate the eyes and throat and can cause loss of
consciousness. Direct contact with styrene can burn the skin.
   The chemical is used principally in the manufacture of plastic
and rubber.
   Meidt said a tug owned by Apex Towing Co. of St. Louis, Mo., was
pushing 13 barges when at least one went aground and cracked.
   At least three crew members reported some queasiness after the
accident, but they did not seek immediate medical attention, he
said.
   The cause of the accident had not been determined, he said.
   The styrene began drifting downstream immediately. Meidt said
there was little evidence of the chemical spill at Natchez Thursday
afternoon.
   ``The cleanup is being facilitated by nature,'' he said.
   Farther down river, a containment boom described by officials as
a floating fence was suspended in the water to stop the chemical
from flowing into the Atchafalaya River.
   The Coast Guard did not known how long the river would be closed
to traffic. No northbound vessels were reported waiting and only
one southbound vessel was stopped near Natchez, Meidt said.
   Asked if the low water level of the drought-stricken Mississippi
River contributed to the accident, Lt. Cmdr. Robert Pond said,
``It's certainly a possibility.''
</TEXT>
