<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:FallArts ADV14   09-09 1115</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Fall Arts, ADV14,1161</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Sept 14 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>No Blockbusters This Fall, But an Earthquake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's an entertainment season without
blockbusters, unless you count that earth-bustin' new show at
Universal Studios.
   But then again, tap-dancing bears, a dying swan and the holy
images of a golden empire also punctuate the fall lineup of arts
and live entertainment.
   As part of an ongoing $140 million expansion, the Universal
Studios tour in Los Angeles, which takes visitors to
behind-the-scenes glimpses of filmmaking, launches ``Earthquake:
The Big One,'' beginning Nov. 21. The experience will be housed in
a 22,000 square foot soundstage where the ground will shake, rattle
and roll.
   Tramways will collapse and tourists will be ``trapped'' amidst
falling telephone poles, walls, ``live'' cables, a train wreck and
60,000 gallons of rushing water. But not to worry: It's all show
biz and special effects.
   Dancing bears who move with the alacrity of humans are the stars
of the Moscow Circus, which launched a 15-city North American tour
in Toronto. Featuring trapeze artists and 17 tigers as well, it
concludes Jan. 1 in San Francisco.
   Another gift from the Soviet Union this season is prima
ballerina Maya Plisetskaya, who will perform Fokine's ``The Dying
Swan'' with the Martha Graham Dance Company, a role she has not
danced in New York in 18 years.
   And from Greece comes an exhibition of Byzantine icons and
frescoes, which opened at the Walters Art Gallery in Baltimore on
Aug. 21. It runs through Oct. 16. Icons, devotional images made in
tempera on gold-flecked wooden panels, represent the spirituality
of the Byzantine Empire (330 A.D. to 1453). The exhibit will be at
the Center for Fine Arts in Miami from November to January before
touring elsewhere in the United States through January, 1990.
   Here are highlights of other events taking place here and abroad
this fall:
   DANCE:
   The New York City Ballet performs at the New Tokyo Bay NK Hall
theater in Tokyo, Japan, from Sept. 15-25. The repertory includes
George Balanchine's ``Agon'' and ``A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' and
Jerome Robbins' ``Afternoon of a Faun.''
   The company's winter season begins at the New York State Theater
on Nov. 21. ``The Nutcracker'' will be danced Dec. 1-31.
   The Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater began a celebration of
its 30th anniversary with a seven-week tour of Europe beginning
Aug. 26 in Spain. The company will give 39 performances in 14
cities before returning to the United States to dance two weeks in
Kansas City.
   It opens its annual New York season at City Center on Dec. 7
with a special anniversary gala.
   The Martha Graham Dance Company returns to City Center for a
three-week run beginning Oct. 4. It will feature a world premiere
by Miss Graham to a score by Pierre Boulez. Other highlights
include ``Letter to the World,'' Miss Graham's vision of Emily
Dickinson's life, with actress Kathleen Turner in the role of ``She
Who Speaks,'' and ``El Penitente,'' a look at the purification
rites of the Penitentes of the American Southwest, starring Mikhail
Baryshnikov as the Penitent. Both dances premiered in 1940.
   The Jose Greco Company brings the fire and passion of Spanish
dance to the Joyce Theater in New York from Sept. 20 to Oct. 2.
   Pilobolus, with its body bending studies of whimsy and
sensuality, opens at the Joyce on Dec. 13 and runs through Jan. 8.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   OPERA:
   The Metropolitan Opera opens its season Sept. 26, with a
performance of ``Il Trovatore,'' starring Eva Marton, Sherrill
Milnes, Luciano Pavarotti and Fiorenza Cossotto. James Levine
conducts.
   Handel's ``Giulio Cesare'' will have its Met premiere on Sept.
27. The cast will include Kathleen Battle as Cleopatra and Tatiana
Troyanos as Caesar. The production marks the Met conducting debut
for English Baroque music specialist Trevor Pinnock.
   The new production of ``Gotterdammerung,'' premieres Oct. 21.
Hildegard Behrens will sing Brunnhilde.
   The Washington Opera opens its season Nov. 5 at the Kennedy
Center with ``Tosca,'' starring Placido Domingo. Adriana Morelli
makes her American debut as the tempestuous title heroine. Gian
Carlo Menotti conducts.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MUSIC:
   Huey Lewis and The News continue their world tour to hype their
ambitious new album ``Small World,'' which ventures into the realms
of jazz, reggae, soul and New Orleans swing.
   Dizzy Gillespie and his quintet blow their way into New York's
Blue Note on Sept. 13, playing through Sept. 18. Sarah Vaughan will
perform there from Oct. 11-16.
   The Cleveland Quartet celebrates its 20th anniversary season
with a tour of the Soviet Union and five European countries from
Sept. 1-30.
   The American Symphony opens Oct. 23 at Carnegie Hall with a
concert celebrating the 65th birthday of composer Ned Rorem,
playing a debut of his ``Frolic.'' On Nov. 13, the orchestra
salutes composer Morton Gould's 75th birthday by performing the
world premiere of his ``Chorales and Rags.''
   Amnesty International launched a six-week world tour to promote
human rights on Sept. 2 in London. It features Sting, Tracy
Chapman, Bruce Springsteen and Peter Gabriel.
   Bob Dylan continues his tour with a performance at Radio City
Music Hall on Oct. 17 and 18, his first ever at the famed art deco
theater.
   Other tours include: B.B. King, New Edition, George Michael,
Monsters of Rock, Pink Floyd, Def Leppard, Sade, Elton John.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ART:
   A Degas retrospective at New York's Metropolitan Museum of Art,
the first major exhibition of Degas' work in 50 years, runs from
Oct. 11 through Jan. 8. It includes paintings, pastels, drawings,
prints, sculpture and photographs as well as depictions of
racetrack scenes and jockeys, ballet dancers, brothels, bathers and
landscapes. It opened Feb. 9 at the Grand Palais in Paris and moved
to the National Gallery of Canada in Ottawa.
   ``Joshua Johnson: Freeman and Early American Portrait Painter,''
has a run at the Whitney Museum of American Art, Fairfield County,
Conn., from Sept. 9-Nov. 8. It features a retrospective of late
18th and early 19th century works of one of the nation's earliest
and most esteemed black portrait painters.
   Harvard University continues an exhibit of Rothko paintings
through Oct. 2 in Cambridge, Mass.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   FILM FESTIVAL:
   The 26th New York Film Festival opens Sept. 23 with Pedro
Almodovar's ``Women on the Verge of a Nervous Breakdown.'' The
movie marks his festival debut.
   The festival closes Oct. 9 with ``Red Sorghum,'' a portrait of
1930s China. It is the directoral debut of Zhang Yimou, the
cinematographer of ``Yellow Earth.''
   Eighteen directors make their debut in the festival, which also
highlights the new British cinema, Russian cinema in the age of
``glasnost,'' the new Asian cinema and American independents.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
