<NOTE>For Release Wed, Sept 14 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Fall Home Video: Touch That Dial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
  There's a face-off this fall between a short,
bug-eyed alien and a pretty blonde pining for her prince.
   ``E.T. The Extraterrestrial'' and Walt Disney's ``Cinderella''
are among the big attractions for home video fans this season, and
the good news is they will retail for only $24.95 and $26.99,
respectively.
   ``E.T.,'' the biggest grosser of all time, has made more than
$228 million in film rentals, and has an estimated worldwide box
office of nearly $500 million. It is being released by MCA Home
Video.
   The movie, produced by Steven Spielberg, tells the story of an
endearing little alien from another world who becomes marooned on
Earth. It is befriended and given sanctuary by children who protect
it from government agents, and who help E.T. return home.
   Walt Disney's ``Cinderella'' earned close to $33 million last
year when it was re-released to movie houses. Disney Home Video
hopes the beautifully animated film will soar past sales figures
for its best-selling ``Lady and the Tramp'' video, which has sold
3.2 million copies. Released in 1950, the 75-minute feature was
nominated for two Academy Awards, including best song for ``Bibbidy
Bobbidi Boo.''
   Also out this fall from Orion Home Video is a series of
contemporary foreign film classics, including Claude Berri's
award-winning ``Jean de Florette,'' which won four British
``Oscars'' including best film, and its sequel ``Manon of the
Spring.''
   Also for September from MCA is ``Swing _ The Best of the Big
Bands,'' a wonderful collection of vintage 1940s and '50s film
footage of such artists as Duke Ellington, Nat ``King'' Cole, Tommy
Dorsey, Charlie Barnet, Gene Krupa and Billie Holiday.
   
   The two-volume package will be available on laser videodisc with
a suggested retail price of $34.98 each.
   Here are other home videos available this fall:
   _ ``batteries not included,'' a whimsical fantasy from the
Steven Spielberg factory, starring Hume Cronyn and Jessica Tandy as
an elderly couple who hold out against a ruthless realtor. From MCA.
   _ ``The Milagro Beanfield War,'' Robert Redford's beautifully
filmed movie about poor Mexican farmers in the Southwest who battle
an evil developer over water rights. From MCA.
   _ ``Switching Channels,'' a poor remake of the newsroom classic
``The Front Page'' and ``His Girl Friday,'' starring Burt Reynolds
and Kathleen Turner. From RCA-Columbia Home Video.
   _ ``Broadcast News,'' James L. Brooks' highly polished look at
TV news starring Holly Hunter and William Hurt. From CBS-Fox Home
Video.
   _ ``White Mischief,'' a look at the degenerate mores of a
British enclave in Kenya during World War II. From Nelson
Entertainment.
   _ ``The Last Emperor,'' the Academy Award-winning epic about
China's last emperor who lives to see the Cultural Revolution. From
Nelson Entertainment.
   _ ``Beetlejuice,'' Michael Keaton's manic portrayal of a ghost
who tries to help a new ghost couple rid their house of the
obnoxious new owners. From Warner Home Video.
   _ ``School Daze,'' Spike Lee's sometimes humorous, sometimes
bittersweet, sometimes muddled look at life on a black college
campus. From RCA-Columbia.
   _ ``The House on Carroll Street,'' an espionage thriller
starring Kelly McGillis. From HBO Home Video.
   _ ``Zelly and Me,'' Tina Rathbone's touching tale of a
love-starved child, her love-starved grandmother and nanny. From
RCA-Columbia.
   _ ``Defense of the Realm,'' Gabriel Byrne, Denholm Elliot and
Greta Scacchi in a thriller about a political coverup. From Nelson.
   _ ``Murder by Decree,'' Christopher Plummer, James Mason and
Donald Sutherland in a thriller about Sherlock Holmes on the trail
of Jack the Ripper. From Nelson.
   _ ``The Ruling Class,'' Peter O'Toole's Oscar nominated
performance about a 14th century earl who thinks he's Jesus Christ.
From Nelson.
   _ Concert sessions from HBO Video: ``Carly Simon: Live From
Martha's Vineyard''; ``James Brown & Friends''; ``Sass & Brass,''
starring Sarah Vaughan with such horn players as Dizzy Gillespie,
Chuck Mangione and Maynard Ferguson; and ``The All-Star Reggae
Session,'' starring Jimmy Cliff, Ziggy Marley and the Melody Makers.
   _ ``Thin Man'' collection, six movies in the delicious
comedy-detective series starring William Powell and Myrna Loy. From
MGM-UA Home Video.
   _ Collection of eight Bette Davis films, including ``Jezebel,''
``Now, Voyager'' and ``Dark Victory.'' From MGM-UA.
   And also from MGM-UA, such timeless classics as ``The
Apartment,'' ``West Side Story,'' Clint Eastwood's ``Hang 'Em
High,'' ``Midnight Cowboy,'' ``North by Northwest'' and ``Raging
Bull.''
</TEXT>
