<1ST_LINE>s i BC-NorthAfrica ADV18-2Takes   09-09 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-North Africa, ADV 18-2 Takes,0832</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: North Africa _ A Search for Unity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: this is the main story of a package of three</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Free of the colonial yoke for three decades, the
five Arab nations of North Africa known as the ``Maghreb'' still
rely heavily on foreigners to keep them going and the democracy
many North Africans fought for still eludes them. But now the five
are seeking solutions in unity.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soaring 300 feet into the air on the
heights overlooking Algiers is a monument to the heroes of the
National Liberation Struggle. The three intertwining concrete
leaves are of Polish design and Canadian execution.
   In neighboring Morocco, a French engineering company is building
the world's largest mosque.
   In Tunisia, a Dutch company is draining the evil-smelling lake
between the capital and its wealthy suburbs.
   In Mauritania, French engineers operate the iron mines and the
railroad providing the country's main source of income.
   In Libya, foreigners operate the oil fields and work at many
other jobs in the country.
   The first three decades of independence have left a vague legacy
of disappointment in the five North African Arab countries known as
the ``Maghreb'' _ the Arab West _ and a reliance on foreigners to
do the important work remains widespread.
   No one dares question the wisdom of going it alone _ that would
put in doubt the very core of their existence. But citizens in the
five Maghreb countries are asking themselves whether their leaders
have gone the right way about getting the most out of their
sovereignty.
   This public discussion has provided the context for the current
debate on unity.
   Not one of the five countries can be described as democratic.
With the exception of Morocco, none has had a genuinely free
election since the end of what was mainly French colonial rule.
   Algeria, which became known as the Democratic People's Republic
after winning its independence war against the French in 1962, is
still recovering from the 13-year dictatorship of Col. Houari
Boumedienne, who died in 1978. His successor, Chadli Bendjedid, is
trying to remove the ``old guard'' without rocking the boat.
   Tunisia shook off the 32-year dictatorship of its ``president
for life,'' Habib Bourguiba, removed from office on grounds of
senility in 1987, only to fall into a more moderate form of
autocratic rule under Zine El Abidine Ben Ali.
   Morocco has a limited form of democracy, but King Hassan II is
the supreme arbiter of all political events. No one rules but the
king.
   Libya is known as the ``Jamahiriya'' or republic. Col. Moammar
Gadhafi is its heaven-sent ruler and no one dares oppose him.
Mauritania has plunged from one military coup into another.
   With such a legacy, it is surprising that the Maghreb countries
have not seen more violence and bloodshed than they have.
   They have set the scene for several air hijackings, American
planes bombed Libyan cities to ``punish'' Gadhafi, and Israeli
aircraft bombed the headquarters of the Palestine Liberation
Organization in Tunis. The PLO's No. 2 man, Abu Jihad, was killed
in his Tunis home by assassins believed to have come from Israel.
   Islam remains the common link for the region. From Tobruk in
eastern Libya to Dakhla in the Western Sahara, muezzin can be heard
calling the faithful to prayer, and most work stops throughout the
holy month of Ramadan.
   Only in Tunisia did Bourguiba once try to stop the Ramadan fast,
publicly drinking orange juice at midday in a much-publicized
gesture of defiance.
   The gesture failed, and Tunisia today is as religious-minded as
ever. With the exception of Morocco, whose king claims direct
descent from the Prophet Mohammed, Islamic fundamentalism is on the
upsurge everywhere.
   In Algeria, the authorities tried to meet this revivalism with a
revolutionary form of socialism. Hard-line officials still try to
keep these principles alive, but few Algerians really believe they
will bring salvation.
   Throughout the region unemployment, as high as 40 percent in
urban centers, is the most pressing problem. Health and education
are close behind. Inflation is rearing its head. No one seems to
have any remedy. The population is soaring by nearly 4 percent a
year, the underlying cause of most other problems.
   Despite official protestations to the contrary, women are
subjected to such discriminatory practices as polygamy, denial of
inheritance rights and unilateral divorce. Only the educated
minority among the women think of protest.
   With the exception of a narrow fertile coastal strip, most of
the land is desert. About 12,000 years ago, it was a fertile region
of fruit trees and tropical animals, as testified by prehistoric
rock paintings. All this has gone. The Sahara moves steadily
outward by hundreds of square miles a year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
