<DOCNO> AP880909-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 2006EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-NorthAfrica ADV18-1stadd   09-09 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-North Africa, ADV 18-1st add,0644</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>ALGIERS: a year.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   With the 19th century collapse of the Turkish Empire, most of
the Maghreb became a French preserve. Only Libya, then a gathering
of impoverished tribes, fell to Italy.
   The discovery of major oil deposits throughout the region made
all the difference.
   Morocco alone had no oil. But it did have massive deposits of
phosphates, the natural chemical needed for fertilizers. Morocco
has nearly one-fourth of all the world's known deposits of
phosphates, without counting the Western Sahara.
   This former Spanish colony, which continues the Moroccan
coastline 1,600 miles to the southwest, was intended mainly as an
outer defense for the Canary Islands. Most of it was left as a
wilderness. Under Moroccan pressure, Spain abandoned the territory
in 1975, and it ultimately fell to Morocco.
   For the past 13 years, a forgotten war has raged between the
Moroccan army and the Algerian-backed Polisario movement seeking
independence for the Western Sahara. But the guerrillas have made
little headway.
   The Moroccans assembled superior firepower and a 1,500-mile wall
that barred access to the territory. The guerrillas proved unable
to breach the wall in strength or to prevent its extension.
   Mauritania, which at first joined with Morocco in suppressing
the guerrillas and then flipped to the opposite side, ended up on
neither side.
   As a result of these moves, the Polisario was gradually
eliminated from the struggle. King Hassan accepted a U.N. proposal
for a controlled international referendum to settle the territory's
future. Unless the Polisario finds some way to block it, the
referendum is likely to take place some time in 1989. It is
generally expected to lead to a Moroccan victory.
   In his vigorous campaign for the Moroccan cause, Hassan forged a
treaty of union with Libya. The treaty stopped Libyan support to
the Polisario but it seriously upset Morocco's American friends.
   When the Polisario had been defeated, the treaty was no longer
needed and Hassan used the first pretext to cancel it.
   Meanwhile, Gadhafi made a series of ill-fated attempts to merge
with his neighbors. They all ended in failure. Everyone likes
Gadhafi's money, but no one wants to be seen selling his
independence to the highest bidder.
   At the same time, the North African leaders bowed to widespread
public pressure and began a serious attempt to find some kind of
unity. The five met in Algiers in June and agreed to work toward a
North African confederation.
   Tunisia and Libya hurriedly restored the diplomatic relations
they had broken over Libya's expulsion of more than 30,000 Tunisian
workers three years earlier. Algeria and Morocco agreed to ignore
Polisario protests and did likewise.
   Hassan arrived in Algiers in a chartered car ferry, and when
Bendjedid came to meet him, the two men fell into each other's
arms. All present felt they saw history in the making.
   Gadhafi again was the odd man out. He played the clown, walking
up and down on the terrace outside the meeting room, declaring the
summit was a ``gathering of has-beens.''
   It took all the diplomatic skill of President Ben Ali of Tunisia
and Secretary-General Chedli Klibi of the Arab League to persuade
Gadhafi to join the meeting.
   Ultimately, they worked out a plan for a greater Maghreb
confederation. It is only on paper, so far, and all the real work
remains to be done.
   But Hassan had learned at first-hand about the advantages of the
European Economic Community, which turned down Morocco's request to
join. He is a fervent advocate of creating a similar community in
North Africa. His arguments won the day.
   The summit instructed the bureaucrats to work out the details.
It remains to be seen how far they will succeed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday, Sept. 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
