<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: North Africa _ War in the Desert</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-North Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RABAT, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The forgotten war that has been raging
across the barren wilderness of northwestern Africa may soon draw
to a close as the two sides _ Morocco and the Marxist Polisario
Front _ are forced into a compromise over the territory of Western
Sahara.
   The framework for the compromise is likely to be suggested by
the United Nations. It could be a long way from the extreme demands
made by the Polisario Front.
   The main reason for the change will be the Algerian government's
disillusionment with the Polisario fighters, whose 13 years of
guerrilla war has not brought them control of a single Saharan city.
   A referendum is to determine the wishes of the original
inhabitants of the disputed territory, whether they now are in the
Moroccan-held cities or in the Polisario-run camps in Algeria.
   Everything lies in the question to be put in the referendum:
Will the estimated 100,000 inhabitants and their adult children be
asked simply whether they want independence, or will they be asked
to endorse the Polisario as their ``sole legitimate
representative?''
   Endorsement of the Polisario would give the guerrilla movement
the right to determine the territory's future, even if trson, I feel a
lot vented toward me by other
whites,'' he said.
   Cleve McDowell, a top official with the state branch of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, said
there had been ``several problems in that area. There is blatant
hostility in that area of the state that does not exist elsewhere.''
   Macon is a town of 2,400 people in east-central Mississippi.
   ``I'm extremely disappointed, but not shocked,'' McDowell said.
``I think it was an action by a person with a low mentality who
thought he was responding to what the white public wanted.''
   The church's adult members, who are mostly college-educated
professionals, have been active in working with the poor.
   ``Our main interest is not just going to church on Sunday. Our
goals are to cater to the needs of the community, but we target
those people in the lower socioeconomic condition,'' Hatcher said.
</TEXT>
