<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   09-09 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0580</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. have
moved quickly to seek access to the government's evidence for its
fraud case against the Wall Street firm. But people familiar with
the firm's strategy predicted prosecutors could mark time until the
U.S. attorney's office finishes its criminal probe.
   The sources, who spoke on condition they not be identified,
contended Thursday that the civil charges filed by the Securities
and Exchange Commission contained no surprises.
   Under civil law rules for pretrial fact-gathering, Drexel
theoretically now has the right to see the SEC's evidence. But the
U.S. attorney, who has been conducting a grand jury inquiry
paralleling the SEC probe, could intervene to halt the discovery
process if he thought it would compromise his effort.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The junk bond market disregarded the
government's huge civil suit against Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.,
which is the largest underwriter of the high-yield, high-risk
corporate debt securities.
   Prices of junk bonds traded in the secondary market were nearly
unchanged Thursday, bond traders said. Many analysts predicted few
future price fluctuations would result from the suit filed by the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite rising interest rates, U.S. businesses
plan to boost plant and equipment spending to record levels this
year as capital investment remains one of the strongest sectors of
the economy, the government has reported.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday a survey found that
businesses planned to spend $429.4 billion this year, after
adjusting for inflation. That would top the previous high of $391.6
billion set in 1985.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans took out $2.6 billion more in
consumer credit than they paid off in July, marking a sharp
slowdown from the pace of growth during the first half of the year,
the Federal Reserve Board says.
   The Fed released a report Thursday showing consumer credit
expanded at an annual rate of just 4.8 percent last month, down
from an annual rate of 10.2 percent from January through June.
   The report said the slowdown reflected a drop in auto sales in
July and lackluster sales of other consumer goods.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic congressmen have criticized federal
regulators for relying on promissory notes to rescue ailing savings
and loans.
   In a hearing Thursday by the House Banking Committee, lawmakers
called the rescue plans ``a massive shell game'' that will only
postpone the crisis until after the Reagan administration leaves
office.
   Over the past three weeks, the Federal Home Loan Bank Board has
pledged more than $12 billion to rescue or close 48 savings
institutions. About half has been in the form of interest-bearing
notes, which obligate the insurance fund for thrifts to billions of
dollars in annual payments for a decade.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate moved closer to approving new curbs
on textile, apparel and shoe imports, possibly setting up a trade
confrontation with the Reagan administration on the eve of the
November elections.
   The Senate continued debate Thursday on the bill, which would
freeze this year's textile and apparel imports at 1987 levels and
allow 1 percent annual growth thereafter. It is similar to a bill
President Reagan vetoed in 1985.
   Proponents said the bill would save jobs, but retailers said
limiting imports would reduce consumers' choices and might boost
prices.
</TEXT>
