<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   09-09 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0585</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's two largest purchasers of home
mortgages have agreed on ways to simplify the often time-consuming
process of obtaining a home mortgage.
   The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. and the Federal National
Mortgage Association, which announced the agreement Thursday, buy
mortgages from primary lenders and resell them as mortgage-backed
securities, thus increasing the pool of money available to make
home loans.
   The Mortgage Bankers Association, an organization of local
lenders, estimated that future progress on streamlining the process
eventually could cut in half the 45 to 60 days it takes to get a
mortgage approved.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hyatt Corp. has offered to buy rival hotelier
Ramada Inc. for an estimated $397 million.
   Ramada officials were noncommittal after Hyatt announced its bid
Thursday, but investors bid Ramada stock up $2.12{ a share to $9.75
in New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Spokesman Joe Cole said the Ramada board would meet to discuss
the offer before the close of business next Friday, the deadline
set by Hyatt chief Jay Pritzker in his offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Utah financier Ian Cumming has made a $1.2
billion cash bid for a majority interest in Utah Power & Light Co.,
an offer that is about $600 million less than the bid by
Oregon-based Pacificorp accepted by UP&L.
   UP&L spokesman Dave Mead said Thursday the privately-held
utility, which is in the process of trying to gain regulatory
approval for a merger with Pacificorp, has not responded to
Cumming's offer. He said the company had no further comment.
   Cumming, who is chairman of Leucadia National Corp., a New
York-based holding company with sales of $320 million in 1986,
could not be reached for comment Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. plans to cut
6,000 jobs in two years from its Network Operations Group and
expects to reduce employment elsewhere in the company as well.
   The cuts in the Network Operations Group, which runs the
long-distance network, will amount to about 8 percent of the unit's
74,000 employees, spokesman Burke Stinson said Thursday. AT&T will
try to achieve as many of the cuts as possible through voluntary
retirements, resignations and reassignments to other parts of the
company, but will not rule out layoffs, Stinson said.
   AT&T's total employment has risen by about 12,000 this year to
about 315,000 after having dropped steadily since the 1984
divestiture of the local operating companies.
