<DOCNO> AP880909-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-InsiderTrading-Junk Bjt   09-09 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Insider Trading-Junk, Bjt,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drexel Charges Have Little Effect on Junk Bond Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY6 of Sept. 8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission's
long-awaited civil suit against junk bond pioneer Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. has had little effect on the market for the
high-yield, high-risk securities.
   Late Thursday, junk bond prices in the secondary market were
little changed from Wednesday. Many analysts predicted few future
price fluctuations would result from the suit filed by the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
   ``I think it was anticipated that this (suit) was going to take
place, and when it actually happened ... it was a bit of a
non-event,'' said Anthony Naylor, a corporate bond analyst at the
securities firm Rodman & Renshaw Inc. The federal civil complaint
filed Wednesday charged Drexel, its junk-bond chief, Michael
Milken, and others with securities violations ranging from insider
trading to falsifying records as part of a secret arrangement with
former speculator Ivan F. Boesky.
   The government acknowledged more than a year ago that it was
investigating Drexel and its junk bond operations, which have been
used to finance some of the biggest corporate takeovers of the
1980s. The probe began after Boesky was charged in the nation's
biggest insider-trading scheme.
   There also has been widespread speculation that the U.S.
attorney's office, which is conducting a parallel investigation of
Drexel, would file criminal charges, perhaps as early as next month.
   ``It's unlikely those chrages would have any effect on the
market,'' said Marshall B. Front, a partner at the Stein Roe &
Farnham, which manages a $100 million junk bond mutual fund. ``None
of my clients have expressed any concern.''
   Milken pioneered the use of junk securities in the late 1970s as
a way of providing capital to a vast majority of companies that
otherwise had limited access to public bond markets because their
credit ratings were too low.
   The only way of raising money for many of those companies had
been through stock sales or loans from banks and insurance
companies, which generally carried numerous restrictions and higher
interest rates.
   Junk bonds generally pay about four percentage points higher
interest than comparable U.S. Treasury securities, essentially
giving investors a higher return to compensate for the higher risk
of default.
   The bonds have since become a staple for many small- and
medium-size companies looking for financing and for institutional
investors such as pension funds and savings associations seeking
income.
   Junk bonds also have been a major financing weapon for corporate
raiders seeking to raise millions or billions of dollars for
hostile takeovers.
   The lucrative market initially was almost solely dominated by
Drexel, but in recent years attracted a host of more traditional
Wall Street firms. Drexel's market share has eroded to about 50
percent of the $17 billion in underwritings so far in 1988.
   ``The market has grown so large it transcends the act of any
individual brokerage firm or underwriter,'' said Robert Waill, a
managing director at the securities firm L.F. Rothschild & Co.
``That's why the SEC charges (against Drexel) are having no effect
on the market.''
   Still, some bond analysts said the Drexel charges might prompt
some companies to put off future issues until the market has time
to digest the consequences of the suit. About 20 deals, valued at
between $6 billion and $8 billion, could be affected, estimated
Gene Wong, a managing director for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Wong said Drexel-underwritten issues of highly leveraged,
volatile companies might also be hurt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880909-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-InsiderTrading-Clients     09-09 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Insider Trading-Clients,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drexel Client Stands By Embattled Firm</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Insider Trading-Drexel Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. is getting support
from Wickes Cos. Inc., a California-based company that the
government says was a victim of insider trading by Drexel.
   Wickes said Thursday it did not expect civil insider trading and
fraud charges against Drexel to have any effect on a proposed
leveraged buyout that depends $423 million in financing through an
issue of junk bonds by Drexel.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission charged Wednesday that
Drexel acted behind Wickes' back in 1986 while Wickes was trying
unsuccessfully to take over National Gypsum Co. The charge was part
of a broader civil suit brought by the SEC accusing Drexel and
others of numerous securities frauds.
   ``Obviously if the charges are ultimately proven, this would be
distressing,'' said Wickes spokesman Michael Sitrick.
   ``However, based on our current knowledge of the situation we
would not anticipate that the filing of this complaint will have
any negative impact on our relationship with Drexel or any of its
people with whom we work,'' Sitrick said.
   Wickes, a building-supplies retailing company based in Santa
Monica, Calif., on Aug. 21 announced plans for a management-led
buyout that values the company at about $600 million.
   Drexel is the dealer-manager and investment banker on the
transaction, which is being held open until Oct. 20 while Bear,
Stearns & Co. searches for bidders that might be willing to offer
more than the management-led group.
   The SEC charged that Drexel, Michael Milken, who is head of its
junk-bond business, and his brother Lowell Milken secretly used the
organization of speculator Ivan Boesky to improperly sell Wickes
common stock for Drexel's benefit.
   The government also alleged that Drexel, Michael Milken and
Milken associate Cary Maultasch used Boesky's organization to buy
stock in National Gypsum ``in breach of fiduciary duties owed ...
to Wickes.''
   Drexel made about $6.7 million off the illicit purchases while
being paid about $1 million for its services by Wickes, the SEC
said.
   Even though Wickes' bid for National Gypsum failed, the episode
was not a loss because Wickes came away with a profit of $3 million
after selling its shares back at a higher price than it paid for
them.
   Maxxam Industries Inc. of Los Angeles, which the SEC said also
was cheated by Drexel, declined comment Thursday on the
allegations. The SEC said Drexel used the Boesky organization to
buy for Drexel the stock of Pacific Lumber Co., which was the
target of a Maxxam tender offer in 1985.
   The complaint says Drexel received more than $22 million in fees
from Maxxam for services rendered in connection with its
acquisition of Pacific Lumber.
   Drexel was supported Wednesday by Triangle Industries Inc.,
which has floated about $1.8 billion in junk bonds through Drexel
for various deals over the past five years.
   Drexel's dealings with Triangle were not named in the SEC
complaint.
   ``We're standing behind Drexel at this point, certainly. We do
not intend to stop doing business with a firm on the basis of an
SEC complaint, especially one we've had such a long and fruitful
relationship with,'' said Triangle spokesman Mark Dorsett.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
