<DOCNO> AP880909-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0314EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TextileBill-Retailers Bjt   09-09 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Textile Bill-Retailers, Bjt,0753</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Textile Restrictions Could Limit Choices, Boost Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed law to further limit imports of
textiles, apparel and shoes also will lead to increased costs and
tighter supplies for the nation's retailers _ and higher prices for
consumers, storeowners say.
   The bill now before the Senate ``opens up a lot of problems,''
said David Jackson, a spokesman for the apparel retailer Gap Inc.
   Under the bill, this year's textile and apparel imports would be
frozen at 1987 levels and growth would be limited to 1 percent
annually in succeeding years.
   That would create what the retail industry calls sourcing
problems: stores will have a harder time obtaining merchandise.
   ``It opens up a whole parade of horribles for us,'' said Jackson.
   Rob Longendyke, a spokesman for Spiegel Inc., the catalog
retailer that also owns the apparel retailers Eddie Bauer and
Honeybee, agreed. ``The first effect would be to send us and other
companies scrambling to find what sources we can onshore that can
produce the merchandise we need.''
   ``The infrastructure for the textile industry does not exist in
this country anymore,'' Longendyke said. ``But there are some small
resources and the first thing that would happen is everyone would
go scrambling after those small resources.''
   ``In some cases, the consumer says he wants a particular kind of
sweater, weave or fabric, but we may not be able to find any kind
of sources'' to supply them, Jackson said.
   Consumers may find some garments, which now are heavily
imported, hard to find and much more expensive. Retailers said the
cost of many other apparel items likewise would be affected if the
bill passed and was signed into law by President Reagan.
   The bill ``most definitely will have a serious effect on prices,
both in (wholesale) costs of goods as well as the retail price,''
said Jackson.
   Higher prices would put retailers between a rock and a hard
place. Industry watchers say one reason for sluggish apparel sales
has been ``sticker shock,'' consumer rebellion against higher
clothing prices.
   Some manufacturers and stores already have absorbed some of the
higher costs for clothes, but would be unable to do so if the bill
became law.
   Retailers could hold the line on prices, Longendyke said, but it
would mean compromising on quality. For example, retailers could
use more domestic wool rather than Australian wool, which is
considered the highest quality, he said.
   Wall Street analysts differed over how much of an impact the
bill might have. Imports to some extent already have been slowed in
recent years by the rise of the dollar, which makes them more
expensive.
   ``It would probably drive up prices to some extent,'' said
Eileen Gormley, an analyst who follows the textile and apparel
industries for Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. She said some
clothing categories would be affected more than others.
   Jay Meltzer, an analyst at Goldman Sachs & Co., doubted the bill
would have a major effect on the apparel industry.
   ``Imports are down this year vs. a year ago to date and will
surely be down for the year,'' he said. ``There's really not much
indication that they're going to go soaring next year, so a 1
percent-a-year growth limit would have no effect on present
conditions for some time.''
   Meltzer predicted the competitiveness of the apparel industry
would keep prices in line.
   Some retailers already have taken steps that would blunt the
impact of the bill's enactment.
   ``We have been busily going about trying to develop textile
resources onshore,'' said Longendyke.
   Whether the bill ever will become law is uncertain. Reagan
vetoed a similar measure three years ago and the administration is
suggesting the same fate may await the latest version.
   U.S. textile and apparel manufacturers have sought import limits
since a wave of Asian textile and apparel imports jolted the
industry in the early 1980s.
   The companies and labor unions say restrictions are needed to
salvage jobs in an industry whose existence they claim is
threatened by foreign competition.
   Retailers say the apparel industry does not need the bill.
   Al Dietzel, a spokesman for the apparel retailer Limited Inc.,
said, ``The textile and apparel industry probably has the highest
rate of employment and they are working at the highest level of
capacity of any industry in the U.S.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
