<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Shakespeare-BankCards     09-09 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shakespeare-Bank Cards,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Face of the Bard to Decorate Bank Cash Cards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To deposit, or not to deposit; that is the
question.
   Starting next week, British banking customers may have a reason
to wax dramatic, as they start using a new series of cash machine
cards bearing pictures of William Shakespeare.
   Starting Monday, the face of Shakespeare _ portrayed in a
hologram that smiles when tilted _ will grace the cash dispenser
cards of 33 of Britain's savings and loan societies and banks.
   Jim Parsons, an official of the association of banks that
monitors money clearing systems, said Wednesday that the ``Bard
Cards'' will be available to all customers of its 33 members by
1990.
   The card can be used to guarantee checks and withdraw money from
cash machines.
   Parsons said he came up with the idea of using Shakespeare's
face after the European Economic Community's ``Eurocheque''
check-guarantee cards began using a hologram of Beethoven.
   ``I thought we should stay with the arts, so for the U.K., why
not Shakespeare?'' he said. ``I had no difficulty in persuading my
colleagues to accept the idea.''
   Asked if there had been any criticism of using such a renowned
literary figure for financial purposes, Parsons said, ``No
difficulties. ...Shakespeare was not cut off from the literary
world. I'm sure if Shakespeare were here today he would not have
had any objections to this.''
</TEXT>
