<DOCNO> AP880909-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0823EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-WPPSSTrial     09-09 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-WPPSS Trial,0702</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Jury Selection Starts, Four More Utilities Sidelined
^By JIM KLAHN
^Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-eight prospective jurors have been
selected in a giant fraud lawsuit over the default on bonds sold to
build two Washington Public Power Supply System nuclear power
plants.
   U.S. District Judge William Browning said he expected to have a
full panel of 20 jurors by the end of today.
   Meanwhile, four small utilities were being sidelined Thursday in
an effort to ease confusion in the complicated case.
   Browning questioned jurors en masse before trimming the number
to 38 Thursday. With time off early next week for a Jewish holiday
and primary elections, opening arguments were expected on Wednesday
and Thursday.
   Dismissal of a couple of jurors indicated how far-reaching the
Washington Public Power Supply fraud case is. One woman was let go
because she said her husband's retirement fund might include supply
system bonds.
   The civil case, one of the largest in the history of American
law, revolves around the default in 1983 by WPPSS on $2.25 billion
on bonds sold to finance construction on two nuclear power plants
in Washington state.
   Settlements have removed most of the original 100-plus
defendants sued by bond buyers, and plaintiff attorneys on Thursday
said four small utilities were being removed in a table-clearing
move that will make the trial easier to understand for jurors.
   Attorney Mel Weiss of New York, an attorney for class action
plaintiffs, said the four utilities are Central Oregon Cooprative
in Oregon, and Steilacoom Municipal, Alder Mutual and Mason Public
Utility District No. 1 of Washington. Formal announcement was
expected early next week.
   Weiss said agreements included a settlement with the
15,000-customer Central Oregon utility. The other three, with just
6,000 customers among them, were severed from the lawsuit with
agreement of the plaintiff attorneys.
   Removal of the four leaves 17 utilities among defendants, and
all 17 are members of the WPPSS board of directors.
   Six other members of the WPPSS board, including Seattle City
Light, have already settled with plaintiff bondholders and class
action plaintiffs.
   Generally it has cost WPPSS board members more to settle than
the non-WPPSS members that were among the 88 utilities contracting
with the supply system to build the two nuclear plants. However,
insurance money accounted for much of the settlements made by the
six WPPSS members off the hook in the lawsuit. The remaining 17
reportedly have little insurance money available, and they had
contracted for about two-thirds of the output of the two nuclear
power plants.
   Weiss said leaving just WPPSS member utilities at the
defendants' table would be less confusing to jurors. While the
Steilacoom, Alder and Mason utilities were severed from the case,
it did not remove them as defendants and they presumably still
could face legal action by plaintiffs, or could figure in a
settlement.
   Other defendants include the construction engineering firms of
United Engineers and Ebasco, and the financial advisory firm Blyth
Eastman.
   While warning that trial could last for ``several months,''
Judge William Browning told jurors he would do what he could to
accommodate those selected as jurors, including maximum payment of
$35 per day, parking assignments and accommodations in town for
people from beyond the metropolitan area.
   The trial had originally been expected to take eight months to
two years, but settlements have cut that time to one year at most.
   Browning told jurors they would serve Monday through Thursday
most weeks, but because they might have to work an occasional
Friday, he would pay them for five days a week.
   He also said the government would pay as much as $72 a day for
jurors outside the Tucson area who would have to move to town for
the duration of trial.
   Though 20 will be selected for trial, only some of those will be
called upon to render a verdict. A minimum of six is required in a
federal civil suit. Browning also said court would not be held for
most of the month of December and for a month next summer, if the
trial is still in session.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
