<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Run, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0041,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinatown Thrift is Target of Run In Case of Mistaken Identity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to restore `million' to 3rd graf.
PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `The headline ... A version moving on
general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A case of mistaken identity spurred a $2 million
run on a Chinatown thrift.
   Hundreds of customers, most of them Chinese, lined up Thursday
at Elmhurst Federal Savings and Loan Association to withdraw money
after confusing the thrift with a financially troubled bank in the
suburb of Elmhurst.
   The assets of that institution, United Security Bank, Inc., were
frozen by a judge last week after a business customer reported
receiving a $1.8 million loan in the form of a check that bounced.
The bank was not properly licensed, the state said.
   ``The headline was, `Elmhurst Bank Fails,''' said David G.
Plummer, president of Elmhurst Federal Savings and Loan
Association. ``I think many of our customers don't even know
there's a town named Elmhurst.''
   Despite a sign in the thrift's window explaining the difference
in Chinese, customers weren't taking any chances, and about 300
showed up Thursday to withdraw their money, Plummer said.
   Withdrawals for the week totaled nearly $2 million by the end of
the day, he said, although he did not expect the run to threaten
his institution.
   ``This is a $35 million branch. We're one of the strongest
savings and loans in the nation,'' he said. ``If we lost $3
million, that's no problem.''
   Plummer said he believed the worst was over Thursday, because
community leaders were working to get the word out, talking with
customers in the thrift's lobby and through a local Chinese
newspaper.
   ``I understand that they say this one is not in trouble, but
it's better to be safe,'' said Tom Moy, 34, a depositor who stood
in line for an hour before getting in the door Thursday.
   Barry Yee translated to the crowd outside, trying to explain the
mixup.
   ``My parents told me that in China, banks were not insured and
when one closed, you just lost your money,'' he said. ``That's what
they believe is happening here today. They just believe in old
ways.''
</TEXT>
