<1ST_LINE>r f PM-InteriorMoney 1stLd-Writethru f0029 09-09 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Interior Money, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0029,0625</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with administration quotes;
picks up 2nd graf pvs, The proposed ...; SUBS 3rd graf pvs to show
bill was passed by Senate. A version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House is studying a possible veto of
legislation that would bar the Reagan administration from any
last-minute oil lease sales in portions of the Pacific and Atlantic
oceans and the Gulf of Mexico, an official said today.
   ``We are still considering our position,'' said Barbara Clay, a
spokeswoman for the White House Office of Management and Budget.
``We are carefully reviewing the legislation.''
   The proposed prohibitions, opposed by the administration, are
contained in the fiscal 1989 spending bill for the Interior
Department, U.S. Forest Service and some Energy Department research
programs.
   The $9.9 billion appropriations package is heading toward the
president's desk following its approval by Congress on Thursday.
The Senate passed it by voice vote; the House endorsed it on a
359-45 roll call.
   The margin of approval in the House indicates the legislation
has sufficient support to ensure its backers could win a
veto-override vote.
   The bill would continue, through September 1989, a ban on
Interior Department sales of oil leases off the coasts of northern
California and Massachusetts and reinstitute a drilling ban for the
waters off southwestern Florida.
   This would stop the administration from holding lease sales for
these areas during its final months in office. Both presidential
candidates _ Republican George Bush and Democrat Michael Dukakis _
have said they oppose petroleum development in sensitive offshore
waters.
   Dropped from the compromise package was a House provision, also
drawing fire from the administration, that sought to require at
least 50 percent U.S. labor and materials for petroleum facilities
along the outer continental shelf.
   The spending bill, which contains no major new programs, would
provide $190 million for the Energy Department's clean-coal
research efforts in fiscal 1989, which begins Oct. 1.
   This is $335 million less than the administration said it needed
to fulfil President Reagan's pledge to Canada to spend $2.5 billion
over five years in a search for ways to curb U.S. emissions of
pollutants that cause acid rain.
   In a letter to lawmakers last month, James C. Miller III,
director of the White House Office of Management and Budget, cited
the refusal of Congress to commit $525 million to the clean-coal
program in fiscal 1989 as another reason the bill might be vetoed.
   Since then, however, administration officials and congressional
leaders have discussed their differences and may be near an
agreement that could make the partial funding acceptable to the
White House, according to an administration source who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Miller also has objected to giving states more than $150 million
for energy conservation programs, which he said should not be
federally financed. His letter also complained about putting more
than $60 million into Indian health facilities when existing
facilities have a 50 percent vacancy rate.
   The bill calls for the National Park Service to receive $1
billion in fiscal 1989, some $280 million more than Reagan proposed
in his budget and about $100 million higher than fiscal 1988.
   The U.S. Forest Service would receive $1.84 billion in fiscal
1989, an increase of about $625 million over the current level and
about $230 million more than the administration requested.
   The bill sets a goal of selling 11.45 billion board feet of
lumber from public forests, 198 million more board feet than the
administration proposed. Road-building money would total about $176
million, down some $20 million from fiscal 1988.
</TEXT>
