<1ST_LINE>r f BC-OPEC-Meetings     09-09 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-OPEC-Meetings,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Early OPEC Price Meeting Debated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuela and Algeria have called
for a special meeting of OPEC's price-monitoring committee to help
stem the decline in oil prices, a Saudi Arabian newspaper reported
Friday.
   The newspaper Al-Sharq Bali quoted unnamed ``high-level Arab oil
sources'' as saying the two OPEC member nations proposed a meeting
for Sept. 21 in Bali, Indonesia.
   Some oil futures prices, meanwhile, moved slightly higher
following the report. On the New York Mercantile Exchange, October
contracts for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude,
rose 5 cents to $14.53 per 14-gallon barrel.
   The Saudi newspaper said a ``moderate'' member of the
five-member pricing committee was opposed to holding a special
meeting, saying it expected world oil prices to improve as winter
approaches.
   The unidentified member also was opposed, the newspaper said,
because the pricing committee would have to call for an emergency
full session of the 13-nation cartel and a regular meeting already
was set for Nov. 21 in Vienna.
   Besides Venezuela and Algeria, the other members of the OPEC
pricing committee are the oil ministers of Saudi Arabia, Nigeria
and Indonesia.
</TEXT>
