<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Technicolor     09-09 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Technicolor,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Company to Acquire Technicolor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Carlton Communications PLC said
Friday it has agreed to buy Technicolor Inc., the film duplicating
company whose trademark appears on many top movies, for $780
million.
   Carlton will buy Technicolor, which makes prints of movies and
also has a presence in the booming videocassette duplication
market, from a company controlled by Revlon Group Inc. Chairman
Ronald Perelman.
   The acquisition would put Carlton in the front lines of the U.S.
and European markets for videocassette duplication and film
processing.
   Besides those activities, Carlton has interests in other
television post-production services and manufactures high-tech
video production equipment used by broadcasters.
   ``The acquisition of Technicolor represents a unique opportunity
for Carlton to establish itself as the largest provider of services
to the growing television and film markets in the U.S.A. and in
Europe,'' Carlton said in a statement.
   The announcement follows Carlton's purchase in March of
Philadelphia-based Modern Video Inc., a high-speed duplicator of
videocassettes, for about $83 million.
   Technicolor, based in Los Angeles, is privately held, as is its
parent company, MacAndrews & Forbes Group Inc. of New York.
MacAndrews & Forbes, which makes licorice and cigars, is owned by
Perelman.
   The sale is expected to be completed Oct. 4, pending approval of
Carlton shareholders, the company said.
   Following the acquisition of Technicolor, Carlton will have
videocassette duplication plants in California, Michigan,
Philadelphia, London, and the Netherlands. It will also have film
processing plants in Los Angeles, New York, London and Rome.
   Technicolor makes the prints of movies that are distributed to
theaters. Its major print customers include the Warner Bros.,
Tri-Star and Paramount studios and it makes videocassettes for
Warner Bros., Disney, Lorimar, Home Box Office and CBS-Fox.
   For all of 1987, Technicolor had an operating profit of $46.9
million on sales of $288.9 million.
   Carlton estimated that for the year ending Sept. 30 it will post
pre-tax profits of at least $82 million, up around 40 percent from
the previous year.
</TEXT>
