<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LordGellerLayoffs     09-09 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lord Geller Layoffs,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lord Geller Ad Agency To Lay Off A Third Of Employees</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lintas:USA, without space, is cq in 4th graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The advertising agency fired last week by
International Business Machines Corp. said Friday it was laying off
about a third of its 270 employees.
   Lord, Geller, Federico, Einstein Inc. said the cuts of about 90
people were effective immediately and were intended ``to match the
level of its current and anticipated business.''
   IBM announced Sept. 2 it was firing its long-time ad agency,
which created the memorable campaign featuring a Charlie
Chaplin-like character and the more recent one reuniting the former
stars of the television show ``M-A-S-H.''
   It hired Lintas:USA, a unit of the Interpublic Group of
Companies, and Wells, Rich Greene Inc. for its U.S. advertising
duties.
   IBM reportedly accounted for about half of Lord, Geller's $200
million in annual billings. The firm, a unit of WPP Group PLC, has
been in turmoil since six of its top executives walked off the job
in March, complaining of interference from WPP.
   Lord, Geller said it would pay employees' salaries for 90 days
and maintain medical benefits and life insurance until the end of
the year.
   ``We are saddened that we are forced to take these actions. The
people affected are highly dedicated and talented professionals,''
Bill Wardell, the president, said in a statement. He said the
company's commitment to its other clients and to seeking new
business was unchanged.
</TEXT>
