<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-09 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Lower On Pre-Weekend Profit-Taking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed strongly lower
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade on pre-weekend profit-taking
and book-squaring ahead of Monday's government crop production
report.
   ``This is the first significant correction we've had in several
weeks,'' said Joel Karlin, an analyst with Research Department Inc.
in Chicago.
   Karlin said traders planning to stay home Monday for the
beginning of the Jewish New Year took profits Friday to minimize
their risk ahead of the Agriculture Department's crop production
report, which will be released after Monday's close.
   The corn and soybean markets were shaken by a respected grain
analyst's prediction the USDA would report little drought damage to
crops occurred last month.
   Chicago-based analyst Conrad Leslie estimated 1988 U.S. corn
production at 4.42 billion bushels and soybean production at 1.46
billion bushels. Those numbers compare with the Agriculture
Department's August estimates of 4.48 billion bushels of corn and
1.47 billion bushels of soybeans.
   Leslie's numbers were significantly higher than the average
private analyst's estimates of 4.21 billion bushels of corn and
1.42 billion bushels of soybeans.
   At the close, wheat was 3 cents to 7\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $4 a bushel; corn was 2 cents
to 5 cents lower with September at $2.85{ a bushel; oats were 3\
cents lower to { cent higher with September at $2.67 a bushel;
soybeans were 6 cents to 18{ cents lower with September at $8.78 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
