<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 2123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AT&T-Software     09-09 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AT&T-Software,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T Hoping For Compromise With Rivals On Unix Software</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. said Friday
progress is being made toward ending a bitter dispute over control
of Unix, the base computer software that has pitted it against such
rivals as International Business Machines Corp. and Digital
Equipment Corp.
   ``We're still in negotiations'' with the Open Software
Foundation, which was formed by IBM, Digital, Hewlett-Packard Co.
and others to create a version of Unix that would not be under
AT&T's control, AT&T spokesman John Skalko said.
   Unix, which was invented by AT&T, has become popular with other
computer makers because it allows programs to run on a wide variety
of computers without alteration. However, the software has
splintered into many versions.
   The Open Software Foundation confirmed Friday it plans to base
its new version of Unix on IBM's version, AIX, but AT&T is trying
to get the group to change its plans and use the AT&T version.
   Skalko denied a report Friday which said AT&T Chairman Robert E.
Allen told securities analysts the Open Software Foundation had
agreed to use AT&T's version.
   Skalko said the report was apparently based on a
misinterpretation of Allen's speech Thursday in Boston in which he
said, ``We see the computer industry moving towards agreement on
some version of our own Unix operating system as an industry
standard.''
   Allen only meant to assert that Unix was originally developed by
AT&T, Skalko said.
</TEXT>
