<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 2124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SingerSuit     09-09 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Singer Suit,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retired Employees File $100 Million Lawsuit Against Singer Co.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired employees of Singer Co. have
filed a $100 million class action suit seeking guarantees of their
health and life insurance benefits.
   The civil suit was filed Tuesday in federal court here on behalf
of more than 9,000 Singer retirees against the company and Florida
investor Paul Bilzerian, who acquired Singer in January for $1.06
billion.
   The Singer Retirees Action Committee said Bilzerian prompted the
suit by refusing several attempts by to discuss the benefits.
   ``I think we had to do what we had to do'' because of
Bilzerian's actions, said committee co-chairman Ralph G. Seel of
Anderson, S.C.
   A woman answering the telephone at Bilzerian's office in
Stamford said neither Singer nor Bilzerian had received
notification that the suit was filed. She declined further comment.
   Before Bilzerian acquired the company, Singer's company-financed
benefits program had agreed to pay full health insurance for
retirees and their spouses for life. Life insurance payments for
the retiree in that program only were reduced on retirement.
   The suit contends Bilzerian has ``failed to make adequate
provisions for the continuation of (retirees') health and life
insurance benefits.''
   The action does not apply to pension benefits, which the
committee does not feel are threatened, Seel said.
   Seel said the suit had to be filed while Singer still has enough
assets to guarantee the contested health and life insurance
benefits, which Singer has said cost about $10 million a year.
   Singer completed the sale last month of its two South Carolina
plants to Ryobi Ltd. of Japan.
   Bilzerian has made eight sales of Singer divisions, with
agreements pending on others. He has said he plans to sell all 12
of Singer's divisions.
   Larry Magarik, a New York attorney representing the committee,
said Thursday a retirees' victory would mean that
as-yet-unidentified Singer assets would be attached to ensure that
the benefits are paid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
