<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 2131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ColaFraud     09-09 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cola Fraud,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Coca-Cola Managers Plead Guilty to Syrup Plant Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former managers at a Coca-Cola syrup plant
here agreed to plead guilty to mail fraud and income tax evasion
charges in a $5 million scheme to defraud the soft drink company.
   The defendants, Hillis A. Smith Jr., 51, the plant's former
general manager, and Lewis H. Addison III, 46, the former
administrative manager, entered their pleas before U.S. District
Judge Joseph C. Howard on Thursday.
   Smith will be sentenced Nov. 1 and Addison Nov. 14.
   Under the agreement, the two said they would cooperate in a
continuing investigation of at least six unindicted co-conspirators
and to testify as government witnesses before grand juries and in
criminal trials if asked.
   Prosecutors said they would recommend the two, who were fired by
Coca-Cola in July 1987 because of the phony invoice scheme, be
given prison terms.
   As part of the plea agreement, the government said it would not
prosecute Addison's wife, Emily.
   Smith faces a maximum penalty of 20 years in prison and $1
million in fines while Addison could receive a maximum 15-year term
and $750,000 in fines. The judge also could require restitution.
   A source familiar with the investigation told The (Baltimore)
Sun Coca-Cola already has recovered $750,000 to $1 million.
   No other people have yet been indicted on criminal charges tied
to the alleged schemes, but six of those accused in the Coca-Cola
suit were identified as co-conspirators in a statement of facts
prosecutors read in court Thursday.
   Smith and Addison opened bank accounts under fictitious
corporate names and used post office boxes to receive kickbacks and
payments on phony invoices that they approved and forwarded to
Coca-Cola's main office in Atlanta from early 1980 to mid-1987,
according to the government's statement.
</TEXT>
