<1ST_LINE>r f AM-RefinerySale     09-09 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Refinery Sale,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Pacific Sells California Refinery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Pacific Corp. announced Thursday
that a subsidiary, Union Pacific Resources, had agreed to sell a
Wilmington, Calif., refinery to a British-owned international oil
company for $440 million.
   Union Pacific and Ultramar PLC expect to complete the sale of
the refinery before the end of this year.
   UP Chairman Drew Lewis, who moved the corporation's headquarters
here from New York last month, said Ultramar would offer employment
to all personnel associated with the refinery and its
administrative and marketing operations.
   The refinery produces approximately 100,000 barrels per day of
unleaded gasoline, diesel fuel and other petroleum products sold
primarily to independent marketers in California, Nevada and
Arizona.
   ``We view this as a very positve step,'' said Lewis. ``It gives
us latitude to redeploy some of all of these assets into businesses
which align better with our strategic objectives.''
   Union Pacific Resources, headquartered in Fort Worth, Texas, put
the refinery up for sale last month and also is seeking to sell a
250-mile pipeline that runs from Colton, Calif., to Las Vegas.
   Lewis said the company is continuing to evaluate bids for the
pipeline.
</TEXT>
