<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 0047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Parker-Pentland     09-09 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Parker-Pentland,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentland Industries To Acquire Parker Pen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pentland Industries, the British industrial
conglomerate that holds a 32 percent stake in the Reebok athletic
shoe company, has agreed to acquire Parker Pen in a deal valued at
about $326 million, the Financial Times reported in its Friday
editions.
   The newspaper, Britain's leading business daily, said full
financial details were not disclosed Thursday.
   However, it said Pentland would buy between 85 percent and 90
percent of Parker for about $287 million, with the balance of the
equity being set aside for British executives who led a $100
million management buyout of the former U.S. company in 1986.
   The paper quoted Parker's chief executive, Jacques Margry, as
saying Reebok's marketing strength in the United States and Far
East would greatly help Parker's international development. More
than 60 percent of Parker's operating profits now come from Europe.
   ``You will not see Reebok pens or anything like that but the
strategy of building global brands is the same if you are selling
shoes, pens or whatever,'' Margry said.
   Reebok International Ltd. is based in Canton, Mass.
   The deal also resolves Parker's recent difficulties, which
started when a stock issue planned for last fall was scrapped as
world stock markets crashed in October, the newspaper stated.
   Parker aborted a second stock issuance attempt in June this year
after a dispute over the size of the issue between the company's
financial advisers and its venture capital investors.
   Despite its troubles, Parker has prospered with its present
management. An investor group led by managment acquired the
business in January 1986 from its former owner, Manpower Inc., of
Milwaukee, Wis.
   Parker, formerly of Janesville, Wis., lost more than $43 million
in the three years before the buy-out from Manpower, the temporary
employment concern that last year was itself acquired by Blue Arrow
PLC.
   Last year, Parker posted pre-tax profit $29 million and results
in the first half of 1988 are expected to show further improvements.
</TEXT>
