<DOCNO> AP880909-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 1936EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PolaroidBid 1stLd-Writethru   09-09 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polaroid Bid, 1st Ld-Writethru,0688</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamrock Launches Tender Offer With Sweetened Bid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Polaroid to Shamrock in 4th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy E. Disney's Shamrock Holdings Inc.
went directly to Polaroid Corp. shareholders Friday with a cash bid
that values the company at about $2.6 billion.
   Polaroid's board of directors last month unanimously rejected an
unsolicited offer from the Burbank, Calif.-based Shamrock that
would have paid $40 a share plus 40 percent of the eventual award
in Polaroid's patent infringement lawsuit against Eastman Kodak Co.
   A percentage of that potential settlement was not included in
the new, hostile tender offer of $42 a share, which bypasses the
directors.
   Shamrock said it would add $2 a share to its bid, raising it to
$44 a share, if directors dropped their resistance to the takeover
attempt.
   On Wall Street, Polaroid stock rose $1.87{ a share to $41.75.
   ``They (Shamrock) have to start making their move and they
have,'' said Chuck Ryan, an analyst with the investment firm
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets in New York. ``Now the ball is in
Polaroid's court. You have to watch what Polaroid will do.''
   Ryan suggested Polaroid still had the option of looking for
friendly suitors.
   The company issued a statement touting the potential of its
restructuring plan for improving profitability, but added that the
new offer would be considered by top management.
   Analysts had said a 40 percent share of the Kodak litigation
proceeds could total $400 million to $800 million, but the increase
in the bid to $42 a share from $40 would give shareholders a
definite $124 million in cash without waiting.
   Shamrock said that if its bid succeeded, it would drop
Polaroid's embryonic venture into 35mm film. It also said it would
sell all or much of Polaroid's undeveloped real property, minimize
the excess capacity in the company's manufacturing facilities,
refocus the company's research and development activities on the
company's core businesses and negotiate a ``commercially
reasonable'' settlement of the Kodak litigation.
   The latest offer is contingent on the invalidation of Polaroid's
recent issuance of 9.7 million shares to a new employee stock
ownership plan, a move Polaroid made early in its attempt to block
Shamrock.
   If the stock ownership plan is not invalidated, the offering
price would be reduced to $40 a share, Shamrock said.
   The $42-a-share offer values the company at roughly $2.6
billion, for 62 million shares, while the $40-a-share offer puts a
value on the company of nearly $2.9 billion, because it assumes the
existence of nearly 10 million more shares.
   About 5 million of the shares are already owned by Shamrock.
   Shamrock, which is owned by the family of Roy E. Disney, nephew
of the late animator Walt Disney, has filed a lawsuit seeking to
overturn the ownershi plan. It is scheduled to go to trial in
Delaware Chancery Court on Oct. 19.
   Shamrock also said that if Polaroid's management agreed to
support a merger, the offer would be amended to increase the price
to $44 a share if the new stock issue was invalidated, or $42 a
share if it was not.
   In an effort to fend off hostile bidders, Polaroid has begun a
corporate restructuring, offering early retirement to hundreds of
employees.
   Polaroid spokeswoman Marcia Phillips issued a brief statement
asserting that the company ``has been making excellent progress
with its comprehensive strategic program designed to dramatically
improve profitability and deliver value to all of its
shareholders.''
   The statement added that ``we are proceeding with that plan,
but, of course, our board and management will consider the offer
from Shamrock and base their determination on the best interests of
all our shareholders.''
   Polaroid is incorporated in Delaware.
   The investment banking firm of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.,
along with Wertheim Schroder & Co., is providing financing for
Shamrock's takeover attempt.
   In addition, Shamrock said that commitments for $1 billion of
financing have been received from Wells Fargo Bank and the Bank of
Nova Scotia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
